<L>And thryes how the ladyis gunne crye<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 54.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2956">Ne how that lad was hom-ward Emalye</L>
<L>Ne how Arcyte was brent to asschyn colde<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 57, 58.</NOTE></L>
<L>Ne how that lyche / wake was I-holde<NOTE PLACE="marg">XI. 59-67.</NOTE></L>
<L>Al thilke nyght ne how the grekys pleye</L>
<L N="2960">The wake-pleyis ne kepe I not to seye</L>
<L>Who wrestelyth best nakyd with oille enoynt</L>
<L>Ne who &thorn;at bar hym best in no disioynt</L>
<L>I wele not tellyn ek how &thorn;at &thorn;ey gon</L>
<L N="2964">Hom to athenys whan the pley is don</L>
<L>But schortly to the poynt &thorn;anne wele I wende</L>
<L>And makyn of myn longe tale an ende
<PB REF="00000101.tif" N="85"></L>
<L>Be proces &amp; be lenthe a certeyn &yogh;erys</L>
<L N="2968">Al styntyd is the mournyng &amp; the terys<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 3, '<I>giorni</I>,' instead of <I>years</I>.</NOTE></L>
<L>Of grekys be on general assent</L>
<L>Than semede me &thorn;ere was a parlement</L>
<L>At athenes vp on certeyn poyntys and cas</L>
<L N="2972">A-mong the poyntys spokyn was</L>
<L>To haue with certeyn poyntys alyance</L>
<L>And haue fully of thebans obeissaunce</L>
<L>ffor which this nobil theseus anon</L>
<L N="2976">Let sendyn aftyr gentil palamon<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 4.</NOTE></L>
<L>Vnwist of hym what was the cause &amp; why</L>
<L>But in hese blake clo&thorn;is sorwefully</L>
<L>He come at hese owene comaundement in hye</L>
<L N="2980">To sente Theseus / for emelye</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;ey were set &amp; hust was al the place<MILESTONE N="173a" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 5.</NOTE></L>
<L>And thesyus abedyn hadde a space</L>
<L>Er ony word cam from hese wyse brest</L>
<L N="2984">Hese eynyn sette he &thorn;ere as was hese lest</L>
<L>And with a sad visage he sikede stille</L>
<L>And aftyr &thorn;at ryght &thorn;us he seyde hese wille</L>
<L>The ferste mournere<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? MS.]</NOTE> of the cause aboue<NOTE PLACE="marg">IX. 51.</NOTE></L>
<L N="2988">Whan he ferst made &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> cheyne of loue<NOTE PLACE="marg"><I>mondo</I>, for 'cheine of loue.'</NOTE></L>
<L>Gret was theffect &amp; hy was hese entent</L>
<L>Wel wiste he why &amp; what &thorn;erof he ment<NOTE PLACE="marg">IX. 51.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor with that fayre cheyne of loue he bond</L>
<L N="2992">The fuyr the eyre the watyr &amp; the lond</L>
<L>In certeyn boundys &thorn;at &thorn;ey may not fle</L>
<L>That same prince &amp; &thorn;at same Moeuere quod he<NOTE PLACE="marg">[See IX. 51, 52, and XII. 6.]</NOTE></L>
<L>Hath stablyschid in this wrechede world a doun</L>
<L N="2996">Certeyn dayis &amp; duracioun</L>
<L>To alle &thorn;at is engenderid in &thorn;is place</L>
<L>Ouer the whiche day &thorn;ey may not pace</L>
<L>Alle mowe &thorn;ey &yogh;it &thorn;e dayis wel a-bregge</L>
<L N="3000">&THORN;ere nedyth non autorite to legge</L>
<L>ffor it is preuyd be experyence</L>
<L>But &thorn;at me lyste to clare myn sentence
<PB REF="00000102.tif" N="86"></L>
<L>Thanne may men by &thorn;is ordere wel diserne</L>
<L N="3004">That tylke moeuere stylle &amp; sterne</L>
<L>Wel may men knowe but it be a fol</L>
<L>That euery part dryuyth from hese hol</L>
<L>ffor nature hath takyn hese begynnyng</L>
<L N="3008">Of no party or of a cantel of a &thorn;yng</L>
<L>But of a &thorn;yng &thorn;at parfyt is &amp; stable</L>
<L>Dessendynge so til it be corumpable</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore for hese wise puruyaunce</L>
<L N="3012">He hath so wel be-set hese ordenaunce</L>
<L>That specyfie of &thorn;yngis &amp; progressiounnys</L>
<L>Shul endure be succesciounnys</L>
<L>And not eterne with-outyn ony lye</L>
<L N="3016">This mayst &thorn;ou vndyrstondyn &amp; sen at eye</L>
<L>lo &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ok that hath so long a norichynge<MILESTONE N="173b" UNIT="folio"><NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 7.</NOTE></L>
<L>ffrom the tyme &thorn;at it ferst begynnyth to sprynge</L>
<L>And hat so long a lyf as we may se</L>
<L N="3020">&YOGH;it at the laste wastyd is the tre</L>
<L>Considerith ek how that the harde ston</L>
<L>Vndir oure fet on whiche we trede &amp; gon</L>
<L>&YOGH;it wastith it as it lyth be the weye</L>
<L N="3024">The brode reuyr sumtyme waxeth dreye</L>
<L>The grete tounnys se we wane &amp; wende</L>
<L>Than may I say &thorn;at al &thorn;is thyng hath ende</L>
<L>Of man &amp; woman se we we wel alsoo<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 8.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3028">That nedyth in on of &thorn;ese termys too</L>
<L>This is to seyne in &yogh;outhe or ellys age</L>
<L>He mote be ded the kyng as schal a page</L>
<L>Some in his bed some in the depe se<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 10.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3032">Some in the large feld as men may se</L>
<L>There helpith not al goth that ilke weye</L>
<L>Thanne may I seyn al &thorn;is &thorn;yng mote nedis deye</L>
<L>What makyth &thorn;is but Iupiter &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> kyng</L>
<L N="3036">That is prynce &amp; cause of alle thyng</L>
<L>Conuertynge al vn-to hese propere welle</L>
<L>ffrom wiche it is deryvit soth to telle
<PB REF="00000103.tif" N="87"></L>
<L>And here ageyn no cryatour on. lyue</L>
<L N="3040">Of no degre a-uaylith for to stryue<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 6.</NOTE></L>
<L>Thanne is it wisdom as it &thorn;ynkyt me<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 11.</NOTE></L>
<L>To makyn vertu of necessite</L>
<L>And take it wel that we may not eschewe</L>
<L N="3044">And nameli that to vs alle is dewe</L>
<L>And ho so grochit out he doth folye<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 13.</NOTE></L>
<L>And rebel is to hym &thorn;at al may gye</L>
<L>And serteynly a man hath most honour<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 9, 12.</NOTE></L>
<L N="3048">To deyen in hese excellence &amp; flour</L>
<L>Whan he is sekyr of hese goode name</L>
<L>Thanne hath he don hese frend ne hym no schame</L>
<L>And gladdere owith hese frend to ben of deth</L>
<L N="3052">Whan with honour is &yogh;oldyn vp hese breth</L>
<L>Than whan his name apeyred is for age<MILESTONE N="174a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor al forgetyn is his wasseyllage</L>
<L>Thanne is it best as for a worthi fame</L>
<L N="3056">A man to deye whan he is best of name</L>
<L>The contrarie of al this is wilfulnes<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 13.</NOTE></L>
<L>Why groche we why haue we heuynes<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 14-17.</NOTE></L>
<L>That goode arcite of chyualrye flour</L>
<L N="3060">Departid is with deynte &amp; honour</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;is foule prysoun of &thorn;is lyf</L>
<L>Why grochyn here his cosyn &amp; his wif</L>
<L>Of [his welfare that loueth hem so wel]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sloane MS. 1685]</NOTE></L>
<L N="3064">Can he hem thank nay god wot neuere adel</L>
<L>That bo&thorn;e hese soule &amp; ek hym self offende</L>
<L>And &yogh;it &thorn;ey mowe here lustis not amende</L>
<L>What may I conclude of &thorn;is longe serye</L>
<L N="3068">But aftyr wo I rede vs to be merye<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 19.</NOTE></L>
<L>And thankyn Iupiter of al hese grace</L>
<L>And er &thorn;at we departe from &thorn;is place</L>
<L>I rede we make of sorwys too</L>
<L N="3072">On parfyt Ioye lastynge eueremo</L>
<L>And lokyth now where most sorwe is her inne</L>
<L>There [wil I first bigynne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sloane MS. 1685]</NOTE>
<PB REF="00000104.tif" N="88"></L>
<L>[Suster quod he this is my ful assent<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sloane MS. 1685]</NOTE></L>
<L N="3076">With alle thaues heere of my parlement</L>
<L>That gentyl palamon &yogh;oure owne knyght</L>
<L>That seruyth &yogh;ou with wil herte and myght</L>
<L>As euer hath don sithen &yogh;e first hym knewe</L>
<L N="3080">That &yogh;e shul of &yogh;oure [grace] vpon him rewe</L>
<L>And taken for husbond and for lord</L>
<L>Lene me &yogh;oure hond for this is oure acorde</L>
<L>Lete see now if youre wommanly pitee</L>
<L N="3084">He is a kingis brother sone parde</L>
<L>A[nd thou&yogh; he be a pore bachelere</L>
<L>S[ithen he hath serued &yogh;ou so many a &yogh;ere</L>
<L>A[nd had for &yogh;ou so gret aduersite</L>
<L N="3088">It [most be considered leuyth me]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sloane <I>extr. ends</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor gentyl mercy owith to passyn ryght<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cambridge Gg. iv. 27</NOTE><MILESTONE N="174b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Than seyde he &thorn;us to palamoun ful rygh[t]</L>
<L>I trowe &thorn;ere nedyth lytil sarmonynge</L>
<L N="3092">To make &yogh;ow assente to the thynge</L>
<L>Come ner &amp; tak &yogh;oure lady bi the hond</L>
<L>By-twe&thorn;yn hem was mad anon the bond<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 69.</NOTE></L>
<L>That hyghte matrymonye or mariage</L>
<L N="3096">By al the cuntre &amp; the barounnage</L>
<L>And &thorn;us with al blys &amp; melody<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 72.</NOTE></L>
<L>Hath Palamoun I-wedded emely</L>
<L>And god &thorn;at al &thorn;is wyde word hath wrought</L>
<L N="3100">Synde hym his loue &thorn;at hath it dere abought</L>
<L>ffor now is Palamoun in alle wele<NOTE PLACE="marg">XII. 83.</NOTE></L>
<L>leuynge in blysse in richesse &amp; in hele</L>
<L>And Emelye hym louyth so tenderely</L>
<L N="3104">And he here seruyth so gentylly</L>
<L>That neuere was &thorn;ere no word hem be-twen</L>
<L>Of Ielousye or ony o&thorn;er teene<NOTE PLACE="marg">[teene: <I>later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>Thus endyth Palamoun &amp; Emelye</L>
<L N="3108">And god saue al this ffayre cumpaynye.<NOTE PLACE="end">[rest of leaf nearly all cut out.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000105.tif" N="89">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>SO whan &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> knyght hath &thorn;us hese tale told<MILESTONE N="175a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>In al &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> route nas &thorn;ere &yogh;yng ne old</L>
<L>That he ne seyde it nas a noble story</L>
<L N="3112">And worthy for to drawe to memory</L>
<L>And nameli &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> gentilis euerychon</L>
<L>Our ost lough and swor so mote I gon</L>
<L>Thys goth aryght onbokeled is the male</L>
<L N="3116">Let sen now who schal telle a no&thorn;er tale</L>
<L>ffor trewely the game is wel begunne</L>
<L>Now tellyth &yogh;e sere monk &yogh;yf &thorn;at &yogh;e cunne</L>
<L>Sumwhat to quite with &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> knyghtis tale</L>
<L N="3120">The mellere that dronke was al pale</L>
<L>So that a-nethe vp on his hors he sat</L>
<L>He nulde a-vale neythyr hod ne hat</L>
<L>Ne abyde no man for hese curteysye</L>
<L N="3124">But in pilat voys he gan to crye</L>
<L>And swor by armys &amp; by blod &amp; bonys</L>
<L>I can a noble tale for thenonys</L>
<L>With whiche he wele now quyte &thorn;e kny&yogh;tis tale</L>
<L N="3128">Oure ost saw &thorn;at he was dronke of ale</L>
<L>And seyde a-byd Robyn myn leue brothyr</L>
<L>Sum betere man schal telle vs fyrst a nothyr</L>
<L>Onbyd &amp; lat vs werke thryftyly</L>
<L N="3132">By goddys soule / quod he &thorn;at wele nat I</L>
<L>ffor I wele speke or ellys gon myn wey</L>
<L>Oure ost answerde telle on a delewey</L>
<L>Thow art a fol thy wit is ouercome</L>
<L N="3136">Now herkenygh quod the mellere alle &amp; some</L>
<L>But fyrst I make a protestacyoun</L>
<L>That I am dronke I knowe it be myn soun</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore &yogh;if I mys speke or seye</L>
<L N="3140">Wite it the ale of Southwerk I preye
<PB REF="00000106.tif" N="90"></L>
<L>ffor I wele telle a legende &amp; a lyf</L>
<L>Bothe of a carpenter &amp; hese wyf</L>
<L>How that a clerk hath set the wryghtis cappe</L>
<L N="3144">The reue answerde &amp; seyde stynt &thorn;yn clappe</L>
<L>let be &thorn;yn lewede dronke harlotrye<MILESTONE N="175b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>It is a synne &amp; ek a gret folye</L>
<L>To apeyre ony man or hym diffame</L>
<L N="3148">And ek to bryngyn whyuys in swych fame</L>
<L>&thorn;ou mayst I-now of o&thorn;ere thyngis sayn</L>
<L>This dronkyn mellere spak ful sone ageyn</L>
<L>And seyde leue brothyr Osewold</L>
<L N="3152">Ho hath no wif he is no coukewold</L>
<L>But I seye not &thorn;erfore &thorn;at &thorn;ou art on</L>
<L>There ben ful goode wivis manyon</L>
<L>And euer a thousent goode a-&yogh;ens on badde</L>
<L N="3156">That knowyst &thorn;ou wel &thorn;yn self / but &yogh;if &thorn;ou madde</L>
<L>Why art &thorn;ou angry with myn tale now</L>
<L>I haue a wif also as wel as &thorn;ou</L>
<L>&YOGH;it nolde I not for the oxsyn in myn plow</L>
<L N="3160">Takyn vp on me more &thorn;an I-now</L>
<L>As demyn in myn self &thorn;at &thorn;ou were on</L>
<L>I wele be-leue wel &thorn;at I ne am non</L>
<L>An husbonde schal not ben inquysityf</L>
<L N="3164">Of goddis priuyte nor of hese wyf</L>
<L>So he may fyndyn godis foysounn there</L>
<L>Of the remenaunt nedyth not tenquyre</L>
<L>What schalde I seyn But this mellere</L>
<L N="3168">He wolde hese wordys for no man forbere</L>
<L>But tolde hese cherlych tale in hese manere</L>
<L>Me thynkyth I schal reherse it here</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore euery gentyl wygh I preye</L>
<L N="3172">ffor goddys loue demyth not &thorn;at I seye</L>
<L>Of euyl entent but for I mot reherse</L>
<L>Here talys al be &thorn;ey betere or werse</L>
<L>Or ellys fallyn sum of myn matere</L>
<L N="3176">And &thorn;erfore who so leste it not here
<PB REF="00000107.tif" N="91"></L>
<L>Turne ouer the lef &amp; ches a no&thorn;er tale</L>
<L>for he schal fynde I-nowe grete &amp; smale</L>
<L>Of storyal thyng &thorn;at touchith gentillesse</L>
<L N="3180">An ek Morallite and holynesse</L>
<L>Blamyth not me &yogh;if &yogh;e chesyn amys<MILESTONE N="176a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>The mellere is a cherl &yogh;e knowe wel this</L>
<L>So was the reue &amp; o&thorn;ere manye mo</L>
<L N="3184">And harlotrye &thorn;ey tolde bothe to</L>
<L>Avyseth &yogh;ow put me out of blame</L>
<L>And ek men schal not makyn ernest of game</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>here endith the prologe/<NOTE PLACE="end">[No gap in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000108.tif" N="92">
<HEAD>&amp; here begynnyth the tale.</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHilhom &thorn;ere was dwellinge in Oxenforde</L>
<L N="3188">A ryche gnoff &thorn;at gestis helde to borde</L>
<L>And of his craft a carpenter</L>
<L>With hym &thorn;ere was dwellynge a pore scoler</L>
<L>Hadde lernede art but of hese fantasye</L>
<L N="3192">Was turned for to lernyn astronomye</L>
<L>And coude a certyn of conclusiounys</L>
<L>To demyn by interrogacyounnys</L>
<L>&YOGH;if that men axsed hym in certeyn hourys</L>
<L N="3196">Whan men schulde haue droughte or elle schourys</L>
<L>Or &yogh;if men axsede hym what schulde be-falle</L>
<L>Of euery thyng I may not rekene hem alle</L>
<L>This clerk was clepid hende nycholas</L>
<L N="3200">Of derne loue he coude &amp; of solas</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto he was sly &amp; ful preue</L>
<L>And lyk a mayde meke for to se</L>
<L>A chambre hadde he in that ostelrye</L>
<L N="3204">Alone with-outyn ony compaygnye</L>
<L>fful fetously I-dygh with erbis sote</L>
<L>And he hym self as swete as is the rote</L>
<L>Of licorys or ony Cetewale</L>
<L N="3208">Hese almageste &amp; bokys grete &amp; smale</L>
<L>Hese augrym stonys lynge fayre apart</L>
<L>Hese astellabre longynge for hese art</L>
<L>On scheluys couchede at hese bedys hed</L>
<L N="3212">Hese presse I-couered with a faldynge red</L>
<L>And al aboue &thorn;ere lay a gay sautrye</L>
<L>On whiche he made on nyghtis melodye</L>
<L>So swetely &thorn;at al the chambere rong<MILESTONE N="176b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3216">And Angelus ad uirginem he song</L>
<L>And aftyr &thorn;at he song the kyngis note</L>
<L>fful oftyn blyssede was hese mery throte
<PB REF="00000109.tif" N="93"></L>
<L>And &thorn;us this swete clerk hese tyme he spente</L>
<L N="3220">Aftyr hese frendys fyndynge &amp; hese rente</L>
<L>This carpenter hadde weddid newe a wyf</L>
<L>Whiche &thorn;at he louede more &thorn;an hese lyf</L>
<L>Of eightene &yogh;er sche was of age</L>
<L N="3224">Ielous he was &amp; held here narwe in cage</L>
<L>ffor sche was wilde &amp; &yogh;yng &amp; he was old</L>
<L>And demede hym self / ben lyk a coukewold</L>
<L>He knew not catoun for hese wit was rude</L>
<L N="3228">That bad men schulde wedde here symylitude</L>
<L>Men schulde wedde aftyr here estat</L>
<L>ffor &yogh;oughte &amp; elde ben oftyn at debat</L>
<L>But sythyn &thorn;at he was fallyn in the snare</L>
<L N="3232">He muste endure as o&thorn;ere folk hese care</L>
<L>ffayr was &thorn;is &yogh;onge wif &amp; &thorn;erwith al</L>
<L>As ony wesele here body gent &amp; smal</L>
<L>A seynt sche werede &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> seynt al of sylk</L>
<L N="3236">A barme cloth as whit as ony mylk</L>
<L>Vp on here lendis ful of manye a gore</L>
<L>Whit was here smok I-brouded al be-fore</L>
<L>And ek be-hyndyn on here coller aboute</L>
<L N="3240">Of col blak silk with-inne &amp; ek with-oute</L>
<L>The tapes of here white voluper</L>
<L>Were of the same sute of here coller</L>
<L>Hyre filet brod of silk I-set ful hye</L>
<L N="3244">And sekyrly sche hadde a lycorous eye</L>
<L>fful smale I-pullede were hese browis to</L>
<L>And &thorn;<SUP>o</SUP> were bent &amp; blake as is a slo</L>
<L>Sche was more blysful on to se</L>
<L N="3248">Than is the newe pere Ionete tre</L>
<L>And softere than is the wolle of a wedyr</L>
<L>And by here gerdil heng a purs of ledyr</L>
<L>Tassellid with sylk &amp; perlit with latoun<MILESTONE N="177a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3252">In al this world to sekyn vp &amp; doun</L>
<L>There is no man so wys that coude thynche</L>
<L>So gay a popelote or swych a wenche
<PB REF="00000110.tif" N="94"></L>
<L>fful bryght was the schynynge of here hewe</L>
<L N="3256">Than in &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tour/ the noble forgit newe</L>
<L>But of here song it was as loude &amp; &yogh;erne</L>
<L>As ony swalwe syttynge on a berne</L>
<L>And &thorn;erto sche coude skippe &amp; make game</L>
<L N="3260">As ony kede or kalf folwende hese dame</L>
