<L>That we ben enteryd in to schepys bord</L>
<L>That non of vs ne speke not a word</L>
<L>Ne clepe ne crye but ben in hese preyere</L>
<L N="3588">ffor it is goddys owene heste dere</L>
<L>Thyn wyf &amp; &thorn;ou motyn hangyn fer a twen</L>
<L>ffor that be-twixe &yogh;ow schal ben no syn</L>
<L>No more in lokynge &thorn;an &thorn;ere schal in dede</L>
<L N="3592">This ordenaunce is seyd go god &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> spede</L>
<L>To morwe at nyght whan we ben alle aslepe</L>
<L>In to oure knedynge tulbis we schul crepe</L>
<L>And sittynge &thorn;ere abydynge goddys grace</L>
<L N="3596">Go now &thorn;yn way I ne haue no lengere space</L>
<L>To make of thys no lengere sarmounnyng</L>
<L>Men seyth &thorn;us / synd &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> wyse &amp; sey no &thorn;yng</L>
<L>Thow art so wys it nedyth &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> not teche</L>
<L N="3600">Go saue oure lyf &amp; that I &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> beseche</L>
<L>This sely carpenter goth forth hese way</L>
<L>fful ofte he seyde allas &amp; welle away</L>
<L>And to hese wif he tolde hese priuyte</L>
<L N="3604">And sche was war &amp; knew it bet &thorn;an he</L>
<L>What al this queynte cast was for to say</L>
<L>But neuertheles sche ferde as sche wolde day</L>
<L>And seyde allas go forth &thorn;yn waye a-non</L>
<L N="3608">Help vs to skape / er we ben dede eche on</L>
<L>I am thyn verray trewe weddede wyf</L>
<L>Go dere spouse &amp; help to saue oure lyf</L>
<L>Lo which a gret thyng is affeccyoun<MILESTONE N="182a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3612">Men may deye thour Imagynacyoun</L>
<L>So depe may impressioun be take</L>
<L>This sely Carpenter begynnyth to quake
<PB REF="00000120.tif" N="104"></L>
<L>Hym thynkyth verayly &thorn;at he may se</L>
<L N="3616">Noyous flod come walwynge as the se</L>
<L>To drenchyn alysoun hese hony dere</L>
<L>He wepyth waylyth makyth sory chere</L>
<L>He sykyth with manye a sory swough</L>
<L N="3620">And goth &amp; getyth hym a knedyng trough</L>
<L>And aftyr a tubbe &amp; a kemelyn</L>
<L>And pryuyly he sente hem to hese in</L>
<L>And hyng hem in the rof in priuyte</L>
<L N="3624">With his owene hand he made ladderys thre</L>
<L>To klymbyn bi &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> roungis &amp; the stalkys</L>
<L>On to the tubbe hangynge in the balkis</L>
<L>And hem vitaylede bothe trow &amp; tubbe</L>
<L N="3628">With bred &amp; chese with good alle in a tubbe</L>
<L>Suffysynge rygh I-now as for a day</L>
<L>But er he hadde mad al thys aray</L>
<L>He sente hese knaue &amp; ek hese wenche also</L>
<L N="3632">Vp on hese nedis to lundene for to go</L>
<L>And on the moneday whan it drow to nyght</L>
<L>He schette hese dore with-outyn candele lygh</L>
<L>And dressede alle thynge as it schulde be</L>
<L N="3636">And schortly vp they clumbe alle thre</L>
<L>They setyn stylle wel a furlong wey</L>
<L>Now pater noster clum seyde Nicholay</L>
<L>And clum quod Ion &amp; clum quod Alysoun</L>
<L N="3640">This carpentyr seyde hese deuocyoun</L>
<L>And stylle he sit &amp; biddyth hese preyere</L>
<L>Awaytynge on the reyn &yogh;if he it here</L>
<L>The dede slep for verray besynesse</L>
<L N="3644">ffel on this Carpentyr rygh as I gesse</L>
<L>A-boute corfeu tyme or lyte more</L>
<L>ffor trauayl<NOTE PLACE="marg">[l: <I>later</I>]</NOTE> of hese gost he groynede sore</L>
<L>And efft he routyth for hese hed mys lay<MILESTONE N="182b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3648">Doun on the laddere stalkyth Nicholay</L>
<L>And Alysoun ful softe a doun sche spedde</L>
<L>With-outyn wordys mo &thorn;ey gon to bedde
<PB REF="00000121.tif" N="105"></L>
<L>There as the carpentyr is wone to lye</L>
<L N="3652">There was the reuel &amp; the melodye</L>
<L>And &thorn;us lyth alysoun &amp; Nycholas</L>
<L>In besynesse of merthe &amp; of solas</L>
<L>Tyl &thorn;at the belle of laudis gan to rynge</L>
<L N="3656">And frerys in the schaunsel gunne synge</L>
<L>Thys parich clerk this Amerouse Absalon</L>
<L>That is for loue alwey so wo begon</L>
<L>Vp on the moneday was at oseneye</L>
<L N="3660">With cumpanye hym to disporte &amp; pleye</L>
<L>And axede vp on cas a cloysterer</L>
<L>fful priuyly aftyr Ion the carpenter</L>
<L>And he drow hym a part out of the cherche</L>
<L N="3664">And seyde I saw here not werche</L>
<L>Syn satyrday I trowe that he be went</L>
<L>ffor tymbyr &thorn;ere oure abbot hath hym sent</L>
<L>ffor he is wont for tymbyr for to go</L>
<L N="3668">And dwellyn at the graunge a day or too</L>
<L>Or ell he is at hese hous serteyn</L>
<L>Where that he be I can not sothly seyn</L>
<L>This absalon ful Ioly was &amp; lyght</L>
<L N="3672">And thoughte now is tyme to wakyn al nygh</L>
<L>ffor sekyrly I say hym not sterynge</L>
<L>A-boutyn hese dore tyl day be-gan to sprynge</L>
<L>So mot I the I schal at cokkys crowe</L>
<L N="3676">fful priuyly knocke at hese wyndowe</L>
<L>That stant ful lowe vndyr hese bourys wal</L>
<L>To alysoun now wele I tellyn al</L>
<L>Myn loue longynge for &yogh;it I schal not mysse</L>
<L N="3680">That at the leste weye I schal here kysse</L>
<L>Sum maner confort schal I haue parfay</L>
<L>Myn mouth hath &yogh;echid al &thorn;is longe day</L>
<L>That is a sygne of kyssynge at the leste<MILESTONE N="183a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3684">Al nyght me mette I was at a feste</L>
<L>Therfore I wele go slepe an oure or tweye</L>
<L>And al the nyght &thorn;anne wele I wake &amp; pleye
<PB REF="00000122.tif" N="106"></L>
<L>Whan that the ferste Cok hath crowe a-non</L>
<L N="3688">Vp rist this Ioly louere this absalon</L>
<L>And hym araye&thorn; gay at poyn deuyse</L>
<L>But fyrst he schewith greyn &amp; licorys</L>
<L>To smelle sote er he hadde kemb his her</L>
<L N="3692">Vndyr hese tunge a trewe loue he ber</L>
<L>ffor therby wende he to be gracious</L>
<L>He romyth to the carpenterys hous</L>
<L>And stille he stant vndyr the schot wyndowe</L>
<L N="3696">Vn to hese brest it raught it was so lowe</L>
<L>And softe he coude with a semy soun</L>
<L>What do &yogh;e hony komb &yogh;e swete alysoun</L>
<L>Myn fayre bryd myn swete synamome</L>
<L N="3700">Awakyth leman myn &amp; spekyth to me</L>
<L>Wol lytil thynkyn &yogh;e vp on myn wo</L>
<L>That for &yogh;oure loue I swete &thorn;ere I go</L>
<L>No wondyr ist &thorn;ow I swalte &amp; swete</L>
<L N="3704">I morne as doth a lamb aftyr &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tete</L>
<L>I-wis leman I haue so meche loue longyng</L>
<L>That lik a turtele I trowe is myn mornyng</L>
<L>I may not ete no more &thorn;an a mayde</L>
<L N="3708">Go from the wyndowe Iakke fol sche sayde</L>
<L>As helpe me god it wele not be cumpame</L>
<L>I loue a-nothir &amp; ell I were to blame</L>
<L>Wel bet &thorn;an &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> be Ihesu Absalon</L>
<L N="3712">Go forth &thorn;yn way or I wele caste a ston</L>
<L>And let me slepe a twenty dele wey</L>
<L>Allas quod absalon &amp; welleawey</L>
<L>That trewe loue was euere so euele be-set</L>
<L N="3716">Than kys me syn it may be no bet</L>
<L>ffor Ihesus<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>MS</I> Ihc]</NOTE> loue &amp; for the loue of me</L>
<L>Wilt &thorn;ou &thorn;anne go thyn wey therewith quod sche</L>
<L>&YOGH;a certis lemman quod &thorn;is absalon<MILESTONE N="183b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3720">Thanne mak &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> redi quod sche I come anon</L>
<L>. . . . .</L>
<L>. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>This Absalon sette hym doun on hese kneis
<PB REF="00000123.tif" N="107"></L>
<L N="3724">And seyde I am a lord at alle degreis</L>
<L>ffor aftyr this I hope &thorn;ere comyth more</L>
<L>leman thyn grace &amp; swete bryd &thorn;yn ore</L>
<L>The wyndowe sche ondoth &amp; that in haste</L>
<L N="3728">Haue don quod sche come of &amp; sped &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> faste</L>
<L>Lest that thyn neyhebouris &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> aspye</L>
<L>This absalon gan wype his mouth ful drye</L>
<L>Derk was the nyght as pouche or as the cole</L>
<L N="3732">And out at the wyndowe sche putte here ars hole</L>
<L>And absalon fel ney&thorn;er bet no&thorn;er wers</L>
<L>But with hese mouth he kyste here nakede ars</L>
<L>fful sauourly er he were war of this</L>
<L N="3736">A bakke he styrte &amp; thouthe it was a mys</L>
<L>ffor wel he wiste a woman hadde no berd</L>
<L>He felte a thyng al row &amp; long I-heryd</L>
<L>And seyde fy allas what haue I do</L>
<L N="3740">Te he quod sche &amp; claptte here wyndowe to</L>
<L>And absalon goth forth a sory pas</L>
<L>A berd a berd quod hynde Nicholas</L>
<L>Bi goddis corpus this goth fayre &amp; wel</L>
<L N="3744">This sely absalon herde euerydel</L>
<L>And on his lippe he gan for angyr bite</L>
<L>And to hym self he seyde I schal &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> quyte</L>
<L>Who rubbyth now ho frotyth now hese lippis</L>
<L>With dust with sond with straw with cloth with schippis</L>
<L>But absolon &thorn;at seyth ful ofte allas</L>
<L>Myn soule be-take I onto saternas</L>
<L>But me were betere &thorn;an al this toun quod he</L>
<L N="3752">Of &thorn;is dispyt a-wrokyn for to be</L>
<L>Allas quod he allas why ne hadde I bleynt</L>
<L>Hese hote loue was cold &amp; al I-queynt</L>
<L>ffor from that tyme that he hadde kyst his ers</L>
<L N="3756">Of paramour he sette not a kres</L>
<L>ffor he was heled of hese maladye<MILESTONE N="184a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>fful ofte paramouris he gan defye</L>
<L>And wepte as doth a chyld &thorn;at is I-bete</L>
<L N="3760">A softe pas he wente ouer the strete
<PB REF="00000124.tif" N="108"></L>
<L>Vn tyl a smyth men clepedyn daun Ieruys</L>
<L>That in hese forge he smethede plow harneys</L>
<L>He scharpith schar &amp; cultyr besyly</L>
<L N="3764">This absalon knokyth al besyly</L>
<L>And seyde ondo Geruays &amp; &thorn;at a-non</L>
<L>What ho art &thorn;ou it am I Absalon</L>
<L>What Absalon what crystis swete tre</L>
<L N="3768">Whi ryse &yogh;e so rathe ey benedicyte</L>
<L>What eylyth &yogh;ow sum gay gerl god it wot</L>
<L>Hath brou&yogh;t &yogh;ow &thorn;us vp on the merytot</L>
<L>This Absolon ne roughte not a bene</L>
<L N="3772">Be seynte note &yogh;e wete wel what I mene</L>
<L>Of al this pley no word he ne spak</L>
<L>He hadde more tow on hese rak</L>
<L>Whan geruays knew &amp; seyde fren so dere</L>
<L N="3776">That hote cultyr in the chemene here</L>
<L>As lene it me I haue &thorn;erwith to done</L>
<L>I wele bryngyn it &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> a-geyn ful sone</L>
<L>Gerueys answerede sertis were it gold</L>
<L N="3780">Or in a poke nobellys al ontold</L>
<L>Thu schuldyst haue as I am trewe smyth</L>
<L>Ey cristis foo what wele &yogh;e do &thorn;erwith</L>
<L>Ther-of quod Alsalon be as be may</L>
<L N="3784">I schal wel telle it &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> to morwe day</L>
<L>And caughte &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> cultyr by the colde stele</L>
<L>fful softe out at &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> dore hym gan stele</L>
<L>And wente vnto &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> carpenterys wal</L>
<L N="3788">He knokyth fyrst &amp; kallyth<NOTE PLACE="marg">[corr.]</NOTE> &thorn;erwithal</L>
<L>Vp on &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> wyndowe rygh as he dede er</L>
<L>This alysoun answerde ho is ther</L>
<L>That knokyst so I warent the a thef</L>
<L N="3792">Why nay quod he god wot myn swete lef</L>
<L>I am thyn absalon myn derelyng<MILESTONE N="184b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of gold quod he I haue &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> brought a ryng</L>
<L>Myn modyr &yogh;af it me so god me saue</L>
<L N="3796">fful fyn it is &amp; &thorn;erto wel I-graue
<PB REF="00000125.tif" N="109"></L>
<L>This wele I &yogh;euen &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> &yogh;if I &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> kysse</L>
<L>This Nicholas was resyn for to pysse</L>
<L>And thoute he wolde a-mendyn al &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> Iape</L>
<L N="3800">He schulde kysse hese ars er &thorn;an he spake</L>
<L>And vp the wyndowe dede he hastyly</L>
<L>And out hese ars he puttyth pryuyly</L>
<L>Ouer the buttok / to &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> haunche bon</L>
<L N="3804">And &thorn;erwith spak this absolon</L>
<L>Spek swete brid I not where &thorn;ou art</L>
<L>This Nicholas a-non let flye a fart</L>
<L>As gret as it hadde ben a thondyr dent</L>
<L N="3808">And with &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> strok he was almost I-blent</L>
<L>And he was redy with hese yryn hot</L>
<L>And Nicholas a mydde &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ars he smot</L>
<L>Off goth the skyn<NOTE PLACE="marg">[corrected]</NOTE> / an hande brede aboute</L>
<L N="3812">The hote cultyr / brende so hese toute</L>
<L>And for the smert he wende for to deye</L>
<L>As he were wod / for wo he gan to crye</L>
<L>Help watyr watyr / help for godys herte</L>
<L N="3816">This carpenter / out of hese slombir sterte</L>
<L>And herde on cryen / watyr as he were wod</L>
<L>And thoughte allas now comyth Newel flod<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<SUP>2</SUP>? Nowel]</NOTE></L>
<L>He sit hym vp with/oute wordys mo</L>
<L N="3820">And with hese ax / he smette the corde on to</L>
<L>A doun he<NOTE PLACE="marg">[corrected]</NOTE> fel.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[corrected]</NOTE> he fond no<NOTE PLACE="marg">[corrected]</NOTE> thyng<NOTE PLACE="marg">[corrected]</NOTE> to selle</L>
<L>Ney&thorn;er bred ne ale / Ne no thyng elle</L>
<L>Vp on the flor / &amp; &thorn;ere aswounne he lay</L>
<L N="3824">Vp styrte here Alysoun &amp; nycholay</L>
<L>And cryedyn out / harrow in the strete</L>
<L>The neygheborys bo&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> smale &amp; grete</L>
<L>In ronne for to gauryn on &thorn;is man.</L>
<L>That &yogh;it a swounne he lay bo&thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> pale &amp; wan.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Cambridge <I>stops till l.</I> 3891.]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor with that fal he brusten hath his arme<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS. 1685 folio" N="43a"></L>
<L>But stonden he must vnto his owne harme</L>
<L>ffor whanne he spak he was anoon bore doun</L>
<L N="3832">With hynde Nicholas and Alisoun
<PB REF="00000126.tif" N="110"></L>
<L>Thei tolde euery man that he was wood</L>
<L>He was a-gast so of the Nowels flood</L>
<L>Thurgh fantasie that of his vanyte</L>
<L N="3836">He hadde bought hym kneding tubbes three</L>
<L>And hadde hem hanged in the roof aboue</L>
<L>And that he praiede hem for goddis loue</L>
<L>To sitten in the roof par companye</L>
<L N="3840">The folk gan laughwen at his fantasie</L>
<L>And to the roof thei kiken and thei gape</L>
<L>And turned al his harm vnto a Iape</L>
<L>ffor what this carpentere answerde</L>
<L N="3844">It was for nought no man his resoun herde</L>
<L>With othes gret he was sworne adoun</L>
<L>That he was holden wood in al that toun</L>
<L>ffor euery clerk anoon right helde with other</L>
<L N="3848">Thei seide the man is wood my leue brother</L>
<L>And euery wight gan laughwen at his stryf</L>
<L>Thus swyued was the carpenters wyf</L>
<L>ffor al his kepyng and his Ialousie<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS. 1685 folio" N="43b"></L>
<L N="3852">And Absolon hath kist hir nethir ye</L>
<L>And Nicholas is scaldid in his toute</L>
<L>This tale is don and god saue al the route</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Explicit fabula molendinarij.<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>Of leaf</I> 85, <I>the Cambridge MS has only</I> cas <I>l.</I> 3855, pleye, <I>l.</I> 3858, <I>and</I> greue <I>l.</I> 3859.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000127.tif" N="111">
<HEAD>&para; Heere bigynneth the prolog of the Reues Tale.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sloane MS 1685]</NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHanne folk han laughwen at this nyce cas</L>
<L N="3856">Of Absolon and hynde Nicholas</L>
<L>Dyuerse folk dyuersely they seide</L>
<L>But for the more part thei lough and pleyde</L>
<L>Ne at this tale I saw no man him greue</L>
<L N="3860">But it were oonly Oswold the Reue</L>
<L>By cause he was of Carpenteres craft</L>
<L>A litel ire is in his herte laft</L>
<L>He gan to grucche and blamede it a lite</L>
<L N="3864">So the yk quod he ful wel kouthe I &yogh;ou quite</L>
<L>With blering of a proude mellers ye</L>
<L>If that me list to speke of rybaudye</L>
<L>But yk am old me list not pleye for age</L>
<L N="3868">Gras tyme is don my foddere is forage</L>
<L>This white top writeth myn olde &yogh;eres</L>
<L>Myn herte is al so mouled as myn heres</L>
<L>But if I fare as doth an openers</L>
<L N="3872">That ilk fruyt is euere lenger the wers</L>
<L>Til it be roten in mullok or in stree</L>
<L>We olde men I drede so fare we</L>
<L>Til we be roten can we nought be ripe</L>
<L N="3876">We hoppen alweye while the world wil pipe</L>
<L>ffor in oure wille ther stiketh euere a naile</L>
<L>To haue an hoor her / and a grene taile</L>
<L>As hath a leek . for though oure might be gon</L>
<L N="3880">Oure wille desireth folye euere in oon</L>
<L>ffor whanne we may nought don than wil we speke</L>
<L>&YOGH;it in oure asshen old is fire reke</L>
<L>ffoure gledes haue we whiche I shal diuise</L>
<L N="3884">Auauntyng . liyng . Angre . Coueitise</L>
<L>These foure sparkles longith vnto elde<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS. 1685 folio" N="40a"></L>
<L>Oure olde lymes mowe wel be vnwelde
<PB REF="00000128.tif" N="112"></L>
<L>But wille ne shal not failen that is soth<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sloane MS 1685]</NOTE></L>
<L N="3888">And &yogh;it haue I alwey a coltes toth</L>
<L>As many a &yogh;ere as it is passed henne</L>
<L>Sith that my tappe of lyf bigan to renne<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sloane extract ends.]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor sekyrly whan I was boryn anon<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cambr. MS. <I>Gg</I> 4. 27</NOTE><MILESTONE N="186a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="3892">Deth drow &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tappe of lyf &amp; let it gon</L>
<L>And euere sithe hath so &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tappe Ironne</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at almost al emty is &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tunne</L>
<L>The strem of lyf now droppith on &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> chymbe</L>
<L N="3896">The sely tunge may wel rynge &amp; chymbe</L>
<L>Of wrechedenesse &thorn;at passede is ful &yogh;ore</L>
<L>With olde folk saue dotage is no more</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> ost hadde herd this sarmounnyng</L>
<L N="3900">He gan to spek as lordly as a kyng</L>
<L>He seyde what amountyth al &thorn;is wit</L>
<L>What schul we speke al day of holy writ</L>
<L>The deuyl made a reue for to preche</L>
<L N="3904">And of a soutere schipman or a leche</L>
<L>Sey forth thyn tale &amp; tarye not &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> tyme</L>
<L>Lo Depeforthe &amp; it is half weye pryme</L>
<L>Lo Grenewych &thorn;ere manye a schrewe is inne</L>
<L N="3908">It were hey tyme &thorn;yn tale to begynne</L>
<L>Now serys quod this Osowold the reue</L>
<L>I preye &yogh;ow alle &thorn;at &yogh;e nat &yogh;ow greue</L>
<L>Thow I answere &amp; sumdel sette hese howe</L>
<L N="3912">ffor lefful it is &thorn;at forse / forse of schowe</L>
<L>This dronkene mellere hath I-told vs here</L>
<L>How &thorn;at begiled was a carpentere</L>
<L>Parauenture in scorn for I am on</L>
<L N="3916">And by &yogh;oure leue I schal &yogh;ow quyte a-non</L>
<L>Ryght in hese cherlis termys wele I speke</L>
<L>I preye to god his nelke mote breke</L>
<L>He can wel in myn eye sen a stalke</L>
<L N="3920">But in hese owene he can not sen a balke
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale"><PB REF="00000129.tif" N="113">
<HEAD>Here begynnyth the<NOTE PLACE="inter">[head of painting of the Reeve]</NOTE> Reue his tale</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>AT Trompyngtoun not fer fram cantabregge<MILESTONE N="186b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&THORN;ere goth a brok &amp; ouer &thorn;at a bregge</L>
<L>Vp on &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> which brok &thorn;er stant a melle</L>
<L N="3924">And this is veray soth &thorn;at I &yogh;ou telle</L>
<L>A mellere was &thorn;er dwellynge many a day</L>
<L>As ony pekok he was proud &amp; gay</L>
<L>Pype he coude and fyssche and netys beete</L>
<L N="3928">And turne cuppis &amp; wel wrestele &amp; schete</L>
<L>Ay by hese belte he bar a long panade</L>
<L>And of a swerd ful trenchaunt was the blade</L>
<L>A Ioly poppere bar he in hese pouche</L>
<L N="3932">Ther was no man for peryl durste hym touche</L>
<L>A sheffeld Thwytel bar he in hese hose</L>
<L>Round was hese face &amp; kammede was hese nose</L>
<L>As pelyd as an ape was hese skolle</L>
<L N="3936">He was a markat betere at &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> fulle</L>
<L>There durste no wygh hand vp on hym leye<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ye <I>corrected</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>That he ne swor &thorn;at he schulde anon a-beye<NOTE PLACE="marg">[ye <I>corrected</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>A thef he was for sothe of corn &amp; mele</L>
<L N="3940">And &thorn;at a sly &amp; vsaunt for to stele</L>
<L>And his name was hotyn deynous symkyn</L>
<L>A wif he hadde comyn of noble kyn</L>
<L>The persoun of the toun here fadyr was</L>
<L N="3944">With here he &yogh;af ful many a peny of bras</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at Symkyn schulde in hese blod alye</L>
<L>Sche was fostered in a nunnerye</L>
<L>ffor Symkyn wolde no wyf as he seyde</L>
<L N="3948">But sche were wel Inoryschid &amp; a mayde</L>
<L>To sauyn hese estat of &yogh;emanrye</L>
<L>And sche was proud &amp; pert as is a pye</L>
<L>A ful fayr syghte was it on hem to</L>
<L N="3952">On holye dayis be-forn here wolde he ge
<PB REF="00000130.tif" N="114"></L>
<L>With hese typet boundyn a-boutyn hese hed</L>
<L>And sche come aftyr in a gite of red</L>
<L>And symkyn hadde hosyn of the same</L>
<L N="3956">Ther durste no wygh clepyn here but dame</L>
<L>Was non hardy &thorn;at wente be &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> weye<MILESTONE N="187a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That durste with here rage or onys pleye</L>
<L>But &yogh;if he wolde be slayn of symkyn</L>
<L N="3960">With panade or knyf or boytekyn</L>
<L>ffor Ielous folk ben perelous euere mo</L>
<L>Algate &thorn;ey wolde here wyuys wenden so</L>
<L>And ek for sche was sumwhat smotyrlych</L>
<L N="3964">Sche was as dygne as watyr In a dich</L>
<L>And ful of hokyr &amp; of bismerye</L>
<L>Sche thoughte &thorn;at a lady schulde here spareye</L>
<L>What for here kynrede &amp; here Norterye</L>
<L N="3968">That sche hadde lerned in &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> nunnerye</L>
<L>A doughtyr hadde &thorn;ey be-twixe hem too</L>
<L>Of twenty &yogh;er with-outyn ony moo</L>
<L>Sauynge a chyld &thorn;at was of sene &yogh;er age</L>
<L N="3972">In cradil it lay &amp; was a propere page</L>
<L>This wenche thikke &amp; wel I-growyn was</L>
<L>With cammuse nose &amp; eyen greye as glas</L>
<L>Buttokkys brode &amp; brestis rounde &amp; hye</L>
<L N="3976">But rygh fayr was here her I wele not lye</L>
<L>This persoun of the toun for sche was so fayr</L>
<L>In purpos was to makyn here hese eyr</L>
<L>But of hese catel &amp; hese mesewage</L>
<L N="3980">And straunge he made it of here maryge</L>
<L>Hese purpos was for to be-stowe here hye</L>
<L>In to sum worthi blod of aunceterye</L>
<L>ffor holicherche good / mote ben dispendit</L>
<L N="3984">On holy cherchis blod / &thorn;at is dessendit</L>
<L>&THORN;erfore he wolde / hese holy blod honoure</L>
<L>Thow &thorn;at he holy cherche / schulde devoure</L>
<L>Gret sokene hath / this mellere out of doute</L>
<L N="3988">With whete &amp; malt / of al the lond a-boute
<PB REF="00000131.tif" N="115"></L>
<L>And namely &thorn;ere was a gret college</L>
<L>Men clepyth &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> soler halle at cantebrege</L>
<L>There was heyre whete &amp; here malt I-grounde</L>
<L N="3992">And on a day it happede in a stounde</L>
<L>Sek lay &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> mauncypele on a malady<MILESTONE N="187b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Men wendyn wisely &thorn;at he schulde dey</L>
<L>ffor which this mellere stal bothe mele &amp; corn</L>
<L N="3996">An hundere tyme more &thorn;an be-forn</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ere be-forn he stal but curteysly</L>
<L>But now he was a thef outragyously</L>
<L>ffor whych &thorn;e wardeyn schod &amp; made fare</L>
<L N="4000">But therof sette this mellere not a tare</L>
<L>He crakyth bost &amp; swor it was not so</L>
<L>&THORN;anne were there pore clerkys too</L>
<L>That dwelledyn in &thorn;is halle of whiche I seyde</L>
<L N="4004">Testyf &thorn;ey were &amp; lusty for to pleye</L>
<L>And only for here myrthe &amp; reuerye</L>
<L>Vp on &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> wardeyn besily &thorn;ey crye</L>
<L>To &yogh;eue hem leue but a lite stounde</L>
<L N="4008">To gon to melle / to sen here corn I-grounde</L>
<L>And hardely &thorn;ey durste leyn here nekke</L>
<L>The mellere schulde not stele hem half a pekke</L>
<L>Of corn be sleyghte ne be forse hem reue</L>
<L N="4012">And at &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> laste &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> wardeyn &yogh;af hem leue</L>
<L>Ion highte &thorn;at on &amp; aleyn hyghte &thorn;at o&thorn;er</L>
<L>Of on toun were &thorn;ey born &thorn;at hyghte strother</L>
<L>ffer in the north I can not tellyn where</L>
<L N="4016">This aleyn makyth redy al hese gere</L>
<L>And on an hors he caste &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sak a-non</L>
<L>Forth goth aleyn &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> clerk &amp; also Ion</L>
<L>With good swerd &amp; bokeler bi here syde</L>
<L N="4020">Ion knew &thorn;e weye hem nedyth no gyde</L>
<L>And at &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> melle &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> sak a-doun he leyth</L>
<L>Aleyn spak fyrst alheyl symound in feyth</L>
<L>How farys &thorn;yn fayre dou&yogh;tyr &amp; thyn wif</L>
<L N="4024">Aleyn wolcome quod symkyn be myn lyf
<PB REF="00000132.tif" N="116"></L>
<L>And Iohn also how now what do &yogh;e here</L>
<L>Symond quod Iohn bi god nede has no pere</L>
<L>He muste serue hym self &thorn;at has no sweyn</L>
<L N="4028">Or ellis he is a fol as clerkis seyn</L>
<L>Oure maunciple I hope he wele be ded<MILESTONE N="188a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Swa werkis ay / &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> wangis in hese hed</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore is I come &amp; ek aleyn</L>
<L N="4032">To grynde oure corn &amp; carie it hom a-geyn</L>
<L>I prey &yogh;ow spede vs hene as &yogh;e may</L>
<L>It schal be don quod symkyn be myn fay</L>
<L>What wel &yogh;e don whil &thorn;at it is in hande</L>
<L N="4036">By god ry&yogh;t by &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> hopyr wele I stande</L>
<L>Quod Ion &amp; sen how &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> corn goth in</L>
<L>&YOGH;it saw I neuere be myn fadir kyn</L>
<L>How &thorn;at &thorn;e hopir wagis to &amp; fra</L>
<L N="4040">Aleyn answerede &amp; seyde wist &thorn;ou swa</L>
<L>Thanne wele I be beneth bi myn croun</L>
<L>And sen how &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> mele fallyth don</L>
<L>In to &thorn;e trow &thorn;at schal ben myn dysport</L>
<L N="4044">ffor Iohn yfayth I may ben of &yogh;ore sort</L>
<L>I is as ille a mellere as is &yogh;e</L>
<L>This mellere smylede of here nysetee</L>
<L>And thou&yogh;te al &thorn;is it nys don but for a wyle</L>
<L N="4048">They wene &thorn;at no man may hem be-gyle</L>
<L>But be myn thryft / &yogh;it wele I blere here ye</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;e sley&yogh;te in here philosofye</L>
<L>The more queynte crokede &thorn;at &thorn;ey make</L>
<L N="4052">The more wele I stele whan I take</L>
<L>In stede of flour / &yogh;it wele I &yogh;eue h&emacr;m bren</L>
<L>The gretteste clerkys ben not wyseste men</L>
<L>As whilom to &thorn;e wolf &thorn;us spak &thorn;e mare</L>
<L N="4056">Of al here art I counte not a tare</L>
<L>Out at &thorn;e dore he goth ful pryuyly</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at he saw hese tyme softely</L>
<L>He lokyth vp &amp; doun tyl he haue founde</L>
<L N="4060">The clerkys hors &thorn;ere as it stod I-bounde
<PB REF="00000133.tif" N="117"></L>
<L>Be-hynde &thorn;e melle vndyr a leuesel</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e hors he goth fayre &amp; wel</L>
<L>He strepith of &thorn;e brydil ryght a-non</L>
<L N="4064">And whan &thorn;e hors was los he gynnyth gon</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e fen &thorn;ere wilde marys renne<MILESTONE N="188b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And forth with wehe &thorn;our theke &amp; thorw thenne</L>
<L>This mellere gooth a-&yogh;en / no word he seyde</L>
<L N="4068">But doth his note &amp; with &thorn;e clerkis pleyede</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at here corn was wel &amp; fayre grounde</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;e mele is salkyd &amp; I-bounde</L>
<L>This Iohn goth out &amp; fynt his hors away</L>
<L N="4072">And gan to crye harow &amp; weyleaway</L>
<L>Oure hors is lorn aleyn for godys bonys</L>
<L>Step on thyn foot Aleyn come of atonys</L>
<L>Allas oure wardeyn has hese palfrey lorn</L>
<L N="4076">This aleyn for-gat bothe mele &amp; corn</L>
<L>Al was out of hese mynde hese hosebondrye</L>
<L>What whedir is he gon he gan to crye</L>
<L>The wyf cam lepynge inward with a ren</L>
<L N="4080">Sche seyde alas &yogh;oure hors goth to &thorn;e fen</L>
<L>Wyth wylde marys as faste as sche may go</L>
<L>Vn-thank come on hese hand &thorn;at bond hym so</L>
<L>And he &thorn;at betere schulde a knyt &thorn;e reyne</L>
<L N="4084">Allas quod aleyn for crystis peyne</L>
<L>Ley doun &thorn;yn swerd / &amp; I wele myn al swa</L>
<L>I is ful wy&yogh;t god woot as is a raa</L>
<L>By goddis herte / he schal nat skape vs ba&thorn;e</L>
<L N="4088">Whi ne haddist &thorn;ou pit &thorn;e capyl in &thorn;e lathe</L>
<L>Ille hayl aleyn be god &thorn;ou is a fonne</L>
<L>These sely clerkis han ful faste I-ronne</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e fen / bothe aleyn &amp; ek Iohn</L>
<L N="4092">And whan &thorn;e mellere saw &thorn;at &thorn;ey were gon</L>
<L>He half a buschel of here flour hath take</L>
<L>And bad hese wif gon knede it in a kake</L>
<L>He seyde I trowe &thorn;e clerkys were a-feryd</L>
<L N="4096">&YOGH;it can a mellere make a clerkys berd
<PB REF="00000134.tif" N="118"></L>
<L>ffor al here art now lat hem gon here woye</L>
<L>Lo where he goth &thorn;at lat &thorn;e childeryn pleye</L>
<L>They gete hym not so ly&yogh;tely / be myn croun</L>
<L N="4100">These sely clerkys rennen vp &amp; doun</L>
<L>Wyth kep kep / stand stand stand Iossa ware &thorn;e rere<MILESTONE N="189a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ga whystele thow &amp; I schal kepe hymm here</L>
<L>But schortly til &thorn;at it was veray nyght</L>
<L N="4104">They coude not Thow they don al here my&yogh;t</L>
<L>Here capil cache he ran al wey so faste</L>
<L>Tyl in a dych &thorn;ey caughte hym at &thorn;e laste</L>
<L>Wery &amp; wet as beste is in &thorn;e reyn</L>
<L N="4108">Comyth sely ion &amp; with hym comyth aleyn</L>
<L>Allas quod Iohn &thorn;e day &thorn;at I was born</L>
<L>Now are we dreuyn tyl hethng &amp; to scorn</L>
<L>Oure corn is stole men wele vs folys calle</L>
<L N="4112">Bo&thorn;e &thorn;e wardayn &amp; oure felas alle</L>
<L>And namely &thorn;e mellere weyleawey</L>
<L>Thus pleynyth Iohn as he goth be &thorn;e wey</L>
<L>Toward &thorn;e melle / &amp; bayard in hese hond</L>
<L N="4116">The mellere sittynge by &thorn;e fyr he fond</L>
<L>ffor it was ny&yogh;t &amp; fer&thorn;ere my&yogh;te &thorn;ey nought</L>
<L>But for &thorn;e loue of god &thorn;ey hym be-sought</L>
<L>Of herberwe &amp; of ese for here peny</L>
<L N="4120">The mellere seyde a-geyn &yogh;if &thorn;ere be eny</L>
<L>Swich as it is &yogh;it schal &yogh;e haue &yogh;oure part</L>
<L>Myn hous is streyt but &yogh;e han lernede art</L>
<L>&YOGH;e cunne with argumentis make a place</L>
<L N="4124">A myle brod of twenty fote of space</L>
<L>Let se now &yogh;if &thorn;is space may suffyse</L>
<L>Or make it roum with speche as is &yogh;oure gyse</L>
<L>Now symond seyde Iohn be seynt Cutbert</L>
<L N="4128">Ay art &thorn;ou merye &amp; &thorn;is is fayre answeryd</L>
<L>I haue herd seyd men schal tan of too thyngis</L>
<L>Swich as he fynd or take swich as he bryngis</L>
<L>But specially I preye &thorn;e hoot &amp; deere</L>
<L N="4132">Gete vs sum mete &amp; drynk &amp; make vs chere
<PB REF="00000135.tif" N="119"></L>
<L>And we wele paye trewely at &thorn;e folle</L>
<L>With emty hand men may none haukys tolle</L>
<L>Lo here oure syluyr / redy for to spende</L>
<L N="4136">This mellere in to &thorn;e tounne hese doughtyr sende</L>
<L>ffor ale &amp; bred &amp; rostede hem a goos<MILESTONE N="189b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And bond here hors it schulde not gon loos</L>
<L>And in hese owene chaumbir made a bed</L>
<L N="4140">With schetis &amp; with chalounnys fayre I-spred</L>
<L>Not from his owene bed ten fote or twelve</L>
<L>Hese dou&yogh;tyr hadde a bed al by here selue</L>
<L>Rygh in &thorn;e same schaumbyr by &amp; by</L>
<L N="4144">It my&yogh;te ben no bet &amp; cause why</L>
<L>There was non roumere herberw in &thorn;e plase</L>
<L>The soupe &amp; &thorn;ey speke hem to solase</L>
<L>And dronkyn ay strong ale at &thorn;e beste</L>
<L N="4148">Aboute medeny&yogh;t wente &thorn;ey to reste</L>
<L>Wel hath this mellere vernychid hese hed</L>
<L>fful pale he was for-drunke &amp; not red</L>
<L>He &yogh;yksneth &amp; spekyth &thorn;ourw &thorn;e nose</L>
<L N="4152">As he were on &thorn;e quakke or on &thorn;e pose</L>
<L>To bedde he go&thorn; &amp; with hym goth his wif</L>
<L>As ony iay sche ly&yogh;t was &amp; iolyf</L>
<L>So was here ioly whistele wel I-wet</L>
<L N="4156">The cradil at here beddys feet is set</L>
<L>To rokke &amp; to &yogh;eue &thorn;e child to souke</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;at dronkyn al was in &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> crouke</L>
<L>To bedde wente &thorn;e dou&yogh;tyr ry&yogh;t a-non</L>
<L N="4160">To bedde goth aleyn &amp; ek Iohn</L>
<L>Ther nas no mor hem neded no dwale</L>
<L>This mellere hath so wysely bibbit alle</L>
<L>That as an hors he snortyth in hese slep</L>
<L N="4164">Ne of hese tayl ne takyth he no kep</L>
<L>Hese wif bar hym a burdoun a ful strong</L>
<L>Men my&yogh;tyn here hyre route too furlong</L>
<L>The wenche routyth ek par cumpaynye</L>
<L N="4168">Aleyn &thorn;e clerk &thorn;at herde &thorn;is melodye
<PB REF="00000136.tif" N="120"></L>
<L>He pokede ion &amp; seyde slepist &thorn;ou</L>
<L>Herdist &thorn;ou euere swich a song er now</L>
<L>Lo swich a copil is a-mong hem alle</L>
<L N="4172">A wylde fyr mote on here bodyis falle</L>
<L>Ho herkenyth euere swich a ferly thyng<MILESTONE N="190a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>&YOGH;a &thorn;ey schal haue &thorn;e flour of ille endyng</L>
<L>This longe ny&yogh;t &thorn;ere tydis me no reste</L>
<L N="4176">But &yogh;it no fors al schal ben for the beste</L>
<L>ffor Iohn seyde he as euere mote I thryue</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at I may &thorn;e wenche wele I schryue</L>
<L>Sum esement has lawe I-schapyn vs</L>
<L N="4180">ffor Iohn &thorn;ere is a lawe &thorn;at says &thorn;us</L>
<L>That &yogh;if a man in a poynt be a-greuyd</L>
<L>That in a no&thorn;er he schal ben releuyd</L>
<L>Oure corn is stolin schortly it is non nay</L>
<L N="4184">And we han had an ille fit al &thorn;is day</L>
<L>And syn I schal han non a-mendement</L>
<L>A-geyn my los I wele haue eysement</L>
<L>By godys sale it schal non o&thorn;er be</L>
<L N="4188">This Iohn answerde Aley a-vise &thorn;e</L>
<L>The mellere is a perlyous man he seyde</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;at he out of hese slep a-breyde</L>
<L>He my&yogh;te vs don bothe a velanye</L>
<L N="4192">Alyn answerde I counte hym not a flye</L>
<L>And vp he sterte &amp; by &thorn;e wenche he crepte</L>
<L>This wenche lay vp ryght &amp; faste slepte</L>
<L>Tyl he so nygh was er sche myghte aspye</L>
<L N="4196">That it hadde be to late for to crye</L>
<L>And schortely for to seyn &thorn;ey were at on</L>
<L>Now pley aleyn for I wele speke of ion</L>
<L>This Iohn lyth stylle a furlong wey or too</L>
<L N="4200">And to hym self he makyth reuthe &amp; woo</L>
<L>Allas quod he &thorn;is is a wekede iape</L>
<L>Now may I seyn &thorn;at I is but an ape</L>
<L>&YOGH;it hath myn felawe sumwhat for hese harm</L>
<L N="4204">He has &thorn;e melleris dou&yogh;tyr in hese arm
<PB REF="00000137.tif" N="121"></L>
<L>He auntered hym &amp; has hese nedis sped</L>
<L>And I lye as a draf sek in myn bed</L>
<L>And whan &thorn;is iape is told a no&thorn;er day</L>
<L N="4208">I schal ben told a daffe a cokenay</L>
<L>I wele ryse &amp; antere it be myn fay<MILESTONE N="190b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vn-hardi is vn-sely &thorn;us men say</L>
<L>And vp he ros &amp; softely he wente</L>
<L N="4212">Vn to &thorn;e cradil &amp; in hese hond it hente</L>
<L>And bar it softe vn to hese bedis feet</L>
<L>Sone aftyr &thorn;is &thorn;e wyf here routyng let</L>
<L>And gan to wake &amp; lefte for to pysse</L>
<L N="4216">And cam a-geyn &amp; gan here cradil mysse</L>
<L>And gropede here &amp; &thorn;ere / but sche fond non</L>
<L>Allas quod sche I hadde almost mys gon</L>
<L>I hadde al most gon to &thorn;e clerkys bed</L>
<L N="4220">Ey benedyste &thorn;anne hadde I foule I-sped</L>
<L>And forth sche goth tyl sche &thorn;e cradel fond</L>
<L>Sche gropede alwey fer&thorn;ere with here hond</L>
<L>And fond &thorn;e bed &amp; thou&yogh;te not but good</L>
<L N="4224">Be cause &thorn;at &thorn;e cradyl by it stod</L>
<L>And nyste where sche was for it was derk</L>
<L>And fayre &amp; wel sche crep in bi &thorn;e clerk</L>
<L>And lyth ful stylle &amp; wolde a cau&yogh;t a slep</L>
<L N="4228">With-inne a while &thorn;is Iohn vp lep</L>
<L>And on &thorn;is goode wif he leyth on sore</L>
<L>So merye a fit ne hadde sche ful &yogh;ore</L>
<L>He prikyth harde &amp; sore as he were mad</L>
<L N="4232">This ioly lyf han &thorn;ese too klerkis lad</L>
<L>Tyl &thorn;at &thorn;e fyrste kok be-gan to synge</L>
<L>Aleyn wex wery in &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> dawenynge</L>
<L>ffor he hadde swonkyn al &thorn;e longe ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="4236">And seyde farwel malyn swete wy&yogh;t</L>
<L>The day is come I may no lengere byde</L>
<L>But euere more where so I go or ryde</L>
<L>I is &thorn;yn owene clerk so haue I sel</L>
<L N="4240">Now dere leman quod sche go fare weel
<PB REF="00000138.tif" N="122"></L>
<L>But er &thorn;ou go on thyng I wele &thorn;e telle</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;ou wendyst homward be &thorn;e melle</L>
<L>Ry&yogh;t at &thorn;e entre of &thorn;e dore be-hynde<MILESTONE N="191a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4244">&THORN;ou schat a cake of half a buschel fynde</L>
<L>&THORN;at was I-makyd ry&yogh;t of &thorn;yn owene mele</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at I halp myn fadyr for to stele</L>
<L>And goode leman god &thorn;e saue &amp; kepe</L>
<L N="4248">And with &thorn;at word sche gan almost to wepe</L>
<L>Aleyn vp ryst &amp; thoughte er &thorn;an it dawe</L>
<L>I wele gon crepe in by myn felawe</L>
<L>And fond &thorn;e cradyl with hese hand a-non</L>
<L N="4252">By god &thorn;ou&yogh;te he al wrong I haue mys gon</L>
<L>Myn hed is toty of myn swynk to ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>&THORN;at makyth me &thorn;at I go not ary&yogh;t</L>
<L>I wot wel by &thorn;e cradyl I haue mys go</L>
<L N="4256">Here lyth &thorn;e mellere &amp; hese wyf also</L>
<L>And forth he goth a twenty deleway</L>
<L>Vn to &thorn;e bed &thorn;ere &thorn;at &thorn;e mellere lay</L>
<L>He wende a crepid bi hese felawe Ion</L>
<L N="4260">An by &thorn;e mellere in he crepede a-non</L>
<L>And cau&yogh;te hym by &thorn;e nekke softe he spak</L>
<L>He seyde &thorn;ou Iohn &thorn;ou sweuenyst a-wak</L>
<L>ffor cristis soule &amp; here a nobele game</L>
<L N="4264">ffor by &thorn;at lord &thorn;at called is seynt Iame</L>
<L>As I haue thryes in &thorn;e schorte ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>Swyuyd &thorn;e melleris dou&yogh;tyr bolt vp ry&yogh;t</L>
<L>Whil &thorn;ou hast as a coward been a-gast</L>
<L N="4268">&YOGH;a false harlot quod &thorn;e mellere hast</L>
<L>A false traytour false clerk quod he</L>
<L>Thow schat ben ded be godis dynete</L>
<L>Ho durste ben so bold to disparage</L>
<L N="4272">Myn dou&yogh;tyr &thorn;at is comyn of swych lenage</L>
<L>And by the throte bolle he caughte aleyn</L>
<L>And he hente hym dyspitously a-geyn</L>
<L>And on &thorn;e nose he smot hym with hese fest</L>
<L N="4276">Doun ran &thorn;e blod strem vp on hese brest
<PB REF="00000139.tif" N="123"></L>
<L>And in &thorn;e floor with nose &amp; mouth to-broke</L>
<L>They walwe as don too piggis in a poke</L>
<L>And vp &thorn;ey gon &amp; don a-geyn a-non<MILESTONE N="191b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4280">Tyl &thorn;at &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> mellere spurnede a&yogh;en a ston</L>
<L>And doun he fyl bakward vp on hese wif</L>
<L>That wiste no &thorn;yng of &thorn;is nyse stryf</L>
<L>ffor sche was falle a slepe a lyte wyght</L>
<L N="4284">With Iohn &thorn;e clerk &thorn;at wakede al ny&yogh;t</L>
<L>And with &thorn;e fal out of here slep sche bryde</L>
<L>Help holy croys of bromeholm sche seyde</L>
<L>In manus tuas lord to &thorn;e I calle</L>
<L N="4288">A-wake symond &thorn;e fend is on vs falle</L>
<L>Myn herte is brokyn allas I ne am but ded</L>
<L>There lyth on vp on myn wombe &amp; on myn hed</L>
<L>Help symkyn for &thorn;e false klerkys fy&yogh;te</L>
<L N="4292">This Iohn styrte vp as faste as euere he my&yogh;te</L>
<L>And graspith by the walle to &amp; fra</L>
<L>To fynde a staf &amp; sche styrte vp alswa</L>
<L>And knew &thorn;e estis betere &thorn;an dede &thorn;is Iohn</L>
<L N="4296">And bi &thorn;e wal a staf sche fond a-non</L>
<L>And saw a lytyl schemeryng of a ly&yogh;t</L>
<L>ffor at an hole in schon &thorn;e mone bryt<NOTE PLACE="marg">[corrected]</NOTE></L>
<L>And by &thorn;at ly&yogh;t sche say hem bo&thorn;e too</L>
<L N="4300">But sekyrly sche nyste ho was who</L>
<L>But as sche say a whit thyng in here eye</L>
<L>And whan sche gan &thorn;e whyte &thorn;yng espye</L>
<L>Sche wende &thorn;e clerk hadde wered a wolyper</L>
<L N="4304">And with the staf sche drow ay ner &amp; ner</L>
<L>And wende an hit &thorn;es aleyn at &thorn;e fulle</L>
<L>And smot &thorn;e mellere on &thorn;e pylede sculle</L>
<L>And doun he goth harow I deye</L>
<L N="4308">These clerkys bete hym wel &amp; lete hym lye</L>
<L>And hastede hem &amp; toke here leue a-non</L>
<L>And ek here mele &amp; on here woye &thorn;ey gon</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e melle &yogh;it &thorn;ey toke here kake</L>
<L N="4312">Of half a buschel flour wol wel I-bake
<PB REF="00000140.tif" N="124"></L>
<L>Thus is &thorn;e proude mellere wel I-bete</L>
<L>And hath I-lost the gryndyng of &thorn;e wete</L>
<L>And payed for &thorn;e souper euery del<MILESTONE N="192a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="4316">Of aleyn &amp; of Iohn &thorn;at bete hym wel</L>
<L>Hese wyf is swyuyd &amp; hese doughtyr als</L>
<L>Lo swich It is a mellere<NOTE PLACE="marg">[re: <I>later</I>]</NOTE> to ben fals</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore this prouerbe is seyd ful soth<NOTE PLACE="marg">[soth: <I>later</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L N="4320">Hym thar not wene wel &thorn;at euele doth</L>
<L>A gylour schal<NOTE PLACE="marg">[l: <I>later</I>]</NOTE> hym self begylede be</L>
<L>And god &thorn;at settyth hye in<NOTE PLACE="marg">[in: <I>later</I>]</NOTE> mageste</L>
<L>Save all &thorn;ese cumpanyis grate<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>? corrected to</I> grete]</NOTE> &amp; smale</L>
<L N="4324">Thus haue I quit &thorn;e mellere in myn tale<NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>Break of</I> 3 <I>lines in the MS.</I>]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000141.tif" N="125">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THe cook of lundene whil &thorn;e reue spak</L>
<L>ffor ioye hym thou&yogh;te he clawede hym on &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> bak</L>
<L>Ha ha ha for cristys passyoun</L>
<L N="4328">This mellere hadde a scharp conclusyoun</L>
<L>Vp on his argument of herbergage</L>
<L>Wel seyde salamon / on his langage</L>
<L>Ne brynge not euery with in to &thorn;yn hous</L>
<L N="4332">ffor herberwynge be ny&yogh;te is perlyous</L>
<L>Wel au&yogh;te a man avysede for to be</L>
<L>Whom &thorn;at he brou&yogh;te in to hese priuyte</L>
<L>I preye to god so &yogh;eue me sorwe &amp; care</L>
<L N="4336">Syn euere I highte hoge of ware</L>
<L>Herde I euere a mellere betere I-set a werke</L>
<L>He hadde a Iape of maleys in &thorn;e derke</L>
<L>But god for-bede &thorn;at we stentyn here</L>
<L N="4340">And &thorn;erfore &yogh;if &yogh;e wouche saf to here</L>
<L>A tale of me &thorn;at am a pore man</L>
<L>I wele &yogh;ow telle as wel as euere I can</L>
<L>A lytyl Iape what fel in oure cete</L>
<L N="4344">Oure ost answerde &amp; seyde I graunte it &thorn;e</L>
<L>Now telle on roger &amp; loke &thorn;at it be good</L>
<L>ffor manye a paste hast &thorn;ou letyn blod</L>
<L>And manye a rakke of douere hast &thorn;ou sold/</L>
<L N="4348">That hath ben twyes hot &amp; twyes cold<MILESTONE N="192b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of manye a pilgrym hast &thorn;ou cristis curs</L>
<L>ffor of thyn persele &yogh;it thy fare &thorn;e wers</L>
<L>That &thorn;ey han etyn with thyn stobil goos</L>
<L N="4352">ffor in thyn schoppe is manye a flye los</L>
<L>Now telle on gentyl roger be &thorn;yn name</L>
<L>But &yogh;it I preye &thorn;e be not wroth for game</L>
<L>A man may sey ful soth in game &amp; play</L>
<L N="4356">Thow seyst ful soth quod roger be myn fay
<PB REF="00000142.tif" N="126"></L>
<L>But sooth pley quaad pley as &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> flemyng seyth</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore herry bayly be &thorn;yn feyth</L>
<L>Be &thorn;ou not wroth er we partyn here</L>
<L N="4360">Thow &thorn;at myn tale be of an ostelere</L>
<L>But natheles I wele nat telle it &yogh;et</L>
<L>But er we parte I-wis &thorn;ou schat be quit</L>
<L>And &thorn;erwithal he low &amp; made chere</L>
<L N="4364">And seyde hese tale as &yogh;e schal aftyr here<NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS.]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000143.tif" N="127">
<HEAD>Here begynnyst the kok of lundene hi tale<NOTE>[painting of the Cook]</NOTE></HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Nearly all leaf</I> 193 <I>of Camb</I>. MS <I>is cut out</I>. Only He l. 4372, As 4373, We 4374, At 4375, H 4376, ff 4377, <I>and bits of</I> O <I>and</I> T, 4378-9, <I>are left, and</I> se <I>of</I> plase, l. 4410, <I>and</I> aunce 4412.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A Prentis whilom dwellid in oure citee<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS. 1685 folio" N="50b"></L>
<L>And of a craft of vitalers was he</L>
<L>Gaillard he was as gol-fynche in &thorn;e schawe</L>
<L N="4368">Broun as bery. a proper short felawe</L>
<L>With lokkes blake I-kempt ful fetisly</L>
<L>Daunce he kou&thorn;e so wel and Iolyly</L>
<L>That he clepid perkyn reueilloure</L>
<L N="4372">He was as ful of loue and paramour</L>
<L>As is &thorn;e hive ful of hony swete</L>
<L>Wel was &thorn;e wenche with him myght mete</L>
<L>At euery bridale wold he synge and hoppe</L>
<L N="4376">He louede bette &thorn;e tauerne &thorn;an &thorn;e shoppe</L>
<L>ffor whan &thorn;er any ridynge was in chepe<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS. 1685 folio" N="51a"></L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e Shoppe &thorn;eder wold he lepe</L>
<L>Til &thorn;at he had al &thorn;e sight I-seyn</L>
<L N="4380">And daunced wel wold he not come a-gayne</L>
<L>And gedrid hym mony of his sort</L>
<L>To hoppe and synge and make suche disport</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere &thorn;ey setten steuene for to mete</L>
<L N="4384">To pleyn at &thorn;e dys in suche a strete</L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;e toun nas ner no prentis</L>
<L>That fairer cou&thorn;e cast a peyre of dys</L>
<L>Then perkyn couth and &thorn;erto he was free</L>
<L N="4388">Of his dispence in place of pryuyte</L>
<L>That fonde his maister wel in his chaffare</L>
<L>ffor ofte tyme he fonde his box ful bare</L>
<L>ffor sikirly a prentis reuelour</L>
<L N="4392">. . . . .<NOTE PLACE="inline">no gap in the MS.</NOTE></L>
<L>His maystir shuld it in his shep abye</L>
<L>Al haue not part of &thorn;e mynstralcie</L>
<L>ffor theft and riot &thorn;ei ben conuertible</L>
<L N="4396">Al can he pleye on geterne or rubible
<PB REF="00000144.tif" N="128"></L>
<L>Reuel and trouth as in lowe degree<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sloane MS 1685]</NOTE></L>
<L>They ben ful wroth al day as men may see</L>
<L>This Iolye prentis with his mayster boode</L>
<L N="4400">Til he were nyghe oute of his prentis-hoode</L>
<L>Al were he snybbit erly and late</L>
<L>And somtyme lad with Reuel to Newgate</L>
<L>But at last his maystir him by-&thorn;oght</L>
<L N="4404">Vpon a day whan he his paper sought</L>
<L>Of a prouerbe &thorn;at saith &thorn;is same word</L>
<L>Wel bet is roten appel oute of hoorde</L>
<L>Than &thorn;at it rotet alle &thorn;e remenant</L>
<L N="4408">So farith it by a ryocous seruant</L>
<L>It is ful lasse harme to late hym passe</L>
<L>Than he shend alle &thorn;e seruauntz in &thorn;e place</L>
<L>Therfore his maystir &yogh;af him a quytaunce</L>
<L N="4412">And bade him go with sorow and myschaunce</L>
<L>And &thorn;us this Ioly prentis had his leuee<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS. 1685 folio" N="51b"></L>
<L>Now let hym Riot al &thorn;e nyght or leue</L>
<L>And for ther is no theof with-oute a loke</L>
<L N="4416">That helpith hym to wasten and to sowke</L>
<L>Of &thorn;at he bribe can or borow may</L>
<L>Anoon he sent his bede and his array</L>
<L>Vn to a couper of his owne soort</L>
<L N="4420">That loued dys Reuel and disport</L>
<L>And had a wif &thorn;at held for contynaunce</L>
<L>A shope and swyfed for hir sustynaunce<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sloane extract ends.]</NOTE>
</L>
</LG>

</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="B" TYPE="group"><PB REF="00000145.tif" N="129">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>B.</B> (&alpha;. FRAGMENT II.)</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 1. MAN OF LAW'S HEAD-LINK. CAMBRIDGE MS. Here begynneth the Prolog of the man of lawe.</HEAD>

<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Harleian MS</I> 1758, <I>leaf</I> 55, <I>back</I>.]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>oure Oste saugh well that the bright sonne.</L>
<L>The arke of his artaficiall day had ronne.</L>
<L>The fourthe parte &amp; half an houre &amp; more.</L>
<L N="4">And though he were not deep experte in lore.</L>
<L>He wist it was the .xviij. day.</L>
<L>Of Aprill that is messager/ to May.</L>
<L>And saugh well that the schadow of euery tre.</L>
<L N="8">Was as in lengthe the same quantite.</L>
<L>That was the body erecte that causid it.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Harl. extract ends]</NOTE></L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore by &thorn;e schadewe he tok hese wit<NOTE PLACE="marg">Camb. MS</NOTE><MILESTONE N="194a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That phebus which &thorn;at schon so cler &amp; bry&yogh;t</L>
<L N="12">Degreis fyue &amp; forty I-clombe on hy&yogh;t</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at day as in &thorn;at latytude</L>
<L>It was ten of &thorn;e clok he gan conclude</L>
<L>And sodeynly he ply&yogh;te hese hors a-boute</L>
<L N="16">Lordyngis quod he I warne &yogh;ow al &thorn;is route</L>
<L>The fourte party of &thorn;is day is gon</L>
<L>Now for &thorn;e loue of god &amp; seynt Iohn</L>
<L>Leseth no tyme as fer forth as &yogh;e may</L>
<L N="20">Lordyngis it wastyth ny&yogh;t &amp; day</L>
<L>And stelyth from vs what priuyly slepynge</L>
<L>And what &thorn;erwith neclygence In oure wakynge</L>
<L>As doth &thorn;e strem &thorn;at turnyth neuere a-geyn</L>
<L N="24">Dessendynge from &thorn;e monteyn In-to pleyn</L>
<L>Wel can senykeke &amp; manye a phylisofere</L>
<L>Bewaylyn tyme more &thorn;an gold in cofere</L>
<L>ffor los of catel may recouerede be</L>
<L N="28">But los of tyme schendyth vs quod he
<PB REF="00000146.tif" N="130"></L>
<L>It wele not come a-geyn with-outyn drede</L>
<L>No more &thorn;an wele malkenys maydynhede</L>
<L>Whan sche hath lost it in here wantounnesse</L>
<L N="32">Let vs not moulyn &thorn;us in ydylnesse</L>
<L>Syre man of lawe so haue &yogh;e blys</L>
<L>Telle vs a tale now as forward is</L>
<L>&YOGH;e ben submyttit &thorn;our &yogh;oure fre assent</L>
<L N="36">To stondyn in &thorn;is cas at myn Iugement</L>
<L>A-quytht &yogh;ow now of &yogh;oure be-heste</L>
<L>&THORN;anne haue &yogh;e don &yogh;oure deuyr at &thorn;e leste</L>
<L>Host quod he depardeux I assente</L>
<L N="40">To brekyn forward is not myn entente</L>
<L>Byheste is dette &amp; I wele holde fayn</L>
<L>Al myn beheste I can no betere seyn</L>
<L>ffor swich lawe as man &yogh;euyth a-no&thorn;er wy&yogh;t</L>
<L N="44">He schulde hym selue vse it be right</L>
<L>Thus wele oure tyxt / but natheles serteyn</L>
<L>I can not now non thrifty tale seyn<MILESTONE N="194b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That Chaucer thoughte he can but lewedely</L>
<L N="48">On metris &amp; on rymyng craftyly</L>
<L>As seyde hem in swich engelych as he can</L>
<L>Of olde tyme as knowyth manye a man</L>
<L>And &yogh;if he haue not seyde hem leue bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="52">In on bok he hath seyd hem in a no&thorn;er</L>
<L>ffor he hath told of louerys vp &amp; down</L>
<L>Mo &thorn;an ouyde made of mencyoun /</L>
<L>In hese epistell &thorn;at ben ful olde</L>
<L N="56">What schulde I telle hem syn &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben tolde</L>
<L>In &yogh;outhe he made of Ceys &amp; alceoun</L>
<L>And sy&thorn;e ha&thorn; he spoke of euerychon</L>
<L>These nobele wyuys &amp; &thorn;ese loueris ek</L>
<L N="60">Who so &thorn;at wole hese large volum sek</L>
<L>Clepid &thorn;e seyntis legende of cupide</L>
<L>There may he se &thorn;e large woundis wyde</L>
<L>Of lucresse &amp; of babiloyn Tisbee</L>
<L N="64">The swerd of dido for &thorn;e false Enee
<PB REF="00000147.tif" N="131"></L>
<L>The tre of phill for here demephoun</L>
<L>The pleynt of dyane &amp; of hermyoun</L>
<L>Of adryane &amp; of Isiphilee</L>
<L N="68">The barayne yle standynge in &thorn;e se</L>
<L>The dreynte leandere for hese erro</L>
<L>The terys of elyne &amp; ek &thorn;e wo</L>
<L>Of brixseyde &amp; of &thorn;e ladomya</L>
<L N="72">The cruelte of &thorn;e quene media</L>
<L>Thy lityl childeryn hangynge by &thorn;e hals</L>
<L>ffor thy Iason &thorn;at was in loue so fals</L>
<L>O ypermystre penolopee Alceste</L>
<L N="76">&YOGH;oure wifhod be commendit with &thorn;e beste</L>
<L>But serteynly no word wryty[t]h he</L>
<L>Of thilk ensaumple of Canacee</L>
<L>That louede here owene bro&thorn;er synfully</L>
<L N="80">Of swiche cursede storyis I seye fy</L>
<L>Or ellis of Thiro appolonyus</L>
<L>[How &thorn;e cursid kynge Anciocus<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS 1685 folio" N="63a"></L>
<L>Byrafte hys dou&yogh;tir hir Maydenhede</L>
<L N="84">&thorn;at ys so horrible a tale for to here</L>
<L>Whan he hir &thorn;rowe &thorn;orough &thorn;e pament</L>
<L>And &thorn;[er]fore he of full avisement</L>
<L>Wolde nevere write in none of his sermones</L>
<L N="88">Of whiche vnkynde abhomynacions</L>
<L>Ne I&middot; ne wil non reherse if &thorn;at I may</L>
<L>But of my tale how shalle doo &thorn;is day</L>
<L>Me were lothe he lykned douteles</L>
<L N="92">To Muses &thorn;at men clepen pieriedes</L>
<L>Metham-orphaseos wot wat y mene</L>
<L>But natheles I ne reche not a bene</L>
<L>Thoughe &middot;y&middot; come after hym with aw bake</L>
<L N="96">I speke in prose &amp; let hym Rymes make</L>
<L>And with &thorn;at worde he with a sobre chere</L>
<L N="98">By-gan his tale as ye shul after here</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Here endithe &thorn;e prolooge <NOTE PLACE="end">[No break in the MS here or between the stanzas.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&amp; bygynnithe &thorn;e tale</HEAD>


<DIV3 TYPE="part"><PB REF="00000148.tif" N="132">
<HEAD>[THE PROLOGUE.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ohatfulle harme condicion of pouert<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sloane MS 1685]</NOTE></L>
<L>With thrust with colde with hungre so confunded</L>
<L>To asken helpe &thorn;e shameth in &thorn;ine hert</L>
<L>If &thorn;ou now axe with nede arte &thorn;ou so wounded</L>
<L>That verray nede vnwrappid al &thorn;i wounde hyd<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS 1685 folio" N="63b"></L>
<L>Maugre &thorn;ine hede &thorn;ou moste for Indegens</L>
<L N="105">Or stele or begge or borowe &thorn;i dispense</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thou blamest crist &amp; seyst fulle vtterly</L>
<L>He in his departith rychesse temporal</L>
<L>Thy neghboure &thorn;ou witest synfully</L>
<L N="109">And seyste &thorn;ou haste to lytelle &amp; he hath alle</L>
<L>Par fay seyste &thorn;ou some tyme &thorn;ou reken shalle</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at his tayle shal brenne in &thorn;e glede</L>
<L N="112">ffor he nou&yogh;t helpith nedefulle in her nede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Herkene what ys &thorn;e menynge of &thorn;e wise</L>
<L>Bet is to dien &thorn;an to haue Indigence &middot;</L>
<L>Thy self neghbore wol &thorn;e dispice</L>
<L N="116">If &thorn;ou be pore fare wele &thorn;i reuerence</L>
<L>&YOGH;et of &thorn;e wise man take &thorn;is sentence &middot;</L>
<L>Alle dayes of pore men be wykke</L>
<L N="119">Be ware &thorn;erfore or &thorn;ou com in &thorn;at prik /</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>If &thorn;ou be pore &thorn;i Brother hatith &thorn;e</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;i ffrendes fleen fro &thorn;e Allas &middot;</L>
<L>O riche merchantes ful of wele be &yogh;e<NOTE PLACE="marg">[The MS trans|poses these two lines.]</NOTE></L>
<L>O noble prudent folke as in &thorn;is cas<NOTE PLACE="marg">[The MS trans|poses these two lines.]</NOTE></L>
<L>youre bagges buth not fullyd with ambes ais</L>
<L>But with sys synke &thorn;at renneth of your chaunce.</L>
<L N="126">At cristes masse merie may ye daunce.
<PB REF="00000149.tif" N="133"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;e sechen londe and See for your wynnynges</L>
<L>As wyse folkes &thorn;at knowen alle &thorn;e staat /</L>
<L>Of regnes ye ben fadres &amp; tydynges</L>
<L N="130">And tales bothen of pees &amp; debate</L>
<L>I were ri&yogh;t nowe of talys dissolate</L>
<L>Nere &thorn;at a marchaunt goon ys many &middot;a&middot; yeere</L>
<L>Me taught a tale whiche as &middot; &yogh;e shal here<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sloane extract ends.]</NOTE><NOTE PLACE="end">[<I>Lines</I> 981-7, <I>p.</I> 161, <I>are repeated in the MS, leaf</I> 208. <I>Here is the second version, marked, in a later hand</I>, vatat, <I>for</I> vacat, <I>at the side:</I>&mdash;<Q><L>This senatourys wif hyre aunte was</L><L>But for al &thorn;at sche knew hyre neuere &thorn;e more</L><L>I wele no lengere taryen in &thorn;is cas</L><L>But to kyng alla which I spak of &yogh;ore</L><L>That for his wyf wepith &amp; sykyth sore</L><L>I wele returne &amp; lete I wele custaunce</L><L>Vndyr &thorn;e senatourys gouernaunce]</L></Q></NOTE></L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="1" TYPE="part">

<PB REF="00000150.tif" N="134">
<HEAD>[THE TALE.]</HEAD>
<HEAD>[PART I.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In Surry whilom dwellede a c[u]mpaignye<NOTE PLACE="marg">Cambridge MS</NOTE><MILESTONE N="196a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of chapmen riche &amp; &thorn;erto sadde &amp; trewe</L>
<L>That wide where sentyn here spicerye</L>
<L N="137">Clothis of gold &amp; satynys ryche of hewe</L>
<L>Here chaffare was so thrifty &amp; so newe</L>
<L>That euery wight hath deynte to chaffare</L>
<L N="140">With hem &amp; ek to sellen hem here ware</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now fil it that &thorn;e maysteris of &thorn;at sort</L>
<L>Han shapyn hem to rome for to wende</L>
<L>Were it for chapmanhod or for disport</L>
<L N="144">Non o&thorn;er message wolde he dedyr sende</L>
<L>But comyn hem self to rome &thorn;is is thende</L>
<L>And in swich place as thoghte hem thawauntage</L>
<L N="147">ffor hire entent &thorn;ey take hire herbergage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Soiournyd han &thorn;ese marchauntis in &thorn;at toun</L>
<L>A serteyn tyme as fel to here plesaunce</L>
<L>But so be-fel &thorn;at thexselent renoun</L>
<L N="151">Of themperourys doghter dame Custaunce</L>
<L>Reportid was with euery circumstance</L>
<L>Vn-to thys surryne marchantys in swich wise</L>
<L N="154">ffrom day to day as I schal &yogh;ow deuyse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This was the comune voys of euery man</L>
<L>Oure emperoure of rome god hym se</L>
<L>A doughtir hath &thorn;at syn &thorn;e world be-gan</L>
<L N="158">To rekene as wel here goodnes as here beute</L>
<L>Was neuere swich a-no&thorn;er as is sche</L>
<L>I preye to god in honour here sustene</L>
<L N="161">And wolde sche were of al Europe &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> quene
<PB REF="00000151.tif" N="135"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In here is high beute with-oute pryde</L>
<L>&YOGH;outhe with-oute grenehede or folye<NOTE PLACE="marg">[in a later hand]</NOTE></L>
<L>To alle here werkys vertu is here gyde</L>
<L N="165">Humblesse hath slayn in here al tyrannye</L>
<L>Sche is myrour of alle curteysye</L>
<L>Here herte is verray chambyr<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>or</I> chambur]</NOTE> of holynesse</L>
<L N="168">Hire hand mynystre of fredom for almesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And al &thorn;is voys was soth as god is trewe<MILESTONE N="196b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But now to purpos lat vs turne ageyn</L>
<L>These marchantys han don frau&yogh;t here schepis newe</L>
<L N="172">And whan &thorn;ey han &thorn;is blysful maydyn seyn</L>
<L>Hom to surry ben &thorn;ey went ful feyn</L>
<L>And on here nedys as &thorn;ey<NOTE PLACE="marg">[han <I>put-in in a later hand</I>]</NOTE> don ful &yogh;ore /</L>
<L N="175">And lyuen in wele I can sey &yogh;ow no more</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now fil it &thorn;at these marchantys stode in grace</L>
<L>Of hym &thorn;at was &thorn;e soudon of surrye</L>
<L>ffor whan &thorn;ey come from ony strange place</L>
<L N="179">He wolde of hese benygne curteysye</L>
<L>Make hem good cher &amp; besyly espye</L>
<L>Tydyngis of sundery regnys for to lere</L>
<L N="182">The wonderis &thorn;at he myghte sen or here</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Amongis o&thorn;ere thyngis specially</L>
<L>These marchauntis han hym told of dame Custaunce</L>
<L>So gret noblesse in ernest certeynly</L>
<L N="186">That this soudan hath cau&yogh;t so gret plesaunce</L>
<L>To han hyre fygure in hese remembraunce</L>
<L>And al hese lust &amp; al hese besy cure</L>
<L N="189">Was for to loue here whil his lyf may dure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Perauenture in thilke large boke</L>
<L>Which &thorn;at clepid is &thorn;e heuene I-wretyn was</L>
<L>With sterrys whan &thorn;at he hese berthe tok</L>
<L N="193">That he for loue schulde han hese deth allas
<PB REF="00000152.tif" N="136"></L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;e sterris clerere than is glas</L>
<L>Is wrete god wot ho so coude it rede</L>
<L N="196">The deth of euery man / with outyn any drede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In sterrys manye a wyntyr there be-forn</L>
<L>Was wretyn &thorn;e deth of ector achilles</L>
<L>Of pompeye Ielyus er &thorn;ey were born</L>
<L N="200">The stryf of thebes &amp; of hercules</L>
<L>Of sampson Thurnus &amp; of socrates</L>
<L>The deth but menys wittys ben so dulle</L>
<L N="203">That no with can wel rede it at &thorn;e fulle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This soudon for hese priuy conseyl sente<MILESTONE N="197a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And schortely of &thorn;is matiere for to pace</L>
<L>He hath to hem declarede his entente</L>
<L N="207">And seyde serteyn but he my&yogh;te han grace</L>
<L>To han custaunce with-inne a lytyl space</L>
<L>He nas but ded &amp; chargede hem in hye</L>
<L N="210">To schapyn for hese lyf sum remedye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Dyuerse men dyuerse thyngys seydyn</L>
<L>They argumentyn &amp; castyn vp &amp; doun</L>
<L>Manye a subtyle resoun forth &thorn;ey leydyn</L>
<L N="214">They spekyn of Magyk &amp; Abusio&umacr;n</L>
<L>But fynally as in conclusioun</L>
<L>They can not sen in that non auantage</L>
<L N="217">Ne in non othir woye saue maryage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thanne sawe they &thorn;erin swich difficulte</L>
<L>Be weye of resoun for to speke al pleeyn</L>
<L>Be cause &thorn;ere was / swich dyuercyte</L>
<L N="221">Be-twethyn here bothe lawys &thorn;at &thorn;ey seyn</L>
<L>They trowede that no crystene prynce wolde fayn</L>
<L>Weddyn his chyld vndyr oure lawys swete</L>
<L N="224">That vs was tau&yogh;t be mahoun oure prophete
<PB REF="00000153.tif" N="137"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And he answerde ra&thorn;ere than I lese</L>
<L>Constance I wele ben cristened douteles</L>
<L>I mote ben hers / I may non o&thorn;er chese</L>
<L N="228">I prey &yogh;ow holde &yogh;oure argument in pes</L>
<L>Sauyth myn lyf &amp; beth nat recheles</L>
<L>To getyn here that hath myn lyf in cure</L>
<L N="231">ffor in &thorn;is wo I may not longe endure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>What nedyth grettere dilatacioun</L>
<L>I sey be tretys &amp; enbassadrye</L>
<L>And bi &thorn;e popis mediacioun</L>
<L N="235">And al the cherch &amp; &thorn;e chyualrye</L>
<L>That in distruccioun of mametrye</L>
<L>And in encres of Crystes lawe dere</L>
<L N="238">They ben ecordit so as &yogh;e schal here</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>How &thorn;at the soudan &amp; hese baronage<MILESTONE N="197b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And alle hese lyges schulde cristenede be</L>
<L>And he schal haue custaunce in maryage</L>
<L N="242">And serteyn gold I not what quantyte</L>
<L>And heer to fyndyn sufficient suretee</L>
<L>This same a-cord was sworn on ey&thorn;er syde</L>
<L N="245">Now fayre Custaunce al-my&yogh;ty god &yogh;ow gyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now wolde sum men waytyn as I gesse</L>
<L>&YOGH;it I schulde telle al &thorn;e puruyaunce</L>
<L>That &thorn;e emperour of his greete noblesse</L>
<L>Hath schapyn for hese doughtur<NOTE PLACE="marg">[altered]</NOTE> dame<NOTE PLACE="marg">[altered]</NOTE> Custaunce</L>
<L>Wel may men knowe &thorn;at so gret ordenaunce</L>
<L>May no man telle in swich a lytyl clause</L>
<L N="252">As was arayed for so high a cause</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Byschopis ben schapyn with here for to wende</L>
<L>Lordyngis ladyis kny&yogh;tis of renoun</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ere folk I-nowe this is the ende</L>
<L N="256">And notyfyed is thorw out &thorn;e toun
<PB REF="00000154.tif" N="138"></L>
<L>That euery kny&yogh;t with gret deuocioun</L>
<L>Schulde preye crist &thorn;at he this maryage</L>
<L N="259">Receyue In gre &amp; spede &thorn;is viage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The day is come of here departynge</L>
<L>I sey the woful fatal day is come</L>
<L>That &thorn;ere may be no lengere taryinge</L>
<L N="263">But forward &thorn;ey hem drese alle &amp; some</L>
<L>Custaunce that was with sorwe al ouyrcome</L>
<L>fful pale a-ryst &amp; dreseth here to wende</L>
<L N="266">ffor weel sche seeth there is non o&thorn;er ende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Allas no wondir is it &thorn;ow sche wepte</L>
<L>That schal be sent in-to straunge nacioun<NOTE PLACE="marg">[altered]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor frendys that so tenderely here kepte</L>
<L N="270">And to ben boundyn vndyr subieccyoun</L>
<L>Of on sche knowyth not hese condicioun</L>
<L>Housbondis ben alle goode &amp; han been &yogh;ore</L>
<L N="273">That knowyn wyuys I dar sey &yogh;ow no moore</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffadyr sche seyde &thorn;yn wrechede chyld Custaunce<MILESTONE N="198a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Thi &yogh;onge dou&yogh;ty fosterede vp so softe</L>
<L>And &yogh;e myn modyr myn souereyn plesaunce</L>
<L N="277">Ouer alle thynge out take cryst on lofte</L>
<L>Custaunce &yogh;ore child hire recomaundyth ofte</L>
<L>Vn-to &yogh;oure grace for I schal to surrye</L>
<L N="280">Ne schal I neuere sen &yogh;ow more with eye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Allas vn-to &thorn;e barbre nacioun</L>
<L>I muste anon sithe &thorn;at it is &yogh;oure wille</L>
<L>But cryst &thorn;at starf for our redempcyoun</L>
<L N="284">So &yogh;eue me grace hese hestis to fulfylle</L>
<L>I wreche woman no fors thow I spille</L>
<L>Wemen are bore to thraldam &amp; penaunce</L>
<L N="287">And to ben vndyr manys gouernaunce
<PB REF="00000155.tif" N="139"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I trowe at troye whan pirrus brak &thorn;e wal</L>
<L>Or ylion brende at thebes the cetee</L>
<L>Nat rome for &thorn;e harm &thorn;orw hanybal</L>
<L N="291">That romaynys han enqueschid tymys three</L>
<L>Nas herd swich tendere wepyng for pete</L>
<L>As in the chaumbere was for here departynge</L>
<L N="294">But forth sche muste / where so sche wepe or synge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O fyrste moeuyng crewel fyrmament</L>
<L>With thi dyurnal which &thorn;at croudist ay</L>
<L>And hurlyst al from est til occident</L>
<L N="298">That naturally wolde holde a-no&thorn;er way</L>
<L>Thi croudyng set &thorn;e heuene in swich aray</L>
<L>At &thorn;e begynynge of this ferse viage</L>
<L N="301">That crewel mars hath slaye &thorn;is maryage</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Infortunat ascendent tortuous</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;e lord is helpeles falle allas</L>
<L>Out of hese angels in-to &thorn;e derkeste hous</L>
<L N="305">O mars o ata&yogh;er as in this cas</L>
<L>O febele mone vn-happi ben thi pas</L>
<L>Thow knyttist &thorn;e &thorn;ere &thorn;at art not reseyuyd</L>
<L N="308">There &thorn;ow were wel from thens art thow weyuyd</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Inprudent Emperour of Rome allas<MILESTONE N="198b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Whas &thorn;ere no philisophere in al thyn toun</L>
<L>Is no tyme bet &thorn;an o&thorn;er in swich cas</L>
<L N="312">Of viage is &thorn;ere non eleccioun</L>
<L>And namely to folk of high condicioun</L>
<L>Nat whan a rote is of a burthe I-knowe</L>
<L N="315">Allas we ben to lewede &amp; to slowe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To schip is brou&yogh;t this woful fayre mayde</L>
<L>Solempnely with euery circumstaunce</L>
<L>Now Ihesu crist be with &yogh;ow alle sche seide<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>altered from</I> sende]</NOTE></L>
<L N="319">There is namore but fare wel fayre Custaunce
<PB REF="00000156.tif" N="140"></L>
<L>Sche peynyth here to make good cuntenaunce</L>
<L>And forth I lete here sayle in this manere</L>
<L N="322">And turne I wele a-geyn to myn matere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The modyr of the soudon welle of vices</L>
<L>Espyed hath here sonys pleyn entente</L>
<L>How he wolde lete his olde sacrifises</L>
<L N="326">And ry&yogh;t a-non sche for here conseyl sente</L>
<L>And they be come to knowe what sche mente</L>
<L>And whan assembelede were &thorn;e folk en feere</L>
<L N="329">Sche sette here doun &amp; seyde as &yogh;e schal here</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lordys quod sche &yogh;e heryn euerychon</L>
<L>How &thorn;at myn sone in poynt is for to lete</L>
<L>The holy lawis of oure alkaron</L>
<L N="333">&YOGH;euen be goddys message Makomete</L>
<L>But on a wow to grete god I heete</L>
<L>The lyf schal ra&thorn;ere out of myn body sterte</L>
<L N="336">On makometes lawe out of myn herte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>What schulde vs tydyn of this newe lawe</L>
<L>But thraldam to oure bodyis &amp; penaunce</L>
<L>And aftyr in helle for to be drawe</L>
<L N="340">ffor we reneyede mahoun oure creaunce</L>
<L>But lordis wele &yogh;e makyn a suraunce</L>
<L>As I schal seyn assentynge to myn lore</L>
<L N="343">And I schal make vs saf for euere more</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>They sworyn &amp; assentyn euery man<MILESTONE N="199a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To lyue with hyre &amp; deye &amp; by here stonde</L>
<L>And eueryche in &thorn;e beste wyse sche can</L>
<L N="347">To strenthe here schal alle here frendis fonde</L>
<L>And sche hath this empryse take on honde</L>
<L>Whiche &yogh;e schal here that I schal deuyse</L>
<L N="350">An[d] to hem alle sche spak ryth in &thorn;is wyse
<PB REF="00000157.tif" N="141"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>We schul fyrst feyne vs cristene-dam to take</L>
<L>Cold watyr schal nat greue vs but a lite</L>
<L>And I schal swich a feste &amp; reuel make</L>
<L N="354">That as I trowe I schal the soudon quyte</L>
<L>ffor thow hese wyf be crystenede neuere so whyte</L>
<L>Sche schal han neede to wasche a-wey the reede</L>
<L N="357">Thow sche a funt ful of watyr with here leede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O soudonesse roote of iniquite</L>
<L>Virago thow semiame the secunde</L>
<L>O serpent vndyr femynynyte</L>
<L N="361">Lyk to the serpent deepe in helle I-bounde</L>
<L>O feynede woman al that may conffounde</L>
<L>Vertu &amp; innocence thour thyn maleyce</L>
<L N="364">Is bred in &thorn;e / as nest in euery vice</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O satan enuyous syn thilke day</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou were chasede &thorn;our oure erytage</L>
<L>Wel knowyst &thorn;ou to wemen &thorn;e elde way</L>
<L N="368">Thow madist eua brynge vs in seruage</L>
<L>Thow wilt for-don this cristene maryage</L>
<L>Thyn Instreument so weyleawey the whyle</L>
<L N="371">Makyst &thorn;ou of wemen wan &thorn;ou wit begile</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This soudonesse whom I &thorn;us blame &amp; warye</L>
<L>Let pryuyly hire conseyl gon here way</L>
<L>What schulde I in this tale lengere tarye</L>
<L N="375">Sche rydith to &thorn;e soudan on a day</L>
<L>And seyde he wolde receyue hire lay</L>
<L>And cristendom of prestis hondis fonge</L>
<L N="378">Repentynge hire sche hethene was so longe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Be-sekynge hem<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>altered from</I> here]</NOTE> to don here &thorn;at honour<MILESTONE N="199b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That sche muste haue &thorn;e crystene folk to feste</L>
<L>To plesyn hem I wele don myn labour</L>
<L N="382">The soudon seyth I wele don at &yogh;oure heste
<PB REF="00000158.tif" N="142"></L>
<L>And kenelynge thankyth here of &thorn;at requeste</L>
<L>So glad he was he nyste what to seye</L>
<L N="385">Sche kyste here sone / &amp; hom sche goth here weye</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="2" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[PART II.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Aryuede ben these crystene men to londe</L>
<L>In surrey with a gret solempne route</L>
<L>And hastiliche &thorn;is soudan sente hese sonde</L>
<L N="389">ffyrst to hese modir &amp; al hese regne a-boute</L>
<L>And seyde hese wyf was comyn out of doute</L>
<L>And preyede hire to ryde a-&yogh;en &thorn;e quene</L>
<L N="392">The honour of hese regne to sustene</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gret was &thorn;e pres &amp; riche was tharay</L>
<L>Of surreynys &amp; romeynys met in fere</L>
<L>The modyr of the soudan ryche &amp; gay</L>
<L N="396">Receyuyth hire with also glad a chere</L>
<L>As any modir my&yogh;te hire dou&yogh;tyr dere</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e nexte sete &thorn;ere be syde</L>
<L N="399">A softe pas solempnely &thorn;ey ryde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Noght trowe I &thorn;e triumphe of Iulius</L>
<L>Of which &thorn;at lucan makyth swich a bost</L>
<L>Was royallere ne more curyous</L>
<L N="403">&thorn;an was thasemble of &thorn;is blysful ost</L>
<L>But &thorn;is scorpioun &thorn;is wekede gost</L>
<L>The soudonesse for al hyre flaterynge</L>
<L N="406">Caste vndyr this ful mortali to stynge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The soudan comyth hym self sone aftyr this</L>
<L>So royali &thorn;at wondir is to telle</L>
<L>He wolcomyth hire with al ioye &amp; blys</L>
<L N="410">And &thorn;us in merthe &amp; ioye I lete hem dwelle
<PB REF="00000159.tif" N="143"></L>
<L>The freut of this matiere is &thorn;at I telle</L>
<L>Whan tyme cam men thou&yogh;te it for &thorn;e beste</L>
<L N="413">That reuel stynte &amp; men gone to here reste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The tyme cam this olde soudonesse<MILESTONE N="200a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Ordeynyd hath this feste of which I telle</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e feste cristene folk hym dresse</L>
<L N="417">In general &yogh;e bothe &yogh;ynge &amp; olde</L>
<L>Here may men feste &amp; rialte be-holde</L>
<L>And deynteis mo &thorn;an I can &yogh;ow deuyse</L>
<L N="420">But al to dere they bou&yogh;te it er they ryse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O sodeyn wo that euere art successour</L>
<L>To wordely blysse spreynt with bittyrnesse</L>
<L>Thende of the ioye of oure wordely labour</L>
<L N="424">Who occupiet the fyn of oure gladnesse</L>
<L>Herkene &thorn;is conseyl for thyn sekyrnesse</L>
<L>Vp-on thyn glade day haue in thyn mynde</L>
<L N="427">The onwar wo or harm that comyth be-hynde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor schortely for to tellyn at on word</L>
<L>The soudon &amp; the crystene euerychone</L>
<L>Ben al to-hewe &amp; stikid at the bord</L>
<L N="431">But it were only dame custaunce a-lone</L>
<L>This olde soudanesse cursede crone</L>
<L>Hath with here frendis don this curssede dede</L>
<L N="434">ffor sche here selue wolde at the cuntre lede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ne &thorn;ere was surreyn non that was conuertid</L>
<L>That of the conseyl of the soudon wot</L>
<L>That he was hewe er that he a-sterted</L>
<L N="438">And custaunce han they take a-non fot hot</L>
<L>And in a schip al stereles god wot</L>
<L>They han hire set &amp; bidde hire lerne sayle</L>
<L N="441">Out of surrie a-geyn ward to ytayle
<PB REF="00000160.tif" N="144"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A serteyn trosor that sche the&thorn;er ladde</L>
<L>And soth to sayn vitayle gret plente</L>
<L>They han hyre &yogh;euyn &amp; clothis ech sche hadde</L>
<L N="445">And forth sche saylyth in the salte see</L>
<L>O myn custaunce ful of benyngnete</L>
<L>O emperouris dou&yogh;tyr &yogh;onge dere</L>
<L N="448">He that is lord of fortune be thi stere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche blysseth hire &amp; with ful pitous voys<MILESTONE N="200b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>On to the Croys of crist thus seyde sche</L>
<L>O cler o wilful auter holy cros</L>
<L N="452">Reed of the lambis blod ful of pite</L>
<L>That wesch &thorn;e world from old iniquite</L>
<L>Me from the fend &amp; from hese clawis kepe</L>
<L N="455">That day &thorn;at I schal drenchyn in &thorn;e deepe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Victorious tre protexioun of trewe</L>
<L>That only worthy were for to bere</L>
<L>The kyng of heuene withese woundis newe</L>
<L N="459">The white lomb that hurt was wyt a spere</L>
<L>fflemere of feendis out of hym &amp; hire</L>
<L>On which thyn lyfis feythfully extenden</L>
<L N="462">Me kep &amp; &yogh;if me my&yogh;t myn lyf to a-menden</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>&YOGH;eerys &amp; dayis fleth this creature</L>
<L>Torw-out the strem of grece in-to strayte</L>
<L>Of marrok whiche that was hese auenture</L>
<L N="466">On manye a sory Mel now may &yogh;e beyte</L>
<L>Aftyr hire deth ful ofte may sche wayte</L>
<L>Er than &thorn;e wylde wawys wole here dryue</L>
<L N="469">Vn-to the place there sche schal a-ryue</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Men my&yogh;tyn axsyn whi sche was not slayn</L>
<L>Ek at the feste ho my&yogh;te hire body saue</L>
<L>And I answere to that demaunde a-gayn</L>
<L N="473">Ho sauede daniel in &thorn;e orybele caue
<PB REF="00000161.tif" N="145"></L>
<L>There euery with saue he maystyr &amp; knave</L>
<L>Was with the lyoun frete er he a-sterte</L>
<L N="476">Non wigh but god &thorn;at he bar in hese herte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>God lyste to schewe his wondyrful merakele</L>
<L>In hire for we schud sen hise my&yogh;ty werkys</L>
<L>Cryst which &thorn;at is / to euery harm tryakele</L>
<L N="480">Be serteyn mene oftyn as knowyn klerkes</L>
<L>Doth thyng to serteyn ende &thorn;at ful derk is</L>
<L>To mannys wit that for oure ignoraunce</L>
<L N="483">Ne kunne not knowe hese prudent puruyaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now sythe sche was not at the feste slawee<MILESTONE N="201a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Who kepte hyre from the drenchynge in &thorn;e see</L>
<L>Who kepte Ionas in the fyschis mawee</L>
<L N="487">Thil he was spoutid out at niniuee</L>
<L>Wel may men knowe it was no wi&yogh;t but he</L>
<L>That kepte &thorn;e peple Ebrayk from here drenchynge</L>
<L N="490">With dreye feet thorw-out &thorn;e se passynge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who bad the foure spirytis of tempest</L>
<L>That power han tanoyen lond &amp; se</L>
<L>Bothe north &amp; south &amp; also west &amp; est</L>
<L N="494">Anoyeth ney&thorn;er se lond ne tree</L>
<L>Sothly the comaundour was hee</L>
<L>That from the tempest ay<NOTE PLACE="marg">[altered]</NOTE> this<NOTE PLACE="marg">[altered]</NOTE> woman kepte</L>
<L N="497">As wel whan sche wok as whan sche slepte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Where my&yogh;te this woman mete or drynk haue</L>
<L>Thre &yogh;er &amp; more how lastyth hire vitayle</L>
<L>Ho fedde &thorn;e egipcien marye in &thorn;e caue</L>
<L N="501">Or in desert no wi&yogh;t but crist sauns fayle</L>
<L>ffyue thousent folk it was a gret meruayle</L>
<L>With louys fyue &amp; fyschis too to feede</L>
<L N="504">God sente hese foysoun at here moste neede
<PB REF="00000162.tif" N="146"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche dryuyth forth in-to oure occian</L>
<L>Thour-out oure wilde see til at &thorn;e laste</L>
<L>Vndyr an hold &thorn;at nemenyn I ne can</L>
<L N="508">ffor in northumbyrlond the wawis hire caste</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e se hire schip stekede so faste</L>
<L>That &thorn;ens ne wolde it not of al a tide</L>
<L N="511">The wyl of here was &thorn;at sche schulde a-byde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The constabele of &thorn;e Castel doun is fare</L>
<L>To sen &thorn;is wrak &amp; al &thorn;e schip he sou&yogh;te</L>
<L>And fond &thorn;is wery woman ful of care</L>
<L N="515">He fond also &thorn;e tresore &thorn;at sche brou&yogh;te</L>
<L>In hyre langage mercy sche be-sou&yogh;te</L>
<L>The lyf out of hire body to twynne</L>
<L N="518">Hire to delyuere of woo &thorn;at sche was inne</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A maner latyn corupt was hire speche<MILESTONE N="201b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But algatis &thorn;erbi was sche vndir-stonde</L>
<L>The Constabele whan hym lyste no lengere seche</L>
<L N="522">This woful woman brou&yogh;te he to the londe</L>
<L>Sche knelyth doun &amp; thankyth godis sonde</L>
<L>But what sche was sche durste no man seye</L>
<L N="525">ffor foul ne fayr thow &thorn;at sche schulde deye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche seyde sche was so masede in the see</L>
<L>That sche forgat hire mynde by hyre<NOTE PLACE="marg">[altered]</NOTE> trouthe</L>
<L>The cunstabele hath of hire gret pite</L>
<L N="529">And ek his wif that &thorn;ey wepe for routhe</L>
<L>Sche was so diligent with-outyn slouthe</L>
<L>To serue &amp; plese eueryche in &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="532">That alle hyre louyn &thorn;at lokyn in hyre face</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This constabil &amp; dame hermengylt his wyf</L>
<L>Were payenys in &thorn;at cuntrey euery where</L>
<L>But Ermengylt louede hire ry&yogh;t as hire lyf</L>
<L N="536">And Custaunce hath so longe soiurnede &thorn;ere
<PB REF="00000163.tif" N="147"></L>
<L>In orisounys with manye a bittere tere</L>
<L>Til Ihesu hath conuertede &thorn;our hese grace</L>
<L N="539">Dame Ermengilt Constabellesse of &thorn;at place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In al &thorn;at lond no cristene durste at route</L>
<L>Alle cristen folk ben fled from &thorn;at cuntre</L>
<L>Thour poynyms &thorn;at conqueredyn al a-boute</L>
<L N="543">The plagis of the north &amp; se</L>
<L>To walis fledde &thorn;e cristianyte</L>
<L>Of olde brytunys dwellynge in &thorn;is yle</L>
<L N="546">There was hire refeut for the mene while</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But &yogh;it nere cristene britounys so exiled</L>
<L>&thorn;at &thorn;ere nere some &thorn;at in hire priuite</L>
<L>Honourede crist &amp; hethene folk begilede</L>
<L N="550">And n[i]gh &thorn;e castel<NOTE PLACE="marg">[altered]</NOTE> swich<NOTE PLACE="marg">[altered]</NOTE> &thorn;ere dweltyn thre</L>
<L>That on of hem was blynd &amp; my&yogh;te not se</L>
<L>But it were with &thorn;e ilke eyen of hise mynde</L>
<L N="553">Wit[h] whiche men sen aftyr &thorn;at &thorn;ey ben blynde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Bry&yogh;t was &thorn;e sune as in &thorn;at someris day<MILESTONE N="202a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>ffor which &thorn;e Constabel &amp; hese wyf also</L>
<L>And custaunce hath I-take &thorn;e ry&yogh;te way</L>
<L N="557">Toward &thorn;e se a furlong wey or to</L>
<L>To pleyen &amp; to romyn too &amp; fro</L>
<L>And in hire walk &thorn;is blynde man &thorn;ey mette</L>
<L N="560">Crokid &amp; old with eyen faste I-schette</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In name of cryst cryede &thorn;is blynde Erytoun</L>
<L>Dame Hermengelt &yogh;if me myn sy&yogh;t a-geyn</L>
<L>This lady wex a-freyed of &thorn;e soun</L>
<L N="564">Lest &thorn;at hire husbonde schortly for [to] seyn</L>
<L>Wolde hire for ihesu crist han slayn</L>
<L>Til Custaunce made hire bold &amp; bad hire for to werche<NOTE PLACE="marg">[altered]</NOTE></L>
<L N="567">The wil of crist as doughtyr of hise cherche
<PB REF="00000164.tif" N="148"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The Constabele wex a-baschid of that sy&yogh;t</L>
<L>And seyde what amounty[t]h al &thorn;is fare</L>
<L>Custaunce answere syre it is cristis my&yogh;t</L>
<L N="571">That helpith folk out of &thorn;e fendis snare</L>
<L>And so fer forth sche gan oure lay declare</L>
<L>That sche &thorn;e Constabele er &thorn;an it was eue</L>
<L N="574">Conuertid &amp; on cryst made hym bileue</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Constabele was no &thorn;yng lord of &thorn;is place</L>
<L>Of whiche I speke &thorn;ere he constaunce fond</L>
<L>But kepte it strongely manye a wynteris space</L>
<L N="578">Vndir alla kyng of al northhumbir londe</L>
<L>That was ful wys &amp; worthi of hese honde</L>
<L>A-geyn &thorn;e skottis as men may wel here</L>
<L N="581">But turne I wele a-gen to myn matyere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Satan &thorn;at euere wayth vs to be-gyle</L>
<L>Saugh of Custaunce al &thorn;e perfeccioun</L>
<L>And caste a-non how he my&yogh;te quite hire while</L>
<L N="585">And made a &yogh;ong kn[y]ght &thorn;at dwellede in &thorn;at toun</L>
<L>Loue hire so hote of foul affeccioun</L>
<L>That verayly hym thou&yogh;te he schulde spille</L>
<L N="588">But he of hire my&yogh;te onys haue hese wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He wowyth hire but it a-uaylyth nou&yogh;t<MILESTONE N="202b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Sche wolde don no synne be no weye</L>
<L>And for dispit he compassith in his thou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="592">To makyn hyre on schamful deth to deye</L>
<L>He waythith whan &thorn;e Constable is a-weye</L>
<L>And priui vp-on a ny&yogh;t he crepte</L>
<L N="595">In-to Hermengildis chaumbere whil sche slepte</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wery for-wakede in hire orysouns</L>
<L>Slepith custaunce and hemegild also</L>
<L>This kny&yogh;t &thorn;our satanys temptacions</L>
<L N="599">Al softeli is to &thorn;e bed I-go
<PB REF="00000165.tif" N="149"></L>
<L>And kitte &thorn;e throte of Hermegild a too</L>
<L>And leyde &thorn;e blodi knyf be dame Custaunce</L>
<L N="602">And wente his wey &thorn;ere god &yogh;yf hym myschaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sone aftyr comyth this Constabele hom ageyn</L>
<L>And ek .Alla. &thorn;at kyng was of &thorn;at lond /</L>
<L>And saw his wif dispitously I-slayn</L>
<L N="606">ffor which ful ofte he wepte &amp; wrong here hon[d]</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e bed &thorn;e blody knyf he fond</L>
<L>By dame Constance Allas what my&yogh;te sche seye</L>
<L N="609">ffor werray woo hire wit was al a-weye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To kyng alla was told &thorn;is tale Mischaunce</L>
<L>And ek &thorn;e tyme where &amp; in what wyse</L>
<L>That in a schyp was founde &thorn;is custaunce</L>
<L N="613">As here be-forn &thorn;at &yogh;e han herd deuyse</L>
<L>The kyngis herte of pete gan to gryse</L>
<L>Whan he saw so benygne a creature</L>
<L N="616">ffalle in desese &amp; in mysauenture</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor as &thorn;e lomb toward &thorn;e deth is brou&yogh;t</L>
<L>So stant this innocent by-fore &thorn;e kynge</L>
<L>This false kny&yogh;t that hath this tresoun wrought</L>
<L N="620">Beryth hire on honde &thorn;at sche hath don &thorn;is thynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">[altered]</NOTE></L>
<L>But natheles &thorn;ere was gret mornyng</L>
<L>A-mong the puple &amp; seyn &thorn;ey can not gesse</L>
<L N="623">That sche hadde don so gret a wekedenesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor they han seyn hire so vertuous<MILESTONE N="203a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And louynge hermengild ry&yogh;t as hire lyf</L>
<L>Of &thorn;is bar witnesse eueryche in that hous</L>
<L N="627">Saue he &thorn;at hermengelt slow with his knyf</L>
<L>This gentil kyng hath cau&yogh;t a gret motyf</L>
<L>Of this witnesse &amp; thoght he wolde enquire</L>
<L N="630">Deppere in this trouthe for to lere
<PB REF="00000166.tif" N="150"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Allas Custaunce &thorn;ou hast no chaumpioun</L>
<L>Ne fy&yogh;te canst &thorn;ou so weyle-awey</L>
<L>But he that starf for oure redempcioun</L>
<L N="634">And bond satan &amp; &yogh;it lyth &thorn;ere he lay</L>
<L>So be &thorn;eyn stronge champioun &thorn;is day</L>
<L>ffor but &yogh;if cryst opyn merakele kythe</L>
<L N="637">With-outyn gilt &thorn;ou schat ben slayn aswythe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Sche sette hire doun on kneis &amp; thus sche seyde</L>
<L>Inmortal god &thorn;at sauedist susanne</L>
<L>ffrom false blame &amp; &thorn;ou merciful mayde</L>
<L N="641">Marye I mene dou&yogh;tyr to seynt ann</L>
<L>By-forn hos child aungell synge osanne</L>
<L>If I be gilteles of this felonye</L>
<L N="644">Myn socour be for ellis schal I deye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Han &yogh;e nat seyn sumtyme a pale face</L>
<L>Among a pres of hym &thorn;at hath be lad</L>
<L>Toward hese deth where as he gat no grace</L>
<L N="648">And swich a colour in hese face hath had</L>
<L>Men my&yogh;te knowe hise face &thorn;at was be-stad</L>
<L>Amongis alle &thorn;e facis in &thorn;at route</L>
<L N="651">So stant custaunce &amp; lokyth hire a boute</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O queenys lyuynge in prosperite</L>
<L>Duchesses &amp; &yogh;e ladijs euerychone</L>
<L>Hauyth sum routhe of hire aduercite</L>
<L N="655">An emperouris dou&yogh;tyr stant a-lone</L>
<L>Sche hath no wy&yogh;t to whom to make hire mone</L>
<L>O blood royal &thorn;at standyst in &thorn;is drede<NOTE PLACE="marg">[altered]</NOTE></L>
<L N="658">ffer ben thyne frendis at thi grete nede</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This alla kyng hath swich compascioun<MILESTONE N="203b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>As gentyl herte is ful fyld of pite</L>
<L>That from hyse eyen ran the watyr doun</L>
<L N="662">Now hastyfliche do feche a bok quod he
<PB REF="00000167.tif" N="151"></L>
<L>And &yogh;if this kn[y]&yogh;t wele swere &thorn;at sche</L>
<L>This woman slow &yogh;it wele we vs auyse</L>
<L N="665">Hom &thorn;at we wele &thorn;at schal ben oure Iustyse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A brytoun bok wrytyn with euaungilis</L>
<L>Was fet in on this bok he swor a-non</L>
<L>Sche gilty was &amp; in the mene whilis</L>
<L N="669">An hand hym smot vp-on the nekke bon</L>
<L>That doun he fyl a-tonys as a ston</L>
<L>And bothe hise eyen broste vp on hise face</L>
<L N="672">In sy&yogh;te of euery body in &thorn;at place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>A woys was herd in general audience</L>
<L>And seyde &thorn;ou hast disclaunderede gilteles</L>
<L>The dou&yogh;tyr of holy cherche in high presence</L>
<L N="676">Thus hast &thorn;ou don &amp; &yogh;it I holde myn pees</L>
<L>Of this mervayle a-gast was al &thorn;e pres</L>
<L>As masede folk they stodyn euerychone</L>
<L N="679">ffor drede of wreche saue Custaunce allone</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gret was &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> dred &amp; ek &thorn;<SUP>e</SUP> repentaunce</L>
<L>Of hem &thorn;at han wrong suspecioun</L>
<L>Vp-on &thorn;is sely Innocent custaunce</L>
<L N="683">And for this myrakele in conclusioun</L>
<L>And by Custauncis mediacioun</L>
<L>The kyng &amp; manye a no&thorn;er in &thorn;at place</L>
<L N="686">Conuertede were thankid be godis grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This false kny&yogh;t was slayn for hise ontrouthe</L>
<L>Be Iugement of alla hastifly</L>
<L>And &yogh;it Custaustaunce hadde of hise deth routhe</L>
<L N="690">And aftyr this Ihesus<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Ihe]</NOTE> of hise mercy</L>
<L>Made alla weddyn solempnely</L>
<L>This holy maydyn &thorn;at is so bry&yogh;t &amp; scheene</L>
<L N="693">And &thorn;us hath Cryst mad Custaunce a queene
<PB REF="00000168.tif" N="152"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But who was woful &yogh;if I sc[h]al not lye<MILESTONE N="204a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of this weddyng but donegild &amp; no mo</L>
<L>The kyngis modir ful of tyrannye</L>
<L N="697">Hire thou&yogh;t hire curssede herte brast a to</L>
<L>Sche wolde not hire sone hadde don so</L>
<L>Hire thou&yogh;te a dispit &thorn;at he schulde take</L>
<L N="700">So straunge a creature vn-to hise make</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Me lyste not of &thorn;e chaf nor of &thorn;e stre</L>
<L>Makyn so long a tale as of &thorn;e corn</L>
<L>What sholde I telle of the royalte</L>
<L N="704">At mariage or wich cours goth be-forn</L>
<L>Who blowith in a trompe or in an horn</L>
<L>The freut of eueri tale is for to seye</L>
<L N="707">They ete &amp; drynke &amp; daunce &amp; synge &amp; pleye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thei gon to bedde as it was skele &amp; ry&yogh;t</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ow &thorn;at wiuys ben ful holye thyngis</L>
<L>They muste takyn in pacience at ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="711">Swiche manere of necessarijs as ben plesyngis</L>
<L>To folk &thorn;at han wedit hem with ryngis</L>
<L>And leyn a lityl here holynesse a-syde</L>
<L N="714">As for &thorn;e tyme it may non o&thorn;er be-tyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>On hire he gat a knave child a-non</L>
<L>And to a bischop &amp; his constabele ek</L>
<L>He tok hise wyf to kepe whan he is gon</L>
<L N="718">To skotlondeward hise fomen for to seke</L>
<L>Now fayre custaunce &thorn;at is so vmble &amp; meke</L>
<L>So longe is gon with childe til &thorn;at stille</L>
<L N="721">Sche halt hire chaumbere a-bydynge cristis wille</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The tyme is come a knaue child sche beere</L>
<L>Mauricyus at &thorn;e funtston &thorn;ey hym calle</L>
<L>This Constabele doth forth<NOTE PLACE="marg">[clepe <I>put at the side, later</I>]</NOTE> a massanger</L>
<L N="725">And wrot on-to his kyng &thorn;at clepid was alle
<PB REF="00000169.tif" N="153"></L>
<L>How &thorn;at this blisful tydyng is byfalle</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ere tydyngis spedful for to seye</L>
<L N="728">He taath &thorn;e lettere &amp; forth he goth hise weye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This massanger to don his auauntage<MILESTONE N="204b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;e kyngis modyr ridyth swythe</L>
<L>And saluyth hire ful fare in hyre langage</L>
<L N="732">Madame quod he &yogh;e may ben glad &amp; bly&thorn;e</L>
<L>And thankede god a hunderede thousent sythe</L>
<L>Myn lady quen hath child with-outyn doute</L>
<L N="735">To Ioye &amp; blysse to al &thorn;e regne a-boute</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Lo here &thorn;e letteris selede of &thorn;is thyng</L>
<L>That I mot bere with &thorn;e haste I may</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &yogh;e wele ou&yogh;t on-to &yogh;oure sone &thorn;e kyng</L>
<L N="739">I am &yogh;oure seruaunt bothe ny&yogh;t &amp; day</L>
<L>Donegild answerede as now at &thorn;is tyme nay</L>
<L>But here al nyght I wele &thorn;ou take &thorn;yn reste</L>
<L N="742">To morwe wele I seye &thorn;e what me leste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This massangere drank faste ale &amp; wyn</L>
<L>And stole were hise letteris priuyly</L>
<L>Out of his box whil he slepte as a swyn</L>
<L N="746">And countyrfetid was ful subtilly</L>
<L>Ano&thorn;er lettere wrou&yogh;t ful synfully<NOTE PLACE="marg">[altered]</NOTE></L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;e kyng direckt of this matere</L>
<L N="749">ffrom his Constabil as &yogh;e schal aftyr here</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The lettere spak &thorn;e quen delyuerede was</L>
<L>Of so orible &amp; fendlyche cryature</L>
<L>That in &thorn;e castel non so hardy was</L>
<L N="753">That ony while durste &thorn;ere endure</L>
<L>The modyr was an elf be nature</L>
<L>I-comyn by charmys or bi socerye</L>
<L N="756">And euery wy&yogh;t hath hire cumpanye
<PB REF="00000170.tif" N="154"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wo was this kyng whan he &thorn;is lettere hath seyn</L>
<L>But to no wy&yogh;t he tolde hise sorwis sore</L>
<L>But of hyse owene hand he wrot a-geyn</L>
<L N="760">Wolcome &thorn;e sonde of cryst for euere more</L>
<L>To me that am now lernede in &thorn;is lore</L>
<L>Lord wolcome be thyn lust &amp; &thorn;yn plesaunce</L>
<L N="763">Myn lust I putte al in thyn ordenaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Kepith this child al be it foul or fayr<MILESTONE N="205a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And ek myn wyf on-to myn hom comynge</L>
<L>Cryst whan hym lyste may sende me an eyr</L>
<L N="767">More agriable &thorn;an this to myn<NOTE PLACE="marg">[altered]</NOTE> lykynge<NOTE PLACE="marg">[altered]</NOTE></L>
<L>This lettere he selyth pryuyly wepynge</L>
<L>Whiche to &thorn;e massangere was take sone</L>
<L N="770">And forth he goth &thorn;ere is no more to done</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O Massanger fulfild of dronkenesse</L>
<L>Strong is thi breth thi lemys falteryn ay</L>
<L>And &thorn;ou be-wreyest alle sekere-nesse</L>
<L N="774">Thyn mynde is lorn &thorn;ou iangelist as a Iay</L>
<L>Thyn face is turnede in a newe aray</L>
<L>There dronkenesse regnyth in ony route</L>
<L N="777">There is no conseyl hid with-outyn doute</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O donegilt I haue non engelissh dygne</L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;yn maleys &amp; thi tyrannye</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore to &thorn;e fend I &thorn;e resigne</L>
<L N="781">Let hym endyte of thyn tratorye</L>
<L>ffy mannyssh fy / o nay by god I lye</L>
<L>ffy fendelyche spirit for I dar wel telle</L>
<L N="784">Thow &thorn;ow here walke thyn spyrit is in helle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Massanger comyth from &thorn;e kyng a-geyn</L>
<L>And at &thorn;e kyngis moderis court he lyghte</L>
<L>And sche was of &thorn;e massenger ful fayn</L>
<L N="788">And plesede hym in al &thorn;at euere sche my&yogh;te
<PB REF="00000171.tif" N="155"></L>
<L>He drank &amp; wel hise gerdyl vndyr py&yogh;t</L>
<L>He slepith &amp; he snortith in hise gyse</L>
<L N="791">Al ny&yogh;t tyl &thorn;e sunne gan a-ryse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Eft were hise letterys stolyn euerychon</L>
<L>And counterfetid letterys in &thorn;is wyse</L>
<L>The kyng comaundyth hise constablis a-non</L>
<L N="795">Vp peyne of hangynge &amp; heigh Iuyse</L>
<L>That he ne schulde suffere in no wyse</L>
<L>Custaunce in whith<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>altered from</I> whiche]</NOTE> his regne for tabyde</L>
<L N="798">Thre dayis &amp; a quartyr of a tide</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But in &thorn;e same schip as he hire fond<MILESTONE N="205b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Hire &amp; hyr &yogh;enge sone &amp; al hire geere</L>
<L>He schulde putte &amp; croude from &thorn;e lond</L>
<L N="802">And charge hire &thorn;at sche neuere eft come &thorn;ere</L>
<L>O myn custaunce wel may &thorn;y gost haue fere</L>
<L>And slepynge in &thorn;yn drem han penaunce</L>
<L N="805">Whan donegilt caste al &thorn;is ordenaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This messenger on morwe he wok</L>
<L>On-to &thorn;e castel holt &thorn;e neste wey</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e constabele he &thorn;e lettere tok</L>
<L N="809">And whan &thorn;at he &thorn;is pitous lettere say</L>
<L>fful ofte he seyde allas &amp; weyle-away</L>
<L>Lord crist how may &thorn;is world endure</L>
<L N="812">So ful of synne is manye a cryature</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O my&yogh;ti god &yogh;if &thorn;at it be &thorn;yn wille</L>
<L>Sith &thorn;ou art ry&yogh;tful Iuge how may &thorn;is be</L>
<L>That &thorn;ou wit suffere innocentis to spille</L>
<L N="816">And wekede folk regnyn in prosperite</L>
<L>O goode Custaunce allas so wo is me</L>
<L>&thorn;at I mote be &thorn;yn turmentour or deye</L>
<L N="819">On schamys deth &thorn;ere is non o&thorn;er weye
<PB REF="00000172.tif" N="156"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wepyn bothe &yogh;ynge &amp; olde in &thorn;at place</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;e kyng his cursede letere sente</L>
<L>And Custaunce with a dedly pale face</L>
<L N="823">The forte day toward hire schip sche wente</L>
<L>But natheles sche takyth in good entente</L>
<L>The wil of crist &amp; knelynge on &thorn;e stronde</L>
<L N="826">Sche seyde lord ay wolcome be &thorn;yn sonde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He &thorn;at me kepte from &thorn;e false blame</L>
<L>Whil I was on &thorn;e lond a-mongis &yogh;ow</L>
<L>He can me kepe from harm &amp; ek from schame</L>
<L N="830">In &thorn;e salte se al &thorn;ow I se nat how</L>
<L>As strong as euere he was he is now</L>
<L>In hym troste I &amp; hyse modyr dere</L>
<L N="833">That is to me myn sayl &amp; ek myn stere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Hyre lytyl child lay wepynge in hire arm<MILESTONE N="206a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And knelynge pitously to hym sche seyde</L>
<L>Pes lityl sone I wele don &thorn;e non harm</L>
<L N="837">With &thorn;at hire couerchif ouer hire hed sche bryde</L>
<L>And ouer hise lityl eyen sche it leyd</L>
<L>And in hyre arm sche lullede it ful faste</L>
<L N="840">And in-to heuene hyre eyen vp sche caste</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Modyr quod sche &amp; mayde / bry&yogh;te marye</L>
<L>Soth is &thorn;at &thorn;our wemanys eggement</L>
<L>Man kynde was lorn &amp; dampnede for to deye</L>
<L N="844">ffor wich &thorn;yn chyld was on a cros I-ret</L>
<L>Thi blysful eyen saw al his turment</L>
<L>Thanne is &thorn;ere non comparisoun be-twene</L>
<L N="847">Thi wo &amp; any wo / man may sustene</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Thow saw &thorn;yn child slawyn be-fore &thorn;yn eyen</L>
<L>And &yogh;it now lyuyth my lityl child parfey</L>
<L>Now lady bry&yogh;t to whom alle folk now cryen</L>
<L N="851">Thow glorye of womanhede fayre may
<PB REF="00000173.tif" N="157"></L>
<L>Thow hauene of refut bry&yogh;te sterre of day</L>
<L>Rewe on myn child &thorn;at of &thorn;yn gentillesse</L>
<L N="854">Rewist on euery reuful in destresse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O lityl child allas what is &thorn;yn gilt</L>
<L>That neuere wroughtist synne as &yogh;it parde</L>
<L>Whi wolde thyn harde fadyr han &thorn;e spilt</L>
<L N="858">O mercy dere constabele quod sche</L>
<L>As lat myn lytil child dwelle here with &thorn;e</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;ou darst not sauyn hym from blame</L>
<L N="861">So kysse hym onys in hese faderys name</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Therwith sche lokith bakward to &thorn;e londe</L>
<L>And seyde farewe[l] housbonde routheles</L>
<L>And vp sche rist &amp; walkyth doun &thorn;e stronde</L>
<L N="865">Toward &thorn;e schip here folwyth al &thorn;e pres</L>
<L>And euere sche preyeth hire child to holde hise pes</L>
<L>And takyth hire leue &amp; with an holy entente</L>
<L N="868">Sche blysseth hire &amp; in-to schip sche wente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vitaylid was &thorn;e schip it is no drede<MILESTONE N="206b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Habundaunt for hyre ful longe space</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ere necessaryis &thorn;at schuldyn nede</L>
<L N="872">Sche hadde I-now haryed be godis grace</L>
<L>ffor wynd &amp; wedyr al-my&yogh;ty god purchase</L>
<L>And brynge hire hom I can no betere seye</L>
<L N="875">But in &thorn;e se sche dryuyth forth hire weye</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3" TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[PART III.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Alla &thorn;e kyng comyth hom soone aftyr &thorn;is</L>
<L>On-to &thorn;e Castel whiche I tolde</L>
<L>And axsith where &thorn;at his wif &amp; his child is</L>
<L N="879">The Constabele gan a-boute hise herte colde
<PB REF="00000174.tif" N="15"></L>
<L>And pleynly al &thorn;e manere hym tolde</L>
<L>As &yogh;e han herd I can telle it no bettre</L>
<L N="882">As schewith &thorn;e kyng his sel &amp; hise lettere</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And seyde lord as &yogh;e comaundede me</L>
<L>Vp peyne of deth so haue I do serteyn</L>
<L>This massanger turmentid was tyl he</L>
<L N="886">Moste beknowe &amp; telle plat &amp; pleyn</L>
<L>ffrom ny&yogh;t to ny&yogh;t what place he hadde leyn</L>
<L>And &thorn;us by wit &amp; subtyl Inquyrynge</L>
<L N="889">Ymagined was bi hom &thorn;is harm gan sprynge</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The hand was knowe &thorn;at &thorn;e lettere wrot</L>
<L>And al &thorn;e venym of &thorn;is cursede dede</L>
<L>But in what wise serteynli I not</L>
<L N="893">Theffect is &thorn;is &thorn;at Alla out of drede</L>
<L>His modyr slow &thorn;at may men pleynly rede</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;at sche traytour was to hire legiaunce</L>
<L N="896">Thus endyth donegild with myschaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The sorwe &thorn;at &thorn;is alla ny&yogh;t &amp; day</L>
<L>Makith for his wif &amp; hise child also</L>
<L>Ther is no tunge &thorn;at it telle may</L>
<L N="900">But now wolde I on-to Custaunce go</L>
<L>That fletyth in &thorn;e se in peyne &amp; wo</L>
<L>ffyue &yogh;er &amp; more as lykede cristis sonde</L>
<L N="903">Er &thorn;at hir schip aprochede to &thorn;e londe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Vndyr an hethene castel at &thorn;e laste<MILESTONE N="207a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Of which &thorn;e name in myn tixt not I fynde</L>
<L>Custaunce &amp; ek hire child &thorn;e se vp caste</L>
<L N="907">Almy&yogh;ty god &thorn;at sawith al mankynde</L>
<L>Haue on custaunce &amp; of hire child sum mynde</L>
<L>that is fallyn in hethene hand eft sone</L>
<L N="910">In poynt to spylle as I schal telle &yogh;ow sone
<PB REF="00000175.tif" N="159"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Doun from &thorn;e castel comyth &thorn;ere manye a wy&yogh;t</L>
<L>To gauryn on &thorn;is wy&yogh;t &amp; on custaunce</L>
<L>But schortly from &thorn;e castel on a ny&yogh;t</L>
<L N="914">The lordis styward god &yogh;eue hym myschaunce</L>
<L>A thef that hadde reneyed oure cre-aunce</L>
<L>Cam in-to &thorn;e schip alone &amp; seyde he schulde</L>
<L N="917">Hire leman be whe&thorn;er sche wolde or nolde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Wo was &thorn;e wrechede woman &thorn;o be-gon</L>
<L>Hire child cryed &amp; sche cryede pitously</L>
<L>Blysful marye halp hyre ry&yogh;t a-non</L>
<L N="921">ffor with hire strogelyng wel &amp; my&yogh;tyly</L>
<L>The thef fel ouyr bord al sodeynly</L>
<L>And in &thorn;e se he dreynte for veniaunce</L>
<L N="924">And &thorn;us hath cryst onwemmede kept custaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>O foule lust of luxurye lo thyn ende</L>
<L>Not only &thorn;at &thorn;ou feyntist manys mynde</L>
<L>But verayly &thorn;ou wilt hise body schende</L>
<L N="928">Thende of &thorn;y werk or of &thorn;ynne lustis blynde</L>
<L>Is compleynynge how manyon may men fynde</L>
<L>That not for werk but only &thorn;e entente</L>
<L N="931">To don &thorn;is synne ben owthir slayn or schente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>How may &thorn;is wayke woman han &thorn;is strenthe</L>
<L>Hire to defende a-&yogh;en &thorn;is Renegat</L>
<L>O golyas vnmesurabe of lenthe</L>
<L N="935">How my&yogh;te dauid make &thorn;e so maat</L>
<L>So &yogh;ong &amp; of armeure so desolat</L>
<L>How durste he loke vp-on &thorn;yn dredful face</L>
<L N="938">Wel may men sen it was but godis grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Ho &yogh;af Iudyth corage or hardynesse<MILESTONE N="207b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To slen hym Olofernus in hise tente</L>
<L>And to delyueryn out of wrechedenesse</L>
<L N="942">The peple of god I sey for &thorn;is entente
<PB REF="00000176.tif" N="160"></L>
<L>But ry&yogh;t as god spyrit of vigour sente</L>
<L>To hym &amp; sauede hym from myschaunce</L>
<L N="945">So sente vigour &amp; my&yogh;t to Custaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>fforth goth the schip &thorn;our-out &thorn;e narwe mouth</L>
<L>Of Iubaltare / and Cepte dryuynge ay</L>
<L>Sumtyme west &amp; sumtyme north &amp; south</L>
<L N="949">And sumtyme est ful many a wery day</L>
<L>Til Cristis modyr blyssede be sche ay</L>
<L>Hath schapyn &thorn;our hire endeles goodnesse</L>
<L N="952">To make an ende of al hire heuynesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now lat vs stynte of Custaunce but a trowe</L>
<L>And speke we of &thorn;e romayn Emperour</L>
<L>That out of surry hath bi letterys knowe</L>
<L N="956">The slauthe of Cristene folk &amp; dishonoure<NOTE PLACE="marg">[? eure]</NOTE></L>
<L>Don to his dou&yogh;tyr by a fals traytoure</L>
<L>I mene &thorn;e wikkede cursede soudonesse</L>
<L N="959">That at &thorn;e feste let sle bo&thorn;e more &amp; lesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor which &thorn;is emperour hath sent a-nor</L>
<L>His senatour with royal ordenaunce</L>
<L>And o&thorn;ere lordis god wot many on</L>
<L N="963">On surryens to take veniaunce</L>
<L>They brenne &amp; slen &amp; brynge hem to myschaunce</L>
<L>fful manyaday but schortly &thorn;is is &thorn;e ende</L>
<L N="966">Homward to rome &thorn;ey schapyn hem to wende</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This senatour repayreth wictorye</L>
<L>To romeward saylynge ful ryalye</L>
<L>And mette &thorn;e schyp dryuynge as seyth &thorn;e story</L>
<L N="970">In which Custaunce sit pitously</L>
<L>No &thorn;yng knewe he what sche was ne why</L>
<L>Sche was in swich a-ray / ne sche wolde seye</L>
<L N="973">Of hyre estat &thorn;ow sche schulde deye
<PB REF="00000177.tif" N="161"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>He bryngith hire to rome &amp; to hise wyf<MILESTONE N="208a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>He &yogh;af hire &amp; hire &yogh;onge sone also</L>
<L>And with &thorn;e senatour sche ledde hire lyf</L>
<L N="977">Thus can oure lady bryngyn out of wo</L>
<L>Woful custaunce &amp; manye a no&thorn;er mo</L>
<L>And long tyme dwellede sche in &thorn;at plase</L>
<L N="980">In holye werkys euere as was hyre grace</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This senatourys wyf hyre aunte was</L>
<L>But for al &thorn;at sche knew hyre neuere &thorn;e more</L>
<L>I wele no lengere taryen in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L N="984">But to kyng alla which I spak of &yogh;ore</L>
<L>That for hise wyf wepede &amp; syghede sore</L>
<L>I wele retorne &amp; lete I wele Custaunce</L>
<L>Vndyr &thorn;e senatourrys gouernaunce<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<I>This stanza is repeated in the MS. See the second version on p.</I> 133 <I>above</I>]</NOTE></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Kyng Alla wich &thorn;at hadde hise modyr slayn</L>
<L>Vp-on a day fil In swich repentaunce</L>
<L>That &yogh;if I schortely schulde telle &amp; playn</L>
<L N="991">To rome he comyth to receyue hese penaunce</L>
<L>And putte hym in &thorn;e popis ordenaunce</L>
<L>In high &amp; logh &amp; Ihesu crist be-sou&yogh;te</L>
<L N="994">ffor&yogh;eue hise wikke werkis &thorn;at he wrou&yogh;te</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The fame a-non &thorn;our rome toun is born</L>
<L>How Alla kyng schal come in pilgrymage</L>
<L>By herberiourys &thorn;at wentyn here be-forn</L>
<L N="998">ffor which &thorn;e senatour as was &thorn;e vsage</L>
<L>Rod hym a-geyn as was &thorn;e vsage</L>
<L>As wel to schewyn his magnificence</L>
<L N="1001">As to don any kyng a reuerence</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Gret cher doth &thorn;is noble senatour<MILESTONE N="208b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>To kyng alla &amp; he to hym also</L>
<L>Euerych of hem do&thorn; o&thorn;er gret honour</L>
<L N="1005">An[d] that with-in a day or too
<PB REF="00000178.tif" N="162"></L>
<L>This senatour is to kyng Alla go</L>
<L>To feste &amp; schortly &yogh;if I schal not lye</L>
<L N="1008">Custauncis sone wente in his cumpanye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Summen wolde seyn at &thorn;e request of Custaunce</L>
<L>This senatour hath lad &thorn;is child to feste</L>
<L>I ne may not tellyn euery circumstaunce</L>
<L N="1012">Be as be may &thorn;ere was he at &thorn;e leste</L>
<L>But soth is &thorn;is &thorn;at at his moderys heste</L>
<L>By-forn Alla durynge &thorn;e metis space</L>
<L N="1015">This child stod lokynge in &thorn;e kyngis face</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This Alla kyng hath of &thorn;e child gret wondyr</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e senatour he seyde a-non</L>
<L>Whos is &thorn;at fayre child &thorn;at standis &yogh;ondyr</L>
<L N="1019">I not quod he bi god &amp; bi seynt Iohn</L>
<L>A modyr he hath but fadyr hath he non</L>
<L>That I of wot &amp; schortly in a stounde</L>
<L N="1022">He tolde alla how &thorn;at &thorn;e child was founde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But god wot quod this senatour also</L>
<L>So verteuous a leuere in myn lyue</L>
<L>Ne saw I neuere as sche ne herde of mo</L>
<L N="1026">Of wordely wemen maydyn nor of wif</L>
<L>I dare wel seyn hire hadde leuere a knyf</L>
<L>Thurgh-out hyre brest &thorn;an ben a woman weke</L>
<L N="1029">&thorn;ere is no man coude brynge hire to &thorn;e prikke</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Now was &thorn;is child as lyk on-to custaunce</L>
<L>As possible is a creatour to be</L>
<L>This alla hath &thorn;is face in remembraunce</L>
<L N="1033">Of dame custaunce &amp; &thorn;eron musede he</L>
<L>&YOGH;if &thorn;at &thorn;e childis modyr were ou&yogh;t sche</L>
<L>That is his wyf &amp; pryuyly he sighte</L>
<L N="1036">And sped hym from &thorn;e table &thorn;at he my&yogh;te
<PB REF="00000179.tif" N="163"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Parfay thou&yogh;te he fantome is in myn hed<MILESTONE N="209a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>I oghte deme of ry&yogh;tful iugement</L>
<L>That in &thorn;e salte se myn wif is ded</L>
<L N="1040">And aftyr he made hise argument</L>
<L>What wot I if &thorn;at crist hath hire I-sent</L>
<L>Myn wif be se as wel as he hire sente</L>
<L N="1043">To myn cuntre from &thorn;ens &thorn;at sche wente</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>And aftyr non hom with &thorn;e senatour</L>
<L>Goth alla for to se &thorn;is wondyr chaunce</L>
<L>This senatour doth alla gret honour</L>
<L N="1047">And hastilyche he sente aftyr custaunce</L>
<L>But trustyth wel hire lyste not to daunce</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at sche wiste wherfore was &thorn;at sonde</L>
<L N="1050">One&thorn;e vp-on hire feet sche my&yogh;te stonde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Whan Alla saw his wif fayre he hire grette</L>
<L>And wep &thorn;at it was routhe for to se</L>
<L>ffor at &thorn;e ferste lok he on hyre sette</L>
<L N="1054">He knewe wel verayly &thorn;at it was sche</L>
<L>And sche for sorwe as doumb stant as a tre</L>
<L>So was hire herte set in distresse</L>
<L N="1057">Whan sche remembrede hys vnkyndenesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Twyes sche swounnyth in hise owene syghit</L>
<L>He wepte &amp; hym excuseth pitously</L>
<L>Now god quod he &amp; hise halwis bry&yogh;te</L>
<L N="1061">So wisely on myn soule as haue mercy</L>
<L>That of &yogh;oure harm as gilteles am I</L>
<L>As is Mauryce myn sone so lyk &yogh;oure face</L>
<L N="1064">Ellis &thorn;e fend me feche out of &thorn;is place</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Long was &thorn;e sobyng &amp; &thorn;e bittere peyne</L>
<L>Er &thorn;at hire woful hertis my&yogh;tyn cesse</L>
<L>Gret was &thorn;e pyte for to here hem pleyne</L>
<L N="1068">Thorgh whiche pleyntis gan hire wo encrese
<PB REF="00000180.tif" N="164"></L>
<L>I prey &yogh;ow of myn labour to relese</L>
<L>I may nat telle here wo vn-tyl to morwe</L>
<L N="1071">I am so wery for to speke of sorwe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>But finalli whan &thorn;at &thorn;e sorwe is wist<MILESTONE N="209b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That Alla giltles was of hire wo</L>
<L>I trowe an hunderede tymys ben &thorn;ey kyst</L>
<L N="1075">And swich a blysse is &thorn;ere be-twen hem two</L>
<L>That saue &thorn;e ioye &thorn;at lastyth eueremo</L>
<L>There is non lyk &thorn;at any creature</L>
<L N="1078">Hath seyn or schal whil &thorn;e word wele dure</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Tho preyede sche hire housbonde mekely</L>
<L>In relef of hire longe pitous peyne</L>
<L>That he wolde preye hire fadyr specially</L>
<L N="1082">That of his maieste he wolde enclyne</L>
<L>To vouche-saf sumday with hem to dyne</L>
<L>Sche preyede hym ek he schulde be no weye</L>
<L N="1085">Vn-to hire fadyr no word of hire seye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Summen wolde seyn how &thorn;at &thorn;e child mauryce</L>
<L>Doth &thorn;is message vn-to &thorn;is emperour</L>
<L>But as I gesse alla was not so nyce</L>
<L N="1089">To hym &thorn;at was of so souereyn honour</L>
<L>As he &thorn;at is of cristene folk &thorn;e flour</L>
<L>Sente any child but it is bet to deme</L>
<L N="1092">He wente him selue &amp; so it may wel seme</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This emperour hath grauntid gentyly</L>
<L>To come to dyner as he hym be-sou&yogh;te</L>
<L>And wel rede I he lokede besily</L>
<L N="1096">Vp-on &thorn;is child &amp; on his dou&yogh;tyr thou&yogh;te</L>
<L>Alla goth to hise in and as hym ou&yogh;te</L>
<L>Arayede for &thorn;is feste in euery wyse</L>
<L N="1099">As fer forth as hise kunnynge may suffyse
<PB REF="00000181.tif" N="165"></L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The morwe cam and alla gan hym dresse</L>
<L>And ek his wif &thorn;is emperour to mete</L>
<L>And forth &thorn;ey rede In ioye &amp; in gladnesse</L>
<L N="1103">And whan sche saw hire fadyr in &thorn;e strete</L>
<L>Sche ly&yogh;te a-doun &amp; fallyth hym to feete</L>
<L>ffadyr quod sche &yogh;oure &yogh;onge chyld Custaunce</L>
<L N="1106">Is now ful clene out of &yogh;oure remembraunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>I am &yogh;oure dou&yogh;ty[r] custaunce quod sche<MILESTONE N="210a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>That whilhom han sent vn-to surrye</L>
<L>It am I fadyr &thorn;at in &thorn;e salte se</L>
<L N="1110">Was put a-lone &amp; dampned for to deye</L>
<L>Now goode fadyr mercy I &yogh;ow preye</L>
<L>Sende me no more vn-to to non hethenesse</L>
<L N="1113">But thanke myn lord here of his kyndenesse</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who can &thorn;e pytous ioye tellyn al</L>
<L>By-twexe hem thre syn &thorn;ey ben &thorn;us I-mette</L>
<L>But of myn tale makyn an ende I schal</L>
<L N="1117">The day goth faste I wele no lengere lette</L>
<L>These glade folk to dyner &thorn;ey ben sette</L>
<L>In ioye &amp; blysse at dyner I lete hem dwelle</L>
<L N="1120">A thousent fold more &thorn;an I can telle</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This child Maurice was sythe emperour</L>
<L>Mad bi &thorn;e pope &amp; lyuede cristene lyf</L>
<L>To Cristis cherche he dede gret honour</L>
<L N="1124">But I lete alle hise storyis passyn by</L>
<L>Of Custaunce is myn tale specially</L>
<L>In &thorn;e olde romayn storyis may men fynde</L>
<L N="1127">Maurycis lyf I bere it not in mynde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>This kyng Alla whan he hise tyme say</L>
<L>With his Custaunce his holy wif so swete</L>
<L>To ingelond ben &thorn;ey come &thorn;e ry&yogh;te way</L>
<L N="1131">Where as &thorn;ey lyue In ioye &amp; in quiete
<PB REF="00000182.tif" N="166"></L>
<L>But lytil while it lastyth I &yogh;ow hete</L>
<L>Ioye of &thorn;is world for tyme wele not a-byde</L>
<L N="1134">ffrom day to ny&yogh;t it schaungith as &thorn;e tyde</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Who lyuede euere in swich delyt a day</L>
<L>That sche ne menede outhir concyence</L>
<L>Or yre or talent or sumkenys a-fray</L>
<L N="1138">Enuye or pride or passioun or offence</L>
<L>I ne seye but for &thorn;is ende this sentence</L>
<L>That lytyl while in ioye &amp; in plesaunce</L>
<L N="1141">Lastith &thorn;e ioye of alla with Custaunce</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>ffor deth &thorn;at takyth of high &amp; low hise rente<MILESTONE N="210b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Whan passede was euene a &yogh;er as I gesse</L>
<L>Out of &thorn;e world &thorn;is kyng alla he hente</L>
<L N="1145">ffor whom Custaunce hath ful gret heuinesse</L>
<L>Now let vs preyen god his soule blysse</L>
<L>And dame Custaunce finally to seye</L>
<L N="1148">Toward &thorn;e toun goth hire weye</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>To rome is comyn &thorn;is holy creature</L>
<L>And fyndith hire frendis hole &amp; sounde</L>
<L>Now is sche scapid al hire Auenture</L>
<L N="1152">And whan &thorn;at sche hire fadyr hath I-founde</L>
<L>Doun on hire kneis fallyth sche to grounde</L>
<L>Wepynge for tendirnesse in herte bly&thorn;e</L>
<L N="1155">Sche heryeth god an hundered thousent sythe</L>
</LG>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>In vertu &amp; holy allemesse dede</L>
<L>They lyuyn alle &amp; neuere asundyr wende</L>
<L>Thil deth departyth hem &thorn;is lyf &thorn;ey leede</L>
<L N="1159">And faryth now wel myn tale is at an ende</L>
<L>Now Ihesu crist &thorn;at of his my&yogh;t may sende</L>
<L>Ioye aftyr wo gouerne vs in hise grace</L>
<L N="1162">And kepe vs alle &thorn;at ben in &thorn;is place. Amen</L>
</LG>
</DIV3>
<TRAILER>Here endyth the man of lawe hise tale<NOTE PLACE="end">[Break of 2 lines, after which is the heading of the Wife of Bath's Prologue.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="D" TYPE="group">

<PB REF="00000183.tif" N="167">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="334">
<HEAD>GROUP <B>D.</B> FRAGMENT V.</HEAD>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">
<HEAD>&sect; 1. WIFE OF BATH'S PREAMBLE. CAMBRIDGE MS. [<I>Sloane MS</I> 1685, <I>leaf</I> 103.] &para; The Prologe &para; Of &thorn; Wyf of Bathe<NOTE PLACE="marg">[headline]</NOTE></HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>Experyment/ &thorn;ough none auctoryte</L>
<L>Were in &thorn;is worlde is ri&yogh;t/ ynou&yogh;e for me</L>
<L>To speke of woo &thorn;at ys in mariage</L>
<L N="4">ffor lordynges si&thorn;en I twelfe yere was of age</L>
<L>Thanked by god &thorn;at ys eterne on lyue</L>
<L>Housbondes atte Chirche dore haue I hade fyue</L>
<L>Yf I so ofte my&yogh;t haue wedded be</L>
<L N="8">But alle were wor&thorn;i men in her degre</L>
<L>But me was tolde certayne not longe a-gone ys</L>
<L>&thorn;at sithen cryste ne went nevere but onys</L>
<L>To weddynge in &thorn;e Cane of Galile</L>
<L N="12">&thorn;at be &thorn;ilke ensample tau&yogh;t he me</L>
<L>&thorn;at I ne shulde wedded be but onys</L>
<L>Herke with a sharpe worde with &thorn;e nonys</L>
<L>By syde a welle Ihesu god &amp; man</L>
<L N="16">Spake in reprefe of &thorn;e Samarytan</L>
<L>Thou haste y-hade .v. husbondes quod he</L>
<L>And &thorn;at ilke man &thorn;at nowe hathe the</L>
<L>Ys not &thorn;ine husbonde &thorn;us sayde he certayne</L>
<L N="20">What he mente &thorn;erby I can not sayne</L>
<L>Well but I axe why &thorn;e fyfte man</L>
<L>Was none housbonde to &thorn;e Samarytan</L>
<L N="24">And herde telle in myne age</L>
<L N="23">howe many my&yogh;t she haue in mariage
<PB REF="00000184.tif" N="168"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="335"></L>
<L>Vpon &thorn;is nombre of diffinicion<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sloane MS 1685]</NOTE></L>
<L>Men may deuyne and glose vp and doun</L>
<L>But wele I wote expresse with-out lye</L>
<L N="28">God bad vs wexe and multiplie</L>
<L>&thorn;at gentille text/ can I wele vndirstonde</L>
<L>Eke wele I wote he sayd myn husbonde</L>
<L>Schulde let ffadir and modir and take to me</L>
<L N="32">But of none nombre mencion made he</L>
