<L>In parfyt Ioye &amp; Ihesu crist vs synde</L>
<L>Husbondis meke &yogh;inge &amp; frosche in bedde</L>
<L N="1260">And grace to ouer byde hem &thorn;at we wedde</L>
<L>And ek I preye Ihesu schorte here lyuys</L>
<L>That wele not been gouernyd by here wyuys</L>
<L>And olde &amp; angery nygardys of dispence</L>
<L N="1264">God sende hem sone verray pestelence</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Here endith the Wif of Bathe hyre tale<NOTE PLACE="end">[Gap of one line in the MS.]</NOTE></TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000220.tif" N="204">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="371">
<HEAD>Here begynnyth the prologe of the frerys tale.<MILESTONE N="227b" UNIT="folio"></HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Gap of</I> 6 <I>lines in the MS. Leaf</I> 228 (<I>containing 'prologe', painting, and</I> 22 <I>lines of the tale</I>) <I>has been cut out.</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>[THis worthi<NOTE PLACE="marg">[worthi, a maner, yet, <I>in the margin</I>]</NOTE> lymytour/ this noble ffrere.<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 1758 folio" N="102a"></L>
<L>he made alweie a maner/<NOTE PLACE="marg">[worthi, a maner, yet, <I>in the margin</I>]</NOTE> louryng chere .</L>
<L>vp-on the Sompnour but yet<NOTE PLACE="marg">[worthi, a maner, yet, <I>in the margin</I>]</NOTE> for honeste .</L>
<L N="1268">No vilenous worde as yet spak/ he .</L>
<L>But at the laste he seide vn-to the wif .</L>
<L>Dame gode god yeue you right good lif/ .</L>
<L>Ye han touched here also mote I the .</L>
<L N="1272">In scole mater/ gret/ difficulte .</L>
<L>Ye han seide mochell thyng right well I seie .<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 1758 folio" N="102b"></L>
<L>But dame here as we riden bi the weie .</L>
<L>Vs nedith not to speken but of game .</L>
<L>And late auctorites go<NOTE PLACE="marg">[go <I>in margin</I>]</NOTE> a goddis name .</L>
<L>To prechyng/ &amp; to scole eke of clergie .</L>
<L>But if it like vn-to this companye .</L>
<L>I will you of a somnour telle a game .</L>
<L N="1280">Parde ye may well knowe be the name .</L>
<L>That of no somnour may no gode be saide .</L>
<L>I praye that non of you be euyll a-paide .</L>
<L>A Somnour is a romere vp &amp; doun .</L>
<L N="1284">With maundementis/ of ffornycacioun .</L>
<L>And is bete at euery townes ende .</L>
<L>Our/ oost tho spak a sir/ ye schulde ben hende .</L>
<L>And curteis as man of your/ estate .</L>
<L N="1288">In companye we woll no debate .</L>
<L>Telleth your/ tale &amp; lateth the Somnour be .</L>
<L>Nay quod the Somnour late hym saie<NOTE PLACE="marg">[saie <I>in margin</I>]</NOTE> to me</L>
<L>What so hym list whan it cometh to my lot .</L>
<L N="1292">Bi god I schall hym quyte euery grot .</L>
<L>I schall hym telle whiche a gret honour/ .</L>
<L>It is to be a flateryng lymytour/ .</L>
<L>And eek/ of full manye another/ cryme .</L>
<L N="1296">Whiche nedith not rehersen at this tyme .</L>
<L>And his office I schall hym telle y-wis .</L>
<L>Our/ hoste answerid pees no more of this .</L>
<L>And aftirwarde he seide vn-to the ffrere .</L>
<L N="1300">Tell forth your/ tale my leue maister/ dere .</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Here endith the prolog/.</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000221.tif" N="205">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="372">
<HEAD>and begynneth the tale;;.<NOTE PLACE="marg"><B>Harl. MS 1758</B>, <I>on leaf</I> 102, <I>back</I></NOTE></HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>WHilom ther/ was dwellyng/ in my contre .</L>
<L>An Erchedekene a man of hye degre .</L>
<L>That boldely dide execucioun .</L>
<L N="1304">In ponyschyng of ffornycacioun .</L>
<L>Of wicchecrafte &amp; eek/ of baudrie .</L>
<L>Of diffamacioun &amp; avoutrie .</L>
<L>Of chirche reeues &amp; of testamentis .</L>
<L N="1308">Of contractis &amp; of lak/ of sacramentis .</L>
<L>Of vsure &amp; Symonye also .</L>
<L>But certis lecchours dide he most wo .</L>
<L>Thei schulden syngen if thei were hent .</L>
<L N="1312">And smale tithers weren foule schent .</L>
<L>Yf ony persone wolde vp-on hem pleyne .</L>
<L>Ther/ myght a-sterte hym no pecunyall peyne .</L>
<L>ffor smale tithes &amp; eek/ smale offerynge .</L>
<L N="1316">he made the peple spitously to synge .</L>
<L>ffor or the Bischop caughte hem with his hooke .</L>
<L>Thei weren in the Erchedekenes booke .</L>
<L>And then had he thorow his Iurdiccion .<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 1758 folio" N="103a"></L>
<L N="1320">Power/ to doon on hem correccion .</L>
<L>he had a Sompnour redy to his honde .</L>
<L>A slier/ boie was non in Engelonde .]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<B>Harl.</B> <I>extract ends</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>ffor subtily he hadde hise expyayle<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS Gg. 4. 27</NOTE><MILESTONE N="229a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1324">That tau&yogh;te hym where hym my&yogh;te a-vayle</L>
<L>He coude spare of lechourys on or two</L>
<L>To techyn hym to foure &amp; twenty mo</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ow &thorn;is somenour wood were as an hare</L>
<L N="1328">To telle his harloterye I wele not spare
<PB REF="00000222.tif" N="206"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="373"></L>
<L>ffor we ben out of his coreccioun</L>
<L>They han of vs no Iurediccioun</L>
<L>Ne neuere ne schuln of alle here lyuys</L>
<L N="1332">Petyr so been wemen at &thorn;e styuys</L>
<L>Quod &thorn;e somenour I-put out of oure cure</L>
<L>Pees with myschaunce &amp; with mysauenture</L>
<L>Thus seyde oure ost &amp; lat hym telle his tale</L>
<L N="1336">Now tellith forth &thorn;ow &thorn;at &thorn;e somenour gale</L>
<L>Ne sparyth not myn owene maystyr dere</L>
<L>This false thef &thorn;is somenour quod &thorn;e frere</L>
<L>Hadde alwey baudys redy to his hond</L>
<L N="1340">As ony hauk to lure in ingelond</L>
<L>That tolde hym al &thorn;e secre &thorn;at &thorn;ey knewe</L>
<L>ffor hire aqueyntauns was not comyn of newe</L>
<L>They were hise apprououris pryuyly</L>
<L N="1344">He tok hym self a profyt &thorn;erby</L>
<L>His maystyr knew not alwey what he wan</L>
<L>With-outyn maundement a lewede man</L>
<L>He coude somounne vp peyne of crystis curs</L>
<L N="1348">And &thorn;ey were ful glad to fille his purs</L>
<L>And made hym noble festis at &thorn;e nale</L>
<L>And ry&yogh;t as Iudas hadde purse smale</L>
<L>And was a thef ry&yogh;t swich a thef was he</L>
<L N="1352">Hise mayster hadde but half his duete</L>
<L>He was &yogh;if I schal &yogh;euyn hym hise lawede</L>
<L>A thef &amp; ek a somenour &amp; a baude</L>
<L>He hadde ek wenchis at his retenew</L>
<L N="1356">That whe&thorn;er syre Robert o&thorn;er syre Hewe</L>
<L>Or Iakke or Raf or who so &thorn;at it were</L>
<L>That lay by hem &thorn;ey tolde it in hise ere</L>
<L>Thus was &thorn;e wenche &amp; he at on assent</L>
<L N="1360">And he wolde feche a feynede maundement</L>
<L>And somoune hem to chapitere bo&thorn;e two<MILESTONE N="229b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>And pile &thorn;e man &amp; lete &thorn;e wenche go</L>
<L>Thanne wolde he sey frend I schal for thyn sake</L>
<L N="1364">Don stryke &thorn;e out of oure letteris blake
<PB REF="00000223.tif" N="207"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="374"></L>
<L>The thar no more as in &thorn;is cas trauayle</L>
<L>I am thyn frend &thorn;ere I &thorn;e may a-vayle</L>
<L>Certeyn he knew of bryberyis mo</L>
<L N="1368">Than possible is to telle in &yogh;eris two</L>
<L>ffor in &thorn;is world nys doge for &thorn;e bowe</L>
<L>Than kan an hurt der from an hol knowe</L>
<L>Bet &thorn;an &thorn;e somenour knew a sly lechour</L>
<L N="1372">Or auoutir or a paramour</L>
<L>And for &thorn;at was &thorn;e freut of al his rente</L>
<L>Therfore he sette on it al hyse entente</L>
<L>And so be-fel &thorn;at onys on a day</L>
<L N="1376">This somenour euere waytynge on hyse pray</L>
<L>Wente for to somounne a wedewe an old rybibe</L>
<L>ffeynynge a cause for he wolde brybe</L>
<L>And happede he saw by-fore hym ryde</L>
<L N="1380">A gay &yogh;eman vndir a forest syde</L>
<L>A bowe he bar &amp; arwis bry&yogh;te &amp; kene</L>
<L>He hadde up-on a courtepy of grene</L>
<L>An hat vp-on his hed with frengis blake</L>
<L N="1384">Syre quod &thorn;e somenour wel a-take</L>
<L>Wolcome quod he &amp; euery good felawe</L>
<L>Whe&thorn;er rydistow vndyr &thorn;is grene wode schawe</L>
<L>Seyde &thorn;is &yogh;eman wilt &thorn;ou fer to day</L>
<L N="1388">This somenour answerde &amp; seyde nay</L>
<L>Here faste by is myn entente</L>
<L>To rydyn &amp; to reysyn vp a rente</L>
<L>That longith on to myn lordis duete</L>
<L N="1392">Art &thorn;ou &thorn;anne a baylyf / ye quod he</L>
<L>He durste not for veray fylthe &amp; schame</L>
<L>Seye he was a somenour for &thorn;e name</L>
<L>De-pardeus quod &thorn;is &yogh;eman leue bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="1396">Thou art a balyf &amp; I am a-no&thorn;er</L>
<L>I am onknowyn as in &thorn;is cuntre</L>
<L>Of thyn aqueyntauns I wolde preye &thorn;e</L>
<L>And ek of brotherhode &yogh;if that &yogh;ow leste<MILESTONE N="230a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1400">I haue gold &amp; siluyr in myn cheste
<PB REF="00000224.tif" N="208"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="375"></L>
<L>&yogh;if &thorn;at &yogh;e happyn to comyn in oure schyre</L>
<L>Al schal be ry&yogh;t as &yogh;e wele desyre</L>
<L>Graunt mercy quod &thorn;is somenour be myn fey[th]</L>
<L N="1404">Eueryche in o&thorn;eres hand his trouthe leyth</L>
<L>ffor to ben swore bre&thorn;eryn tyl &thorn;ey deye</L>
<L>In daliaunce &thorn;ey ryde forth &amp; pleye</L>
<L>This somenour &thorn;at was so ful of Iangelys</L>
<L N="1408">As ful of venym ben &thorn;ese variangelys</L>
<L>And euere enquyrynge vp-on euery thyng</L>
<L>Brothir quod he where is &yogh;oure dwellyng</L>
<L>A-no&thorn;er day &yogh;if &thorn;at I schulde &yogh;ow seche</L>
<L N="1412">This &yogh;eman hym answerede in softe speche</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er quod he fer in &thorn;e north cuntre</L>
<L>Where as I hope sumtyme I schal &thorn;e se</L>
<L>Er we departe I schal &thorn;e so wel wische</L>
<L N="1416">That of myn hous ne shalt &thorn;ou neuere mysse</L>
<L>Now bro&thorn;er quod &thorn;e somenour I &yogh;ow preye</L>
<L>Teche me whils &thorn;at &yogh;e ryde by &thorn;e weye</L>
<L>Syn &thorn;at &yogh;e be a balyf as am I</L>
<L N="1420">Sum subtilete &amp; telle me feythfully</L>
<L>In myn offys how I may most wynne</L>
<L>And sparyth not for concience ne for synne</L>
<L>But as myn bro&thorn;er telle me how do &yogh;e</L>
<L N="1424">Now by myn trouthe bro&thorn;er dere seyde he</L>
<L>As I schal telle &thorn;e a feythful tale</L>
<L>Mynne wagis been ful streyte &amp; ful smale</L>
<L>Myn lord is hard to me &amp; daungerous</L>
<L N="1428">And myn offys is ful laberous</L>
<L>And &thorn;erfore by extorciounnys I leue</L>
<L>ffor sothe I take al &thorn;at men wele me &yogh;eue</L>
<L>Algate by sley&yogh;te or by violence</L>
<L N="1432">ffrom &yogh;er to &yogh;er I wynne al myn dispence</L>
<L>I can no betere telle feythfully</L>
<L>Now sertis quod &thorn;is somenour so fare I</L>
<L>I spare not to take god it wot</L>
<L N="1436">But &yogh;if it be to heuy or to hoot
<PB REF="00000225.tif" N="209"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="376"></L>
<L>What I may gete in conseyl pryuyly<MILESTONE N="230b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>No manere concience haue I</L>
<L>Nere myn extorcioun I my&yogh;te not lyue</L>
<L N="1440">Ne of sweche Iapis I wele not be schreue</L>
<L>Stomak ne concience knowe I non</L>
<L>I schrewe &thorn;ese schryft faderys euerychon</L>
<L>Wel be we met by god &amp; by seynt Iame</L>
<L N="1444">But leue bro&thorn;er telle me &thorn;anne &thorn;yn name</L>
<L>Quod this somenour &amp; in &thorn;is mene while</L>
<L>This &yogh;eman gan a lytyl for to smyle</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er quod he wilt &thorn;ou &thorn;at I &thorn;e telle</L>
<L N="1448">I am a fend myn dwellyng is in helle</L>
<L>And here I ryde a-boute myn purchasyng</L>
<L>To wete where men wolde &yogh;eue me ony thyng</L>
<L>Myn purchas is &thorn;e effect of al myn rente</L>
<L N="1452">Loke how &thorn;ou rydist for &thorn;e same entente</L>
<L>To wynne good &thorn;ou rekist neuere how</L>
<L>Ryght so fare I for ryde wolde I now</L>
<L>Vnto &thorn;e worldis ende for a preye</L>
<L N="1456">A quod &thorn;e somenour benediste what seye</L>
<L>I wende &yogh;e were a &yogh;eman trewely</L>
<L>&yogh;e haue a manys schap as wel as I</L>
<L>H[a]ue &yogh;e a figure &thorn;anne determynat</L>
<L N="1460">In helle &thorn;ere &yogh;e ben in &yogh;oure estat</L>
<L>Nay serteyn quod he &thorn;ere haue we non</L>
<L>But whan vs lykyth &thorn;anne can we takyn on</L>
<L>Or ell make &yogh;ow seme &thorn;at we been schape</L>
<L N="1464">Sumtyme lyk a man or lyk an ape</L>
<L>Or lyk an aungel can I ryde or go</L>
<L>It is no wondyr thyng thow it be so</L>
<L>A lousy iogelour can deseyue &thorn;e</L>
<L N="1468">And parde &yogh;it can I more craft &thorn;an he</L>
<L>Whi quod &thorn;e somenour ride &yogh;e &thorn;anne or gon</L>
<L>In sundery schap &amp; not alwey in on</L>
<L>ffor we quod he wele vs swich formys make</L>
<L N="1472">As most able is oure prey for to take
<PB REF="00000226.tif" N="210"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="377"></L>
<L>What makyth &yogh;ow to haue al &thorn;is labour</L>
<L>fful manye a cause leue sire Somenour</L>
<L>Seyde &thorn;is fend but alle thynge hath tyme<MILESTONE N="231a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1476">The day is schort / &amp; it is passede pryme</L>
<L>And &yogh;it ne wan I no thyng on this day</L>
<L>I wele entende to wynnyng &yogh;if I may</L>
<L>And noght entende oure wordis to declare</L>
<L N="1480">ffor bro&thorn;er myn thyn wit is al to bare</L>
<L>To vndyrstonde al thow I tolde hem the</L>
<L>But for &thorn;ou axsyst why laboure we</L>
<L>ffor sumtyme we ben goddys instrumentis</L>
<L N="1484">And meeuy[n] for to don hise comaundementis</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at hym lyste vp-on hyse creaturys</L>
<L>In dyuerse art &amp; in dyuerse figurys</L>
<L>With-outyn hym we haue no my&yogh;t certeyn</L>
<L N="1488">&yogh;if &thorn;at him liste stande &thorn;ere ageyn</L>
<L>And sumtyme at oure preyere han we leue</L>
<L>Only &thorn;e body but not &thorn;e soule to greue</L>
<L>[Wytnesse on Iob whom &thorn;at we &middot; did woo</L>
<L>And some tyme haue we my&yogh;t of bothe two<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS 1685 folio" N="122a">]</L>
<L>This is to seyne of soule &amp; body ek</L>
<L>And sumtyme be we sufferede for to sek</L>
<L>Vp-on a man &amp; don his soule onreste</L>
<L N="1496">Noght his body &amp; al is for &thorn;e beste</L>
<L>Whan he withstandith oure temptacioun</L>
<L>It is &thorn;e cause of his sauacioun</L>
<L>Al be it &thorn;at it was not oure entente</L>
<L N="1500">He schulde be saf but &thorn;at we wolde hym hente</L>
<L>And sumtyme be we seruauntys vn-to man</L>
<L>As to &thorn;e Erchebischop seynt Dunstan</L>
<L>And to &thorn;e apostell ek seruauaunt was I</L>
<L N="1504">&yogh;it telle me quod &thorn;e sumnour feythfully</L>
<L>Make &yogh;e &yogh;ow newe bodyis &thorn;us alwey</L>
<L>Of elementis / &thorn;e fend answerde nay</L>
<L>Sumtyme we feyne &amp; sumtyme we areyse</L>
<L N="1508">With deede bodyis in ful sundery wyse
<PB REF="00000227.tif" N="211"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="378"></L>
<L>And speke as renable &amp; fayre &amp; wel</L>
<L>As to &thorn;e Phitonyssa dede Samuel</L>
<L>And &yogh;it wele some men seyn it was nat</L>
<L N="1512">I do no fors of &yogh;oure dyuynyte</L>
<L>But o thyng warne I &thorn;e I wele not iape</L>
<L>Thow wolt algatis wete how we ben schape</L>
<L>Thow schalt here aftyward myn bro&thorn;er dere<MILESTONE N="231b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1516">Come / where &thorn;e nedyth not of me to lere</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou schat by thyn owene experyence</L>
<L>Cunne in a chayer &thorn;anne rede &thorn;is sentence</L>
<L>Bet &thorn;an virgilie whilis he w[as] on lyue</L>
<L N="1520">Or daunt also whils he was on lyue</L>
<L>ffor I wele holde cumpanye with &thorn;e</L>
<L>Til it be so &thorn;at &thorn;ou for-sake me</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;e somenour &thorn;at schal neuere be-tyde</L>
<L N="1524">I am a &yogh;eman knowyn is ful wyde</L>
<L>Myn trouthe wele I holde [to &thorn;e as in &thorn;is caas</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou&yogh;e &thorn;ou were &thorn;e Deuell Sathanas</L>
<L>My trou&thorn;e wolle I holde<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS 1685 folio" N="122b">] myn leue bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="1528">As I am sworn and eche of vs tyl o&thorn;er</L>
<L>ffor to be trewe bro&thorn;er in &thorn;is cas</L>
<L>And bo&thorn;e we gon a-boute oure purchas</L>
<L>Take &thorn;ou &thorn;yn part of &thorn;at men wele &thorn;e &yogh;eue</L>
<L N="1532">And I schal myn &thorn;us may we bo&thorn;e leue</L>
<L>And &yogh;if &thorn;at ony of vs haue more &thorn;an o&thorn;er</L>
<L>Let hym be trowe &amp; parte it with his bro&thorn;er</L>
<L>I graunte quod &thorn;e deuyl be myn fey</L>
<L N="1536">And with &thorn;at word &thorn;ey ryde forth here wey</L>
<L>And ry&yogh;t at &thorn;e enterynge at &thorn;e tounnys ende</L>
<L>To which &thorn;is somenour schop hym for to wende</L>
<L>The[y] saw a carte &thorn;at chargede was with hey</L>
<L N="1540">Which &thorn;at a Cartere drof ferth in &thorn;e wey</L>
<L>Dep was &thorn;e weye for which &thorn;is carte stod</L>
<L>The cartere smot and cryede as he were wood</L>
<L>Hayt sket hayt lyarad hat brok atonys</L>
<L N="1544">The fend quod he &yogh;ow feche body &amp; bonys
<PB REF="00000228.tif" N="212"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="379"></L>
<L>As ferforth as euere were &yogh;e folyd</L>
<L>So meche woo as I haue with &yogh;ow tholyd</L>
<L>The deuyl haue al bo&thorn;e hors &amp; carte &amp; hey</L>
<L N="1548">The somenour seyde here schul we haue a pley</L>
<L>And ner &thorn;e frere he drow as nou&yogh;t ne were</L>
<L>fful priuyly &amp; rounnede in his ere</L>
<L>Herke myn bro&thorn;er herke be thyn feith</L>
<L N="1552">Heryst &thorn;ou nought how &thorn;e cartere seyth</L>
<L>Hende it a-non for he hath &yogh;ouen it &thorn;e</L>
<L>Bo&thorn;e hey &amp; carte &amp; ek his capillis thre</L>
<L>Nay quod &thorn;e deuyl neuere a del<MILESTONE N="232a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1556">It is not his entente troste wel</L>
<L>Axe hym thyn self &yogh;if &thorn;ou not trostiste me</L>
<L>Or ellis stynte a-while &amp; &thorn;ou schat se</L>
<L>This cartere thakkyth hise hors vp-on &thorn;e croupe</L>
<L N="1560">And &thorn;ey be-gunne to drawe &amp; to stoupe</L>
<L>Hayt now quod he now Ihesu cryst &yogh;ow blysse</L>
<L>And al hise hondwerk bo&thorn;e more &amp; lesse</L>
<L>That was wel twy&yogh;t myn owene lyard boy</L>
<L N="1564">I preye god saue &thorn;e body &amp; seynt loy</L>
<L>Now is myn carte out of the slow parde</L>
<L>Lo bro&thorn;er quod &thorn;e fend what tolde I the</L>
<L>Heere may &yogh;e seen myn owene dere bro&thorn;er</L>
<L N="1568">The cherl spak on thyng &amp; mente a-no&thorn;er</L>
<L>Lat vs gon forth a-boutyn oure viage</L>
<L>Here wynne I no good vp-on caryage</L>
<L>Whan &thorn;at &thorn;ey comyn sumwhat out of tounne</L>
<L N="1572">This somenour to his bro&thorn;er gan to rounne</L>
<L>Bro&thorn;er quod he here wonyth an old rebekke</L>
<L>That hadde almost as lef to lese his nekke</L>
<L>As for to &yogh;eue a peny of hire good</L>
<L N="1576">I wele haue twelue penys thow sche be wood</L>
<L>Or I wele somounne hyre to oure offys</L>
<L>And &yogh;it god wot can I no vys</L>
<L>But for &thorn;ou canyst not as in &thorn;is cuntre</L>
<L N="1580">Wynne thyn cost take here ensaumple at me
<PB REF="00000229.tif" N="213"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="380"></L>
<L>This somenour clepith at &thorn;e wedewis gate</L>
<L>Come out quod he &thorn;ou olde verye crate</L>
<L>I trowe &thorn;ou hast sum frere or prest with the</L>
<L N="1584">Ho clepith &thorn;ere seyde &thorn;is widew benedicice</L>
<L>God saue &yogh;ow syre what is &yogh;oure swete wille</L>
<L>I haue quod he of somounnys a bille</L>
<L>Vp peyne of cursynge loke &thorn;at &thorn;ou be</L>
<L N="1588">To morwe by-fore &thorn;e Erchedekenys kne</L>
<L>To answere to &thorn;e court of serteyn thyngis</L>
<L>Now lord quod sche Ihesu kyng of kyngis</L>
<L>So wysely helpe me as I ne may</L>
<L N="1592">I haue be sek &amp; &thorn;at ful manye a day</L>
<L>I may not goon quod sche so fer ne ryde<MILESTONE N="232b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>But I be ded so prykyth it in myn syde</L>
<L>May I not axe a libel syre somenour</L>
<L N="1596">And answere &thorn;ere by myn procatour</L>
<L>To swich thyng as men wele oposyn me</L>
<L>&yogh;is quod this somenour pay a-non lat se</L>
<L>Twelue penys lat se &amp; I wele &thorn;e aquyte</L>
<L N="1600">I schal no profyit haue &thorn;erby but lyte</L>
<L>Myn maystir hath the profit &amp; not I</L>
<L>Come of &amp; let me rydyn hastely</L>
<L>&yogh;eue me twelve penys I may no lengere lette</L>
<L N="1604">Twelue penys quod sche now lady seynte marye</L>
<L>So wysely helpe me out of care &amp; synne</L>
<L>This wyde world &thorn;ow &thorn;at I schulde wynne</L>
<L>Ne haue I not twelue penys with-inne myn holld</L>
<L N="1608">&yogh;e knowe wel &thorn;at I am pore &amp; old</L>
<L>Kythe &yogh;oure almesse on me pore wreche</L>
<L>Nay &thorn;anne quod he &thorn;e fend me feche</L>
<L>&yogh;if I &thorn;e excuse th[o]w &thorn;ow schuldist be spylt</L>
<L N="1612">Allas quod sche god wot I haue no gilt</L>
<L>Pay me quod he or be swete seynt anne</L>
<L>As I wele bere a-wey &thorn;yn newe panne</L>
<L>ffor dette whiche &thorn;ou owist me of old</L>
<L N="1616">Whan &thorn;at &thorn;ou haddist &thorn;yn husbonde coukewold
<PB REF="00000230.tif" N="214"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="381"></L>
<L>I payede at hom for &thorn;yn coreccioun</L>
<L>Thow lyxt quod sche be myn sauacyoun</L>
<L>Ne was I neuere er no wedewe ne wyf</L>
<L N="1620">Somounede on to &yogh;oure court in al myn lyf</L>
<L>Ne neuere I nas but of myn body trewe</L>
<L>Vn-to &thorn;e deuyl blak &amp; row of hewe</L>
<L>&yogh;eue I thyn body &amp; myn panne also</L>
<L N="1624">And whan &thorn;e deuyl herde hire curse so</L>
<L>Vp-on hire kneis sche seyde on &thorn;is manere</L>
<L>Now mabelyn myn owene modir dere</L>
<L>Is &thorn;is &yogh;oure wille in ernest &thorn;at &yogh;e seye</L>
<L N="1628">The deuyl quod sche so feche hym er he deye</L>
<L>And panne &amp; al but he wele hym repente</L>
<L>Nay olde stot &thorn;at is not myn entente<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<B>Gg. 4. 27</B> <I>stops</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>[Quod &thorn;e Somnour for to repent me<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS 1685 folio" N="124a"></L>
<L N="1632">ffor eny &thorn;enge &thorn;at I haue hade of &thorn;e</L>
<L>I wolde I hade &thorn;i smok/ &amp; euery clothe</L>
<L>Nowe Bro&thorn;er/ quod &thorn;e Deuyll be not wrothe</L>
<L>Thy body and &thorn;is panne ys myne by ri&yogh;t</L>
<L N="1636">Thou shalte with me to helle &middot; &yogh;it to ny&yogh;t/</L>
<L>&thorn;ere &thorn;ou shalt/ knowe of/ oure pryuete</L>
<L>More &thorn;an a Maystre of/ Diuinite</L>
<L>And with &thorn;at worde &thorn;e foule fende hym hent</L>
<L N="1640">Body and soule with &thorn;e fende went</L>
<L>Where &thorn;at Somonours haue hir/ herytage</L>
<L>And god &thorn;at made aftyr/ hys Image</L>
<L>Man-kynde saue and gyde vs alle and somme</L>
<L N="1644">And leue &thorn;is Somonour/ gode man by-come/.</L>
<L>Lordynges I coude a tolde you quod &thorn;e frere<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS 1685 folio" N="124b"></L>
<L>Hade I hade leyser/ of thys Somnour here</L>
<L>After/ &thorn;e Tyxt/ Cryst poule &amp; Iohn .</L>
<L N="1648">And of other/ doctours many on .</L>
<L>Suche peynes &thorn;at youre hertes may a-gryse .</L>
<L>Also by hyt &thorn;at no &thorn;enge may deuyse .</L>
<L>Thou &thorn;at I my&yogh;t/ a &thorn;ousand wynter/ telle .</L>
<L N="1652">The peyne of &thorn;ilke Cursed house of helle .
<PB REF="00000231.tif" N="215"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="382"></L>
<L>But for to kepe vs fro &thorn;at cursed place<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Sloane 1685]</NOTE></L>
<L>Wakethe and preithe Ihesu for his grace</L>
<L>To kepe vs . fro &thorn;e Temptour/ Sathanas</L>
<L N="1656">herken &thorn;is worde be ware in &thorn;is caas</L>
<L>The lyonn sit in his wayt alway</L>
<L>To sle &thorn;e Innocent yf &thorn;at he may</L>
<L>Disposethe ay youre hertes to withstonde</L>
<L N="1660">&thorn;e fende &thorn;at you wolde make &thorn;rall and bonde</L>
<L>he may not tempten you ouere your my&yogh;t</L>
<L>And Cryst woll be youre Champioun and your kny&yogh;t</L>
<L>And preythe &thorn;at &thorn;is Sompnour/ hym repent</L>
<L N="1664">Of/ hys mysdede or &thorn;e fende hym hent</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Here endethe &thorn;e ffreres tale</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000232.tif" N="216">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="383">
<HEAD>[Here begynneth the Prolog/ of the Somnour/.</HEAD>
<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Harl. MS</I> 1758, <I>leaf</I> 106, <I>back</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>THis Somnour/ in his stirop hye stood .</L>
<L>Vp-on this ffrere his herte was so wood .</L>
<L>That like an Aspen leef he quoke for yre .</L>
<L N="1668">Lordyngis quod he but oo thyng I desire .</L>
<L>I you beseke that of your/ curtesie .</L>
<L>Sethyns ye han herd this fals ffrere lye .</L>
<L>As suffreth me I maye a tale telle .<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 1758 folio" N="107a"></L>
<L N="1672">This ffrere bosteth that he knoweth helle .</L>
<L>And god woot that it is litell wondir/.</L>
<L>ffreres &amp; fendes ben but litell a sondir/.</L>
<L>ffor parde ye han ofte tyme herd telle .</L>
<L>how that a ffrere rauysched was in <NOTE PLACE="marg">[to <I>is in margin</I>]</NOTE>to helle .</L>
<L>In spirit onys by a visioun .</L>
<L>And as an angell lad hym vp &amp; doun .</L>
<L>To schewyn hym the peynes that ther/ were .</L>
<L N="1680">In all the place sawe he not a ffrere .</L>
<L>Of other/ folke he sawe y-now in woo .</L>
<L>Vn-to this angell spake the ffrere tho .</L>
<L>Now sir/ quod he han ffreres suche grace .</L>
<L N="1684">That non of hem schall come to this place .</L>
<L>Yes quod this angell manye a mylioun .</L>
<L>And vn-to Sathanas he lad hym a-doun .</L>
<L>And now hath Sathanas saith he a taile .</L>
<L N="1688">Bradder/ then of the Carik is the saile .</L>
<L>Holde vp thyn taile Sathanas quod he .</L>
<L>Schewe forth thyne ers &amp; lete the ffrere se .</L>
<L>Where is the neste of ffreres in this place .</L>
<L N="1692">And er/ that half/ a forlong/ wey of space .
<PB REF="00000233.tif" N="217"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="384"></L>
<L>Right so as Bees swermen out of an hyue .<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Harl. 1758]</NOTE></L>
<L>Out/ of the deuylles ers thei gon dryue .</L>
<L>.xx.<SUP>ti</SUP> thousande ffreris on a route .</L>
<L N="1696">And thorow-out helle swarmed all a-boute .</L>
<L>And camen a-yen as fast/ as thei may gone .</L>
<L>And in his ers thei crepedyn euerichone .</L>
<L>He clapt/ his tale a-yen &amp; laye still .</L>
<L N="1700">This ffrere when he lokid had his fill .</L>
<L>Vp-on this tormentis of this sory place .</L>
<L>his spirit god restorid of his grace .</L>
<L>Vn-to his bodye a-yen &amp; he a-woke .</L>
<L N="1704">But natheles for fere yet he quoke .</L>
<L>So was the deuelis ars ay in his mynde .</L>
<L>That is his heritage of verrey kynde .</L>
<L>God saue you alle saue this cursid ffrere .</L>
<L N="1708">Mi Prolog woll I ende in this manere .</L>
</LG>
<TRAILER>Here endith the Prolog/</TRAILER>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 TYPE="tale">

<PB REF="00000234.tif" N="218">
<MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="385">
<HEAD>and begynneth the Tale.</HEAD>

<HEADNOTE><P>[<I>Harl. MS</I> 1758, <I>on leaf</I> 106, <I>back</I>]</P></HEADNOTE>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>LOrdyngis ther/ is in york schire as I gesse.</L>
<L>A merschy contre called holdernesse.</L>
<L>In whiche ther/ wente a lymytour/ a-boute.</L>
<L N="1712">To preche &amp; eek/ to begge it is no doute.</L>
<L>And so bifell that on a daye this ffrere.</L>
<L>had preched at chirche in this manere.</L>
<L>And specially a-bouyn euery thyng.</L>
<L N="1716">Excited he the peple in his prechyng.</L>
<L>To trentalis &amp; to yeue for goddis sake.<MILESTONE UNIT="Harl. 1758 folio" N="107b"></L>
<L>Wher/-with men myghte holi housis/ make.</L>
<L>Ther/ as deuyne seruyse is honoured.</L>
<L N="1720">Nought ther/ as it is wasted &amp; deuoured.</L>
<L>Ne there it nedith not for to be yeue.</L>
<L>As to possessioners that may ellis lyue.</L>
<L>Thanked <NOTE PLACE="marg">[h, <I>with the tail scratcht out</I>]</NOTE>be god in wele &amp; habundaunce.</L>
<L N="1724">Trentales seide he delyuerith fro penaunce.</L>
<L>Here frendes soules as well olde as yong.</L>
<L>Yef that thei ben hastely song.</L>
<L>Nought for to holde a preest ioly &amp; gay.</L>
<L N="1728">he syngeth not but oo messe in a day.</L>
<L>Delyuerith out/ a man quod he the soulis.</L>
<L>ffull hard it is with fleschehoke or with oulis.</L>
<L N="1732">Now spede you hastely for cristes sake.</L>
<L N="1731">To kepe you fro peynes of fendis blake.</L>
<L>And whan the ffrere had seide alle his entente.</L>
<L>With Qui cum patre forth he wente.</L>
<L>When folke in chirche had yeue hym what hem lest.</L>
<L N="1736">he wente his way no lenger/ wolde he rest.
<PB REF="00000235.tif" N="219"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="386"></L>
<L>With scrippe &amp; tipped staf tucked full hye.<NOTE PLACE="marg">[Harl. 1758]</NOTE></L>
<L>In euery hous he gan to pore &amp; prye.</L>
<L>And beggeth mele or chese or ellis corn.</L>
<L N="1740">his felalawe had a staf tipped with horn.</L>
<L>A peire of/ tablis of yuory.</L>
<L>And a poyntell polched fetisly.</L>
<L>And wrot/ alweye the names there he stood.</L>
<L N="1744">Of alle folke that yaf hym any good.</L>
<L>As-caunce as he wolde for hem preie.</L>
<L>Yeue vs a buschell whete malt/ or reie.]<NOTE PLACE="marg">[<B>Harl.</B> <I>extract ends</I>]</NOTE></L>
<L>A godis kechil or a trip of chese<NOTE PLACE="marg">MS Gg. 4. 27</NOTE><MILESTONE N="235a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1748">Or ellis what &yogh;ow lyste we may not chese</L>
<L>A godis halpeny or a masse pany</L>
<L>Or &yogh;eue vs of &yogh;oure braun &yogh;if &yogh;e han any</L>
<L>A dagoun of &yogh;oure blanket leue dame</L>
<L N="1752">Oure sistyr dere lo here I wryte &yogh;oure name</L>
<L>Bacoun or bef or swich &thorn;yng as &yogh;e fynde</L>
<L>A sturdy harlot wente hem ay by-hynde</L>
<L>That was here ostys man &amp; bar a sak</L>
<L N="1756">And what men &yogh;oue hem leyde it on his bak</L>
<L>And whan he was out at &thorn;e dore a-non</L>
<L>He planede a-wey &thorn;e namys euerychon</L>
<L>That he be-fore hadde wrytyn in hyse tablis</L>
<L N="1760">He servede hem with nyflys &amp; wyth fablys</L>
<L>Nay &thorn;ere &thorn;ou lext &thorn;ou somenour quod &thorn;e frere</L>
<L>Pes quod oure ost for cristis modyr dere</L>
<L>Telle forth &yogh;oure tale &amp; spare it not at al</L>
<L N="1764">So thryue I quod the somenour so I schal</L>
<L>So longe he wente hous be hous tyl he</L>
<L>Cam to an hous &thorn;ere he was wone to be</L>
<L>Refresched more &thorn;an in an hunderede placis</L>
<L N="1768">Sek lay &thorn;e goode man whos &thorn;e place is</L>
<L>Bedrede vp-on a couche lowe he lay</L>
<L>Deus hic quod he O tomays frend good day</L>
<L>Seyde &thorn;is frere curteysly &amp; softe</L>
<L N="1772">Thomas quod he god &yogh;elde &yogh;ow ful ofte
<PB REF="00000236.tif" N="220"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="387"></L>
<L>Haue I vp-on &thorn;is benche fare ful wel</L>
<L>Here haue I ete ful manye a murye mel</L>
<L>And fro &thorn;e bench he drof awoy &thorn;e cat</L>
<L N="1776">And leyde a-doun his potente &amp; his hat</L>
<L>And ek his scryppe &amp; sette hym softe adoun</L>
<L>His felawe was go walkede in &thorn;e toun</L>
<L>fforth with his knawe vn-to &thorn;at ostelrye</L>
<L N="1780">Where as he schop hym &thorn;e ilke ny&yogh;t to lye</L>
<L>O dere maystir quod &thorn;is syke man</L>
<L>How haue &yogh;e fare sythe &thorn;at March be-gan</L>
<L>I saw &yogh;ow not &thorn;is fourteny&yogh;t or more</L>
<L N="1784">God wot quod he laboured haue I ful sore</L>
<L>And sp[e]cially for thyn saluacioun<MILESTONE N="235b" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L>Haue I seyd manye a precious orisoun</L>
<L>And for oure o&thorn;ere frendis god hem blysse</L>
<L N="1788">I haue to day been at &yogh;oure cherche at messe</L>
<L>And seyd a sarmoun aftyr myn symple wit</L>
<L>Nat al aftyr &thorn;e text of holy wret</L>
<L>ffor it is hard to &yogh;ow as I suppose</L>
<L N="1792">And &thorn;erfore wele I telle &yogh;ow al &thorn;e glose</L>
<L>Glosyng is a glorious thyng serteyn</L>
<L>ffor lettere sleth as we clerkis seyn</L>
<L>There haue I tau&yogh;t hem to be charytable</L>
<L N="1796">And spende here good &thorn;ere it is resonable</L>
<L>And &thorn;ere I saw oure dame a where is sche</L>
<L>&YOGH;ond in &thorn;e &yogh;erd I trowe &thorn;at sche be</L>
<L>Seyde &thorn;is man &amp; sche wele come a-non</L>
<L N="1800">Ey maystir wolcome be &yogh;e by seynt Iohn</L>
<L>Seyde &thorn;is wif how fare &yogh;e hertely</L>
<L>This frere arysith vp ful curteysly</L>
<L>And hire enbraseth in hise armys narwe</L>
<L N="1804">And kysseth hire swete / &amp; chirketh as a sparwe</L>
<L>With his lippis dame quod he ry&yogh;t wel</L>
<L>As he &thorn;at is &yogh;oure seruaunt euerydel</L>
<L>Thankede be god &thorn;at &yogh;ow &yogh;af soule &amp; lyf</L>
<L N="1808">&yogh;it saw I not &thorn;is day so fayr a wyf
<PB REF="00000237.tif" N="221"><MILESTONE UNIT="6-text p" N="388"></L>
<L>In al &thorn;e cherche god so saue me</L>
<L>&yogh;a god amende &thorn;e fautis sere quod sche</L>
<L>Algatis wolcome &yogh;e by myn fey</L>
<L N="1812">Graunt merci dame &thorn;is haue I founde alwey</L>
<L>But of &yogh;oure grete goodnesse by &yogh;oure leue</L>
<L>I wolde preye &yogh;ow &thorn;at &yogh;e nat &yogh;ow greve</L>
<L>I wele with Thomas speke a lytyl throwe</L>
<L N="1816">These curatis been ful neglygent &amp; slowe</L>
<L>To grope tenderely a concience</L>
<L>In schrifte in prechynge is myn diligence</L>
<L>And stodie in peteris wordis &amp; in Poulis</L>
<L N="1820">I walke to fyche cristene menys soulys</L>
<L>To &yogh;ilde Ihesu crist / hise propere rente</L>
<L>To sprede his word is set al myn entente</L>
<L>Now by &yogh;oure leue o deere maystyr quod sche<MILESTONE N="236a" UNIT="folio"></L>
<L N="1824">Schidith hym wel for seynte trynyte</L>
<L>He is as angery as a pissemyre</L>
<L>Thow that he haue al &thorn;at he can desyre</L>
<L>Thow I hym wrye a ny&yogh;t &amp; make hym warm</L>
<L N="1828">And ouer hym leye myn leg o&thorn;er myn arm</L>
<L>He gronyth lik oure bor lyth in oure sty</L>
<L>O&thorn;er disport ry&yogh;t non of hym haue I</L>
