<DIV3 TYPE="part">
<HEAD>[Tale.]</HEAD>
<LG TYPE="stanza">
<L>The tale of &yogh;ong Gamelyn</L>
<L N="1">Erthen and listeneth and herkenyth a right</L>
<L>And shul here of a doughty knyght</L>
<L>Sir Iohan de Boundys was his name</L>
<L N="4">He coude of norture and of mochel game</L>
<L>Thre sones &thorn;e knyght had and with his body hem wan</L>
<L>The eldest was a moche schrewe and sone he be-gan</L>
<L>His brethren loued wel her fader and of hym were a-gast</L>
<L N="8">The eldist disserued his fader curs and had it at &thorn;e last</L>
<L>The gode knyght his fader lyued so &yogh;ore</L>
<L>That deth was comen hym to. and handelid him ful sore</L>
<L>The gode knyght cared sore. sike &thorn;ere he lay</L>
<L N="12">How his children shuld lyuen after his day</L>
<L>He had ben wide where but non husbond he was</L>
<L>Al &thorn;e londe &thorn;at he had hit was purchas</L>
<L>ffayn he wold hit were dressed a-mong hem alle</L>
<L N="16">That eche of hem hadde his part as it myght falle</L>
<L>Tho sente he in to cuntre after wise knyghtes</L>
<L>To helpen delen his londes and dressen hem to rightes</L>
<L>He sent hem. word by lettres &thorn;ai shuld hye blyue</L>
<L N="20">&YOGH;if &thorn;ei wold speke with him while he was on lyue
<PB REF="00000700.tif" N="2"></L>
<L>Tho &thorn;e knyghtes. herden. sike &thorn;at he lay</L>
<L>Had &thorn;ey no rest nothir nyght ne day</L>
<L>Til &thorn;ey come to him &thorn;ere he lay stille</L>
<L N="24">On his deth bed to a-bide goddes wille.</L>
<L>Then seyde &thorn;e goode knyght sike &thorn;ere he lay<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS. 1685 folio" N="52a"></L>
<L>Lordes I &yogh;ou warne for so&thorn;e with-oute nay</L>
<L>I may no lenger lyuen here in &thorn;is stonde</L>
<L N="28">ffor thorugh goddes wille deth drawes to gronde</L>
<L>Ther nas non of hem alle &thorn;at herde hem a right</L>
<L>That &thorn;ey hadden reuthe of &thorn;at ilke knyght</L>
<L>And seiden sir for goddes loue ne dismay &yogh;ou nou&yogh;t</L>
<L N="32">God may done bote of bale &thorn;at is now I-wrou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Than spake &thorn;e gode knyght sike &thorn;ere he lay</L>
<L>Bote of bale god may sende I wote it is not nay</L>
<L>But I beseche &yogh;ou knyghtes for &thorn;e loue of me</L>
<L N="36">Goth and dresseth my londes a-mong my sones thre</L>
<L>And for &thorn;e loue of god delith not hem amys</L>
<L>And for-&yogh;ete&thorn; not Gamelyn my &yogh;ong sone &thorn;at is</L>
<L>Taketh hede to &thorn;at one as wel as to &thorn;at o&thorn;er</L>
<L N="40">Selde &yogh;e seen any heire helpen his brother</L>
<L>Tho leten &thorn;ey &thorn;e knyght lyen &thorn;at was not in hele</L>
<L>And wenten in to counseil his londis for to dele</L>
<L>ffor to delen hem alle to oon &thorn;at was her &thorn;oght</L>
<L N="44">And for Gamelyn wast &yogh;ongest he shuld haue nou&yogh;t</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;e lond &thorn;at &thorn;er was &thorn;ei dalten it in two</L>
<L>And leten Gamelyn &thorn;e &yogh;ong with-outen lond go</L>
<L>And eche of hem saide to other ful lowde</L>
<L N="48">His brethren myght &yogh;eue hym lond when he good cowde</L>
<L>When &thorn;ey had deled at her wille</L>
<L>They comen to &thorn;e knyght &thorn;er he ley stille</L>
<L>And tolde hym a-non how &thorn;ei had wrought</L>
<L N="52">And &thorn;e knyght ther he lay likid it right nought</L>
<L>Than seyde &thorn;e knyght by seynt martyn</L>
<L>ffor al &thorn;at &yogh;e haue don &yogh;et is &thorn;e lond myn</L>
<L>ffor go goddes loue Neigboures stondith al stille</L>
<L N="56">And I wil delen my lond right after my wille
<PB REF="00000701.tif" N="3"></L>
<L>Iohn my eldest sone shal haue plowes fyue</L>
<L>That was my fadres heritage while he was on lyue</L>
<L>And my mydlest sone fyue plowes of lond</L>
<L N="60">That I halp for to gete with my right hond</L>
<L>And al myn o&thorn;er purchas of londes and ledes<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS. 1685 folio" N="52b"></L>
<L>That I be-quee&thorn;e Gamelyn and alle my gode stedes</L>
<L>And I beseke &yogh;ou good men &thorn;at law con of lond</L>
<L N="64">ffor Gamelyns loue &thorn;at my quest stond</L>
<L>Thus dalt &thorn;e knyght his lond by his day</L>
<L>Right on his deth bed sike &thorn;ere he lay</L>
<L>And sone aftirward he lay stoon stille</L>
<L N="68">And died whan tyme come as it was cristes wille</L>
<L>A-none as he was deed and vnder gras graue</L>
<L>Sone &thorn;e elder bro&thorn;er gyled &thorn;e &yogh;ong knaue</L>
<L>He toke in to his honde and his lede</L>
<L N="72">And Gamelyn him selfe to clothen and to fede</L>
<L>He clo&thorn;ed hym and fedde hym yuel and eke wrothe</L>
<L>And lete him his londes for-fare and his houses bo&thorn;e</L>
<L>His parkes and his wodes and dide no&thorn;yng welle</L>
<L N="76">And sithen he it a-bow&yogh;t on his owne felle</L>
<L>So longe was Gamelyn in his brothers halle</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;e strengest of good wille &thorn;ei doutenden alle</L>
<L>Ther was none &thorn;ere in. no&thorn;er &yogh;ong ne old</L>
<L N="80">That wold wrath Gamelyn where he neuer so bold</L>
<L>Gamelyn stode on a day in his brothers &yogh;erde</L>
<L>And by-gan with his hand to hondel his berde</L>
<L>He &thorn;ou&yogh;t on his landes &thorn;at lay on-sawe</L>
<L N="84">And his faire okes &thorn;at doune were I-drawe</L>
<L>His parkes were broken and his dere reved</L>
<L>Of alle his good stedes noon was him by-leued</L>
<L>His houses were vn-hiled and ful euel dight</L>
<L N="88">Tho &thorn;ou&yogh;t Gamelyn it went not a right</L>
<L>Aftirward came his brother walkyng &thorn;ere</L>
<L>And seide to Gamelyn is oure mete &yogh;ere</L>
<L>Tho wrathed him Gamelyn and swore by goodes booke</L>
<L N="92">Thou shalt go bake &thorn;y self I wilnot be &thorn;i cooke
<PB REF="00000702.tif" N="4"></L>
<L>Now bro&thorn;er Gamelyn hou vnswarest &thorn;ou now</L>
<L>Thou spakkest neuer suche a word as &thorn;ou dost now</L>
<L>By my feythe seide Gamelyn now me &thorn;ynkith nede</L>
<L N="96">Of alle &thorn;e armes &thorn;at I haue I toke neuer &yogh;et hede</L>
<L>My parkes ben broken and my dere by-reved<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS. 1685 folio" N="53a"></L>
<L>Of myn armes and my stedes noght is me byleued</L>
<L>Al &thorn;at my fader me qua&thorn; al goth to schame</L>
<L N="100">And &thorn;erfore haue goddes curs bro&thorn;er by &thorn;yn name</L>
<L>Than spak his brother &thorn;at rape was of rees</L>
<L>Stand stille gadlyng and hold &thorn;y pees</L>
<L>Thou shalt fayne to haue &thorn;y mete and &thorn;y wede</L>
<L N="104">What spekest &thorn;ou gadlyng of lond or of lede</L>
<L>Than seide Gamelyn &thorn;e child &thorn;at was &yogh;yng</L>
<L>Cristes curs mote he haue &thorn;at clepith me gadlyng</L>
<L>I am no worse gadlyng ne no worse wight</L>
<L N="108">But borne of a lady and geten of a knyght</L>
<L>Ne dirst he note to Gamelyn neuer a fote go</L>
<L>But clepid to him his men and saide to hem &thorn;o</L>
<L>Goth and bethet &thorn;is boy and reueth him his witte</L>
<L N="112">And lette hym lerne an o&thorn;er tyme to vnsware me bette</L>
<L>Then seide &thorn;e child &yogh;ong Gamelyn</L>
<L>Cristes curs mote &thorn;ou haue brother art &thorn;ou myn</L>
<L>And &yogh;if y shal algate be beten a-noon</L>
<L N="116">Cristes curs mote &thorn;ou haue but &thorn;ou be &thorn;at oon</L>
<L>An-noon his brother in &thorn;at grete hete</L>
<L>Made his men to fette staffes Gamelyn to bete</L>
<L>When euery of hem hed a staffe nomen</L>
<L N="120">Gamelyn was ware tho he seigh hem comen</L>
<L>Tho Gamelyn seigh hem comen he lokid ouer all</L>
<L>And was war of a pestel stood vnder &thorn;e wall</L>
<L>Gamelyn was light and &thorn;ider he can lepe</L>
<L N="124">And droff alle his brothers men right sone on hepe</L>
<L>And lokid as a wild lyon and layde on gode wone</L>
<L>Tho his brother sei &thorn;at he by-gan to gone</L>
<L>He fley vp in to a loft and shete &thorn;e dore fast</L>
<L N="128">Thus Gamelyn with his pestel made hem alle a-gast
<PB REF="00000703.tif" N="5"></L>
<L>Some for Gamelyns loue and some for eye</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;ey drowen hem to halues &thorn;oo he gan to flee</L>
<L>What now seide Gamelyn euel mote &yogh;e &thorn;e</L>
<L N="132">Wille &yogh;e by-gynne contyk and so sone flee</L>
<L>Gamelyn sou&yogh;t his brother whider he was flow<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS. 1685 folio" N="53b"></L>
<L>And saughe where he lokid oute of a wyndow</L>
<L>Brother seyde Gamelyn come a litul nere</L>
<L N="136">And I wille teche the a play at the bokeler</L>
<L>His brother him vnswarid and seide by seynt Richere</L>
<L>While &thorn;at pestel is in thi hond I wole come no nere</L>
<L>Brother I wil make thi pees I swere by cr[i]stes ore</L>
<L N="140">Cast a-way &thorn;e pestel and wrath the no more</L>
<L>I moste nede saide Gamelyn wrath me at ones</L>
<L>ffor &thorn;ou wold make &thorn;y men to breke my bones</L>
<L>Ne hadde I hadde mayn and myght in myn armes</L>
<L N="144">To haue hem fro me thei wold haue do de harmes</L>
<L>Gamelyn saide his brother be &thorn;ou not wroth</L>
<L>ffor to seen the haue harme me were right loth</L>
<L>I ne dede it nou&yogh;t brother but for a fondyng</L>
<L N="148">ffor to loken or &thorn;ou art strong and art so &yogh;yng</L>
<L>Come a doune &thorn;en to me and graunt me my bone</L>
<L>Of o &thorn;yng I wil &thorn;e axe and we shul saught sone</L>
<L>Downe &thorn;an come his brother &thorn;at fekil was and felle</L>
<L N="152">And was swich sore a-ferd of the pestell</L>
<L>He seide brother Gamelyn axe me &thorn;y bone</L>
<L>And loke &thorn;ou blame but I it graunt sone</L>
<L>Than seide Gamelyn brother I was</L>
<L N="156">And we shull be at one &thorn;ou most graunt me &thorn;is</L>
<L>Alle &thorn;at my fader me by-qua&thorn; while &thorn;at he was on lyue</L>
<L>Thou moust do me it haue &yogh;if we shul not stryve</L>
<L>That shalt &thorn;ou haue Gamelyn I swere by cristes ore</L>
<L N="160">Alle &thorn;at fader &thorn;e be-qua&thorn; &thorn;ough &thorn;ou woldest haue more</L>
<L>Thi lond &thorn;at lith leye. wel it shal be sowe</L>
<L>And &thorn;yn houses reised vp &thorn;at ben leide ful lowe</L>
<L>Thus seide &thorn;e knyght to Gamelyn with mouth</L>
<L N="164">And &thorn;ou&yogh;t on falsenes as he wel couth
<PB REF="00000704.tif" N="6"></L>
<L>The knyght &thorn;ought on treson an Gamelyn on none</L>
<L>And went and kissed his brother and whenne &thorn;ey weren atone</L>
<L>Allas &yogh;ong Gamelyn no &thorn;yng he ne wiste</L>
<L N="168">With suche fals treson his brother hym kyste</L>
<L>Lyithenyth and lystnyth and holdith &yogh;oure tong<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS. 1685 folio" N="54a"></L>
<L>And &yogh;e shul here talkyng of Gamelyn &thorn;e &yogh;ong</L>
<L>Ther was ther be siden. cried a wrastlyng</L>
<L N="172">And ther for ther was sette a Ram and a ryng</L>
<L>And Gamelyn was in wille to wende &thorn;er to</L>
<L>ffor to preuen his myght what he coude do</L>
<L>Brother seid Gamelyn be seynt Richere</L>
<L N="176">Thou most lene me to nyght a litel coursere</L>
<L>That is fressh to &thorn;e spores on for to ryde</L>
<L>I most on an Erand a litel here by side</L>
<L>Be god seide his bro&thorn;er of stedes in my stalle</L>
<L N="180">Go and chese the best spare non of hem alle</L>
<L>Of stedes and of coursers that stoden hem be side</L>
<L>And telle me gode brother whedir &thorn;ou wilt ride</L>
<L>Here by side brother ys cried a wrastlyng</L>
<L N="184">And &thorn;erfore shal be set a Ram an a ryng</L>
<L>Moche worship it were brother to vs alle</L>
<L>Might &yogh;e the ram and &thorn;e ryng bryngen home to &thorn;is halle</L>
<L>A stede &thorn;er was sadeled smertly and skete</L>
<L N="188">Gamelyn did a paire of spores fast on his fete</L>
<L>He sette his foot in &thorn;e stirop &thorn;e stede he by-strood</L>
<L>And toward &thorn;e wrastlyng &thorn;e yong child rood</L>
<L>Tho Gamelyn &thorn;e yong was riden oute at gate</L>
<L N="192">The fals knyght his brother lokid yit after &thorn;ate</L>
<L>And by-sou&yogh;t ihesu crist &thorn;at is heuen kyng</L>
<L>He myght breke his nekke in &thorn;at wrastlyng</L>
<L>As sone as Gamelyn come &thorn;ere the place was</L>
<L N="196">He light doun of his stede on the gras</L>
<L>And ther he herde a frankeleyn weylaway synge</L>
<L>And bi-gan bitterly his hondes for to wrynge</L>
<L>Gode man saide Gamelyn whi makest &thorn;ou &thorn;is fare</L>
<L N="200">Is ther no man &thorn;at may &yogh;ou helpen oute of care
<PB REF="00000705.tif" N="7"></L>
<L>Allas seide &thorn;is f[r]ankelyn &thorn;at euer y was bore</L>
<L>ffor twey stalworth sones I wene &thorn;at I haue lore</L>
<L N="203">A Champyon is in &thorn;e place &thorn;at ha&thorn; wrou&yogh;t me sorowe</L>
<L>ffor he hath slayn my two sones but &yogh;if god hem borowe</L>
<L>I wel &yogh;eue ten pound by ihesu crist and more<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS. 1685 folio" N="54b"></L>
<L>With &thorn;e nones that I fonde a man to handle hym sore</L>
<L>Gode man seide Gamelyn wilt &thorn;ou wel done</L>
<L N="208">Hold my hors while my man drawith of my shone</L>
<L>And helpe my man to kepe my clothes and my stede</L>
<L>And I wil in to place gone to loke if y may spede</L>
<L>By god seyde the frankeleyn it shal be done</L>
<L>I wille my self be &thorn;y mane<NOTE PLACE="marg">[MS name]</NOTE> to draw of &thorn;y shone</L>
<L>And wende &thorn;ou in to place ihesu crist the spede</L>
<L>And drede not of thi clothes ne of thi gode stede</L>
<L>Barfoot and vngirt Gamelyn In came</L>
<L N="216">Alle &thorn;at were in &thorn;e place hede of him &thorn;ei name</L>
<L>How he dorste auntre him to done his myght</L>
<L>That was so doughty a champion in wrastlyng and in fight</L>
<L>Vp sterte &thorn;e Champion rapely a-none</L>
<L N="220">Toward &yogh;ong Gamelyn he by-gan to gone</L>
<L>And seide who is &thorn;y fader and who is &thorn;y sire</L>
<L>ffor so&thorn;e &thorn;ou art a grete foole &thorn;at &thorn;ou come here</L>
<L>Gamelyn vnswarid &thorn;e Champion tho</L>
<L N="224">Thou knew wel my fader while he couthe go</L>
<L>Whilis he was on lyue by seynt Martyn</L>
<L>Sire Iohan of Boundis was his name and I Gamelyn</L>
<L>ffelaw seide the Champion so mote I thryue</L>
<L N="228">I knewe wel the fader whiles he was on lyue</L>
<L>And thi self Gamelyn I wil &thorn;at &thorn;ou it here</L>
<L>While &thorn;ou were a &yogh;ong boy a moche schrew &thorn;ou were</L>
<L>Than saide Gamelyn and swore by cristes ore</L>
<L N="232">Now I am older wax &thorn;ou shal fynde me a more</L>
<L>By god seyde &thorn;e Champion wel come mote &thorn;ou be</L>
<L>Come &thorn;ou ones in myn honde &thorn;ou shalt neuer the</L>
<L>It was wel with-inne nyght and &thorn;e mone shone</L>
<L N="236">When Gamelyn and the Champion to gedre gon gone
<PB REF="00000706.tif" N="8"></L>
<L>The Champion cast tornes to Gamelyn &thorn;at was prest</L>
<L>And Gamelyn stode and bade hym done his best</L>
<L>Than seide Gamelyn to &thorn;e Champion</L>
<L N="240">Thou art fast a-boute to bryng me a-don.</L>
<L>Now I haue proued mony tornes of thyne<MILESTONE UNIT="Sloane MS. 1685 folio" N="55a"></L>
<L>Thow most he seide proue on or two of myne</L>
<L>Gamelyn to the Champion &yogh;ede smertly a-none</L>
<L N="244">Of alle tornes &thorn;at he couthe he shewed hym but one</L>
